01
01Gn 1:1 In the beginning God created the heavens and the earth.
01Gn 1:2 Now the earth was formless and empty, darkness covered the surface of the watery depths, and the Spirit of God was hovering over the surface of the waters.
01Gn 1:3 Then God said, "Let there be light," and there was light.
01Gn 1:4 God saw that the light was good, and God separated the light from the darkness.
01Gn 1:5 God called the light "day," and He called the darkness "night." Evening came, and then morning: the first day.
01Gn 1:6 Then God said, "Let there be an expanse between the waters, separating water from water."
01Gn 1:7 So God made the expanse and separated the water under the expanse from the water above the expanse. And it was so.
01Gn 1:8 God called the expanse "sky." Evening came, and then morning: the second day.
01Gn 1:9 Then God said, "Let the water under the sky be gathered into one place, and let the dry land appear." And it was so.
01Gn 1:10 God called the dry land "earth," and He called the gathering of the water "seas." And God saw that it was good.
01Gn 1:11 Then God said, "Let the earth produce vegetation: seed-bearing plants, and fruit trees on the earth bearing fruit with seed in it, according to their kinds." And it was so.
01Gn 1:12 The earth brought forth vegetation: seed-bearing plants according to their kinds and trees bearing fruit with seed in it, according to their kinds. And God saw that it was good.
01Gn 1:13 Evening came, and then morning: the third day.
01Gn 1:14 Then God said, "Let there be lights in the expanse of the sky to separate the day from the night. They will serve as signs for festivals and for days and years.
01Gn 1:15 They will be lights in the expanse of the sky to provide light on the earth." And it was so.
01Gn 1:16 God made the two great lights-- the greater light to have dominion over the day and the lesser light to have dominion over the night-- as well as the stars.
01Gn 1:17 God placed them in the expanse of the sky to provide light on the earth,
01Gn 1:18 to dominate the day and the night, and to separate light from darkness. And God saw that it was good.
01Gn 1:19 Evening came, and then morning: the fourth day.
01Gn 1:20 Then God said, "Let the water swarm with living creatures, and let birds fly above the earth across the expanse of the sky."
01Gn 1:21 So God created the large sea-creatures and every living creature that moves and swarms in the water, according to their kinds. [He also created] every winged bird according to its kind. And God saw that it was good.
01Gn 1:22 So God blessed them, "Be fruitful, multiply, and fill the waters of the seas, and let the birds multiply on the earth."
01Gn 1:23 Evening came, and then morning: the fifth day.
01Gn 1:24 Then God said, "Let the earth produce living creatures according to their kinds: livestock, creatures that crawl, and the wildlife of the earth according to their kinds." And it was so.
01Gn 1:25 So God made the wildlife of the earth according to their kinds, the livestock according to their kinds, and creatures that crawl on the ground according to their kinds. And God saw that it was good.
01Gn 1:26 Then God said, "Let Us make man in Our image, according to Our likeness. They will rule the fish of the sea, the birds of the sky, the animals, all the earth, and the creatures that crawl on the earth."
01Gn 1:27 So God created man in His own image; He created him in the image of God; He created them male and female.
01Gn 1:28 God blessed them, and God said to them, "Be fruitful, multiply, fill the earth, and subdue it. Rule the fish of the sea, the birds of the sky, and every creature that crawls on the earth."
01Gn 1:29 God also said, "Look, I have given you every seed-bearing plant on the surface of the entire earth, and every tree whose fruit contains seed. This food will be for you,
01Gn 1:30 for all the wildlife of the earth, for every bird of the sky, and for every creature that crawls on the earth-- everything having the breath of life in it. [I have given] every green plant for food." And it was so.
01Gn 1:31 God saw all that He had made, and it was very good. Evening came, and then morning: the sixth day.
01Gn 2:1 So the heavens and the earth and everything in them were completed.
01Gn 2:2 By the seventh day, God completed His work that He had done, and He rested on the seventh day from all His work that He had done.
01Gn 2:3 God blessed the seventh day and declared it holy, for on it He rested from His work of creation.
01Gn 2:4 These are the records of the heavens and the earth, concerning their creation at the time that the LORD God made the earth and the heavens.
01Gn 2:5 No shrub of the field had yet [grown] on the land, and no plant of the field had yet sprouted, for the LORD God had not made it rain on the land, and there was no man to work the ground.
01Gn 2:6 But water would come out of the ground and water the entire surface of the land.
01Gn 2:7 Then the LORD God formed the man out of the dust from the ground and breathed the breath of life into his nostrils, and the man became a living being.
01Gn 2:8 The LORD God planted a garden in Eden, in the east, and there He placed the man He had formed.
01Gn 2:9 The LORD God caused to grow out of the ground every tree pleasing in appearance and good for food, including the tree of life in the midst of the garden, as well as the tree of the knowledge of good and evil.
01Gn 2:10 A river went out from Eden to water the garden. From there it divided and became the source of four rivers.
01Gn 2:11 The name of the first is Pishon, which encircles the entire land of the Havilah, where there is gold.
01Gn 2:12 Gold from that land is pure; bdellium and onyx are also there.
01Gn 2:13 The name of the second river is Gihon, which encircles the entire land of Cush.
01Gn 2:14 The name of the third river is the Tigris, which flows to the east of Assyria. And the fourth river is the Euphrates.
01Gn 2:15 The LORD God took the man and placed him in the garden of Eden to work it and watch over it.
01Gn 2:16 And the LORD God commanded the man, "You are free to eat from any tree of the garden,
01Gn 2:17 but you must not eat from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil, for on the day you eat from it, you will certainly die."
01Gn 2:18 Then the LORD God said, "It is not good for the man to be alone. I will make a helper who is like him."
01Gn 2:19 So the LORD God formed out of the ground each wild animal and each bird of the sky, and brought each to the man to see what he would call it. And whatever the man called a living creature, that was its name.
01Gn 2:20 The man gave names to all the livestock, to the birds of the sky, and to every wild animal; but for the man no helper was found who was like him.
01Gn 2:21 So the LORD God caused a deep sleep to come over the man, and he slept. God took one of his ribs and closed the flesh at that place.
01Gn 2:22 Then the LORD God made the rib He had taken from the man into a woman and brought her to the man.
01Gn 2:23 And the man said: This one, at last, is bone of my bone, and flesh of my flesh; this one will be called woman, for she was taken from man.
01Gn 2:24 This is why a man leaves his father and mother and bonds with his wife, and they become one flesh.
01Gn 2:25 Both the man and his wife were naked, yet felt no shame.
01Gn 3:1 Now the serpent was the most cunning of all the wild animals that the LORD God had made. He said to the woman, "Did God really say, 'You can't eat from any tree in the garden'?"
01Gn 3:2 The woman said to the serpent, "We may eat the fruit from the trees in the garden.
01Gn 3:3 But about the fruit of the tree in the middle of the garden, God said, 'You must not eat it or touch it, or you will die.'"
01Gn 3:4 "No! You will not die," the serpent said to the woman.
01Gn 3:5 "In fact, God knows that when you eat it your eyes will be opened and you will be like God, knowing good and evil."
01Gn 3:6 Then the woman saw that the tree was good for food and delightful to look at, and that it was desirable for obtaining wisdom. So she took some of its fruit and ate [it]; she also gave [some] to her husband, [who was] with her, and he ate [it].
01Gn 3:7 Then the eyes of both of them were opened, and they knew they were naked; so they sewed fig leaves together and made loincloths for themselves.
01Gn 3:8 Then the man and his wife heard the sound of the LORD God walking in the garden at the time of the evening breeze, and they hid themselves from the LORD God among the trees of the garden.
01Gn 3:9 So the LORD God called out to the man and said to him, "Where are you?"
01Gn 3:10 And he said, "I heard You in the garden, and I was afraid because I was naked, so I hid."
01Gn 3:11 Then He asked, "Who told you that you were naked? Did you eat from the tree that I had commanded you not to eat from?"
01Gn 3:12 Then the man replied, "The woman You gave to be with me-- she gave me [some fruit] from the tree, and I ate."
01Gn 3:13 So the LORD God asked the woman, "What is this you have done?" And the woman said, "It was the serpent. He deceived me, and I ate."
01Gn 3:14 Then the LORD God said to the serpent: Because you have done this, you are cursed more than any livestock and more than any wild animal. You will move on your belly and eat dust all the days of your life.
01Gn 3:15 I will put hostility between you and the woman, and between your seed and her seed. He will strike your head, and you will strike his heel.
01Gn 3:16 He said to the woman: I will intensify your labor pains; you will bear children in anguish. Your desire will be for your husband, yet he will dominate you.
01Gn 3:17 And He said to Adam, "Because you listened to your wife's voice and ate from the tree about which I commanded you, 'Do not eat from it': The ground is cursed because of you. You will eat from it by means of painful labor all the days of your life.
01Gn 3:18 It will produce thorns and thistles for you, and you will eat the plants of the field.
01Gn 3:19 You will eat bread by the sweat of your brow until you return to the ground, since you were taken from it. For you are dust, and you will return to dust."
01Gn 3:20 Adam named his wife Eve because she was the mother of all the living.
01Gn 3:21 The LORD God made clothing out of skins for Adam and his wife, and He clothed them.
01Gn 3:22 The LORD God said, "Since man has become like one of Us, knowing good and evil, he must not reach out, and also take from the tree of life, and eat, and live forever."
01Gn 3:23 So the LORD God sent him away from the garden of Eden to work the ground from which he was taken.
01Gn 3:24 He drove man out, and east of the garden of Eden He stationed cherubim with a flaming, whirling sword to guard the way to the tree of life.
01Gn 4:1 Adam knew his wife Eve intimately, and she conceived and gave birth to Cain. She said, "I have had a male child with the LORD's help."
01Gn 4:2 Then she also gave birth to his brother Abel. Now Abel became a shepherd of a flock, but Cain cultivated the land.
01Gn 4:3 In the course of time Cain presented some of the land's produce as an offering to the LORD.
01Gn 4:4 And Abel also presented [an offering]-- some of the firstborn of his flock and their fat portions. The LORD had regard for Abel and his offering,
01Gn 4:5 but He did not have regard for Cain and his offering. Cain was furious, and he was downcast.
01Gn 4:6 Then the LORD said to Cain, "Why are you furious? And why are you downcast?
01Gn 4:7 If you do right, won't you be accepted? But if you do not do right, sin is crouching at the door. Its desire is for you, but you must master it."
01Gn 4:8 Cain said to his brother Abel, "Let's go out to the field." And while they were in the field, Cain attacked his brother Abel and killed him.
01Gn 4:9 Then the LORD said to Cain, "Where is your brother Abel?" "I don't know," he replied. "Am I my brother's guardian?"
01Gn 4:10 Then He said, "What have you done? Your brother's blood cries out to Me from the ground!
01Gn 4:11 So now you are cursed [with alienation] from the ground that opened its mouth to receive your brother's blood you have shed.
01Gn 4:12 If you work the land, it will never again give you its yield. You will be a restless wanderer on the earth."
01Gn 4:13 But Cain answered the LORD, "My punishment is too great to bear!
01Gn 4:14 Since You are banishing me today from the soil, and I must hide myself from Your presence and become a restless wanderer on the earth, whoever finds me will kill me."
01Gn 4:15 Then the LORD replied to him, "In that case, whoever kills Cain will suffer vengeance seven times over." And He placed a mark on Cain so that whoever found him would not kill him.
01Gn 4:16 Then Cain went out from the LORD's presence and lived in the land of Nod, east of Eden.
01Gn 4:17 Cain knew his wife intimately, and she conceived and gave birth to Enoch. Then Cain became the builder of a city, and he named the city Enoch after his son.
01Gn 4:18 Irad was born to Enoch, Irad fathered Mehujael, Mehujael fathered Methushael, and Methushael fathered Lamech.
01Gn 4:19 Lamech took two wives for himself, one named Adah and the other named Zillah.
01Gn 4:20 Adah bore Jabal; he was the father of the nomadic herdsmen.
01Gn 4:21 His brother was named Jubal; he was the father of all who play the lyre and the flute.
01Gn 4:22 Zillah bore Tubal-cain, who made all kinds of bronze and iron tools. Tubal-cain's sister was Naamah.
01Gn 4:23 Lamech said to his wives: Adah and Zillah, hear my voice; wives of Lamech, pay attention to my words. For I killed a man for wounding me, a boy for striking me.
01Gn 4:24 If Cain is to be avenged seven times over, then for Lamech it will be seventy-seven times!
01Gn 4:25 Adam knew his wife intimately again, and she gave birth to a son and named him Seth, for [she said,] "God has given me another child in place of Abel, since Cain killed him."
01Gn 4:26 A son was born to Seth also, and he named him Enosh. At that time people began to call on the name of the LORD.
01Gn 5:1 These are the family records of the descendants of Adam. On the day that God created man, He made him in the likeness of God;
01Gn 5:2 He created them male and female. When they were created, He blessed them and called them man.
01Gn 5:3 Adam was 130 years old when he fathered [a child] in his likeness, according to his image, and named him Seth.
01Gn 5:4 Adam lived 800 years after the birth of Seth, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:5 So Adam's life lasted 930 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:6 Seth was 105 years old when he fathered Enosh.
01Gn 5:7 Seth lived 807 years after the birth of Enosh, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:8 So Seth's life lasted 912 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:9 Enosh was 90 years old when he fathered Kenan.
01Gn 5:10 Enosh lived 815 years after the birth of Kenan, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:11 So Enosh's life lasted 905 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:12 Kenan was 70 years old when he fathered Mahalalel.
01Gn 5:13 Kenan lived 840 years after the birth of Mahalalel, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:14 So Kenan's life lasted 910 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:15 Mahalalel was 65 years old when he fathered Jared.
01Gn 5:16 Mahalalel lived 830 years after the birth of Jared, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:17 So Mahalalel's life lasted 895 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:18 Jared was 162 years old when he fathered Enoch.
01Gn 5:19 Jared lived 800 years after the birth of Enoch, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:20 So Jared's life lasted 962 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:21 Enoch was 65 years old when he fathered Methuselah.
01Gn 5:22 And after the birth of Methuselah, Enoch walked with God 300 years and fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:23 So Enoch's life lasted 365 years.
01Gn 5:24 Enoch walked with God, and he was not there, because God took him.
01Gn 5:25 Methuselah was 187 years old when he fathered Lamech.
01Gn 5:26 Methuselah lived 782 years after the birth of Lamech, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:27 So Methuselah's life lasted 969 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:28 Lamech was 182 years old when he fathered a son.
01Gn 5:29 And he named him Noah, saying, "This one will bring us relief from the agonizing labor of our hands, caused by the ground the LORD has cursed."
01Gn 5:30 Lamech lived 595 years after Noah's birth, and he fathered sons and daughters.
01Gn 5:31 So Lamech's life lasted 777 years; then he died.
01Gn 5:32 Noah was 500 years old, and he fathered Shem, Ham, and Japheth.
01Gn 6:1 When mankind began to multiply on the earth and daughters were born to them,
01Gn 6:2 the sons of God saw that the daughters of man were beautiful, and they took any they chose as wives for themselves.
01Gn 6:3 And the LORD said, "My Spirit will not remain with mankind forever, because they are corrupt. Their days will be 120 years."
01Gn 6:4 The Nephilim were on the earth both in those days and afterwards, when the sons of God came to the daughters of man, who bore children to them. They were the powerful men of old, the famous men.
01Gn 6:5 When the LORD saw that man's wickedness was widespread on the earth and that every scheme his mind thought of was nothing but evil all the time,
01Gn 6:6 the LORD regretted that He had made man on the earth, and He was grieved in His heart.
01Gn 6:7 Then the LORD said, "I will wipe off the face of the earth: man, whom I created, together with the animals, creatures that crawl, and birds of the sky-- for I regret that I made them."
01Gn 6:8 Noah, however, found favor in the eyes of the LORD.
01Gn 6:9 These are the family records of Noah. Noah was a righteous man, blameless among his contemporaries; Noah walked with God.
01Gn 6:10 And Noah fathered three sons: Shem, Ham, and Japheth.
01Gn 6:11 Now the earth was corrupt in God's sight, and the earth was filled with violence.
01Gn 6:12 God saw how corrupt the earth was, for all flesh had corrupted its way on the earth.
01Gn 6:13 Then God said to Noah, "I have decided to put an end to all flesh, for the earth is filled with violence because of them; therefore I am going to destroy them along with the earth.
01Gn 6:14 "Make yourself an ark of gofer wood. Make rooms in the ark, and cover it with pitch inside and outside.
01Gn 6:15 This is how you are to make it: The ark will be 450 feet long, 75 feet wide, and 45 feet high.
01Gn 6:16 You are to make a roof, finishing [the sides of the ark] to within 18 inches [of the roof.] You are to put a door in the side of the ark. Make it with lower, middle, and upper [decks].
01Gn 6:17 "Understand that I am bringing a deluge-- floodwaters on the earth to destroy all flesh under heaven with the breath of life in it. Everything on earth will die.
01Gn 6:18 But I will establish My covenant with you, and you will enter the ark with your sons, your wife, and your sons' wives.
01Gn 6:19 You are also to bring into the ark two of every living thing of all flesh, male and female, to keep them alive with you.
01Gn 6:20 Two of everything-- from the birds according to their kinds, from the livestock according to their kinds, and from every animal that crawls on the ground according to its kind-- will come to you so that you can keep them alive.
01Gn 6:21 Take with you every kind of food that is eaten; gather it as food for you and for them."
01Gn 6:22 And Noah did this. He did everything that God had commanded him.
01Gn 7:1 Then the LORD said to Noah, "Enter the ark, you and all your household, for I have seen that you [alone] are righteous before Me in this generation.
01Gn 7:2 You are to take with you seven pairs, a male and its female, of all the clean animals, and two of the animals that are not clean, a male and its female,
01Gn 7:3 and seven pairs, male and female, of the birds of the sky-- in order to keep offspring alive on the face of the whole earth.
01Gn 7:4 Seven days from now I will make it rain on the earth 40 days and 40 nights, and I will wipe off the face of the earth every living thing I have made."
01Gn 7:5 And Noah did everything that the LORD commanded him.
01Gn 7:6 Noah was 600 years old when the deluge came [and] water covered the earth.
01Gn 7:7 So Noah, his sons, his wife, and his sons' wives entered the ark because of the waters of the deluge.
01Gn 7:8 From the clean animals, unclean animals, birds, and every creature that crawls on the ground,
01Gn 7:9 two of each, male and female, entered the ark with Noah, just as God had commanded him.
01Gn 7:10 Seven days later the waters of the deluge came on the earth.
01Gn 7:11 In the six hundredth year of Noah's life, in the second month, on the seventeenth day of the month, on that day all the sources of the watery depths burst open, the floodgates of the sky were opened,
01Gn 7:12 and the rain fell on the earth 40 days and 40 nights.
01Gn 7:13 On that same day Noah along with his sons Shem, Ham, and Japheth, Noah's wife, and his three sons' wives entered the ark with him.
01Gn 7:14 They [entered it] with all the wildlife according to their kinds, all livestock according to their kinds, every creature that crawls on the earth according to its kind, all birds, every fowl, and everything with wings according to their kinds.
01Gn 7:15 Two of all flesh that has the breath of life in it entered the ark with Noah.
01Gn 7:16 Those that entered, male and female of all flesh, entered just as God had commanded him. Then the LORD shut him in.
01Gn 7:17 The deluge continued 40 days on the earth; the waters increased and lifted up the ark so that it rose above the earth.
01Gn 7:18 The waters surged and increased greatly on the earth, and the ark floated on the surface of the water.
01Gn 7:19 Then the waters surged even higher on the earth, and all the high mountains under the whole sky were covered.
01Gn 7:20 The mountains were covered as the waters surged [above them] more than 20 feet.
01Gn 7:21 All flesh perished-- creatures that crawl on the earth, birds, livestock, wildlife, and all creatures that swarm on the earth, as well as all mankind.
01Gn 7:22 Everything with the breath of the spirit of life in its nostrils-- everything on dry land died.
01Gn 7:23 He wiped out every living thing that was on the surface of the ground, from mankind to livestock, to creatures that crawl, to the birds of the sky, and they were wiped off the earth. Only Noah was left, and those that were with him in the ark.
01Gn 7:24 And the waters surged on the earth 150 days.
01Gn 8:1 God remembered Noah, as well as all the wildlife and all the livestock that were with him in the ark. God caused a wind to pass over the earth, and the water began to subside.
01Gn 8:2 The sources of the watery depths and the floodgates of the sky were closed, and the rain from the sky stopped.
01Gn 8:3 The water steadily receded from the earth, and by the end of 150 days the waters had decreased significantly.
01Gn 8:4 The ark came to rest in the seventh month, on the seventeenth day of the month, on the mountains of Ararat.
01Gn 8:5 The waters continued to recede until the tenth month; in the tenth month, on the first day of the month, the tops of the mountains were visible.
01Gn 8:6 After 40 days Noah opened the window of the ark that he had made,
01Gn 8:7 and he sent out a raven. It went back and forth until the waters had dried up from the earth.
01Gn 8:8 Then he sent out a dove to see whether the water on the earth's surface had gone down,
01Gn 8:9 but the dove found no resting place for her foot. She returned to him in the ark because water covered the surface of the whole earth. He reached out and brought her into the ark to himself.
01Gn 8:10 So Noah waited seven more days and sent out the dove from the ark again.
01Gn 8:11 When the dove came to him at evening, there was a plucked olive leaf in her beak. So Noah knew that the water on the earth's surface had gone down.
01Gn 8:12 After he had waited another seven days, he sent out the dove, but she did not return to him again.
01Gn 8:13 In the six hundred and first year, in the first month, on the first day of the month, the water [that had covered] the earth was dried up. Then Noah removed the ark's cover and saw that the surface of the ground was drying.
01Gn 8:14 By the twenty-seventh day of the second month, the earth was dry.
01Gn 8:15 Then God spoke to Noah,
01Gn 8:16 "Come out of the ark, you, your wife, your sons, and your sons' wives with you.
01Gn 8:17 Bring out every living thing of all flesh that is with you-- birds, livestock, creatures that crawl on the ground-- and they will spread over the earth and be fruitful and multiply on the earth."
01Gn 8:18 So Noah, along with his sons, his wife, and his sons' wives, came out.
01Gn 8:19 All wildlife, all livestock, every bird, and every creature that crawls on the earth came out of the ark by their groups.
01Gn 8:20 Then Noah built an altar to the LORD. He took some of every kind of clean animal and every kind of clean bird and offered burnt offerings on the altar.
01Gn 8:21 When the LORD smelled the pleasing aroma, He said to Himself, "I will never again curse the ground because of man, even though man's inclination is evil from his youth. And I will never again strike down every living thing as I have done.
01Gn 8:22 As long as the earth endures, seedtime and harvest, cold and heat, summer and winter, and day and night will not cease."
01Gn 9:1 God blessed Noah and his sons and said to them, "Be fruitful and multiply and fill the earth.
01Gn 9:2 The fear and terror of you will be in every living creature on the earth, every bird of the sky, every creature that crawls on the ground, and all the fish of the sea. They are placed under your authority.
01Gn 9:3 Every living creature will be food for you; as [I gave] the green plants, I have given you everything.
01Gn 9:4 However, you must not eat meat with its lifeblood in it.
01Gn 9:5 I will require the life of every animal and every man for your life and your blood. I will require the life of each man's brother for a man's life.
01Gn 9:6 Whoever sheds man's blood, his blood will be shed by man, for God made man in His image.
01Gn 9:7 But you, be fruitful and multiply; spread out over the earth and multiply on it."
01Gn 9:8 Then God said to Noah and his sons with him,
01Gn 9:9 "Understand that I am confirming My covenant with you and your descendants after you,
01Gn 9:10 and with every living creature that is with you-- birds, livestock, and all wildlife of the earth that are with you-- all the animals of the earth that came out of the ark.
01Gn 9:11 I confirm My covenant with you that never again will all flesh be wiped out by the waters of a deluge; there will never again be a deluge to destroy the earth."
01Gn 9:12 And God said, "This is the sign of the covenant I am making between Me and you and every living creature with you, a covenant for all future generations:
01Gn 9:13 I have placed My bow in the clouds, and it will be a sign of the covenant between Me and the earth.
01Gn 9:14 Whenever I form clouds over the earth and the bow appears in the clouds,
01Gn 9:15 I will remember My covenant between Me and you and every living creature of all flesh: water will never again become a deluge to destroy all flesh.
01Gn 9:16 The bow will be in the clouds, and I will look at it and remember the everlasting covenant between God and every living creature of all flesh on earth."
01Gn 9:17 God said to Noah, "This is the sign of the covenant that I have confirmed between Me and all flesh on earth."
01Gn 9:18 Noah's sons who came out of the ark were Shem, Ham, and Japheth. Ham was the father of Canaan.
01Gn 9:19 These three were Noah's sons, and from them the whole earth was populated.
01Gn 9:20 Noah, a man of the soil, was the first to plant a vineyard.
01Gn 9:21 He drank some of the wine, became drunk, and uncovered himself inside his tent.
01Gn 9:22 Ham, the father of Canaan, saw his father naked and told his two brothers outside.
01Gn 9:23 Then Shem and Japheth took a cloak and placed it over both their shoulders, and walking backwards, they covered their father's nakedness. Their faces were turned away, and they did not see their father naked.
01Gn 9:24 When Noah awoke from his drinking and learned what his youngest son had done to him,
01Gn 9:25 he said: Canaan will be cursed. He will be the lowest of slaves to his brothers.
01Gn 9:26 He also said: Praise the LORD, the God of Shem; Canaan will be his slave.
01Gn 9:27 God will extend Japheth; he will dwell in the tents of Shem; Canaan will be his slave.
01Gn 9:28 Now Noah lived 350 years after the flood.
01Gn 9:29 So Noah's life lasted 950 years; then he died.
01Gn 10:1 These are the family records of Noah's sons, Shem, Ham, and Japheth. They also had sons after the deluge.
01Gn 10:2 Japheth's sons: Gomer, Magog, Madai, Javan, Tubal, Meshech, and Tiras.
01Gn 10:3 Gomer's sons: Ashkenaz, Riphath, and Togarmah.
01Gn 10:4 And Javan's sons: Elishah, Tarshish, Kittim, and Dodanim.
01Gn 10:5 The coastland peoples spread out into their lands. These are [Japheth's sons] by their clans, in their nations. Each [group] had its own language.
01Gn 10:6 Ham's sons: Cush, Egypt, Put, and Canaan.
01Gn 10:7 Cush's sons: Seba, Havilah, Sabtah, Raamah, and Sabteca. And Raamah's sons: Sheba and Dedan.
01Gn 10:8 Cush fathered Nimrod, who was the first powerful man on earth.
01Gn 10:9 He was a powerful hunter in the sight of the LORD. That is why it is said, "Like Nimrod, a powerful hunter in the sight of the LORD."
01Gn 10:10 His kingdom started with Babylon, Erech, Accad, and Calneh, in the land of Shinar.
01Gn 10:11 From that land he went to Assyria and built Nineveh, Rehoboth-ir, Calah,
01Gn 10:12 and Resen, between Nineveh and the great city Calah.
01Gn 10:13 Egypt fathered Ludim, Anamim, Lehabim, Naphtuhim,
01Gn 10:14 Pathrusim, Casluhim (the Philistines came from them), and Caphtorim.
01Gn 10:15 Canaan fathered Sidon his firstborn, and the Hittites,
01Gn 10:16 the Jebusites, the Amorites, the Girgashites,
01Gn 10:17 the Hivites, the Arkites, the Sinites,
01Gn 10:18 the Arvadites, the Zemarites, and the Hamathites. Afterwards the Canaanite clans scattered.
01Gn 10:19 The Canaanite border went from Sidon going toward Gerar as far as Gaza, and going toward Sodom, Gomorrah, Admah, and Zeboiim, as far as Lasha.
01Gn 10:20 These are Ham's sons, by their clans, according to their languages, in their own lands and their nations.
01Gn 10:21 And Shem, Japheth's older brother, also had children. Shem was the father of all the children of Eber.
01Gn 10:22 Shem's sons were Elam, Asshur, Arpachshad, Lud, and Aram.
01Gn 10:23 Aram's sons: Uz, Hul, Gether, and Mash.
01Gn 10:24 Arpachshad fathered Shelah, and Shelah fathered Eber.
01Gn 10:25 Eber had two sons. One was named Peleg, for during his days the earth was divided; his brother was named Joktan.
01Gn 10:26 And Joktan fathered Almodad, Sheleph, Hazarmaveth, Jerah,
01Gn 10:27 Hadoram, Uzal, Diklah,
01Gn 10:28 Obal, Abimael, Sheba,
01Gn 10:29 Ophir, Havilah, and Jobab. All these were Joktan's sons.
01Gn 10:30 Their settlements extended from Mesha to Sephar, the eastern hill country.
01Gn 10:31 These are Shem's sons by their clans, according to their languages, in their lands and their nations.
01Gn 10:32 These are the clans of Noah's sons, according to their family records, in their nations. The nations on earth spread out from these after the flood.
01Gn 11:1 At one time the whole earth had the same language and vocabulary.
01Gn 11:2 As people migrated from the east, they found a valley in the land of Shinar and settled there.
01Gn 11:3 They said to each other, "Come, let us make oven-fired bricks." They had brick for stone and asphalt for mortar.
01Gn 11:4 And they said, "Come, let us build ourselves a city and a tower with its top in the sky. Let us make a name for ourselves; otherwise, we will be scattered over the face of the whole earth."
01Gn 11:5 Then the LORD came down to look over the city and the tower that the men were building.
01Gn 11:6 The LORD said, "If, as one people all having the same language, they have begun to do this, then nothing they plan to do will be impossible for them.
01Gn 11:7 Come, let Us go down there and confuse their language so that they will not understand one another's speech."
01Gn 11:8 So the LORD scattered them from there over the face of the whole earth, and they stopped building the city.
01Gn 11:9 Therefore its name is called Babylon, for there the LORD confused the language of the whole earth, and from there the LORD scattered them over the face of the whole earth.
01Gn 11:10 These are the family records of Shem. Shem lived 100 years and fathered Arpachshad two years after the deluge.
01Gn 11:11 After he fathered Arpachshad, Shem lived 500 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:12 Arpachshad lived 35 years and fathered Shelah.
01Gn 11:13 After he fathered Shelah, Arpachshad lived 403 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:14 Shelah lived 30 years and fathered Eber.
01Gn 11:15 After he fathered Eber, Shelah lived 403 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:16 Eber lived 34 years and fathered Peleg.
01Gn 11:17 After he fathered Peleg, Eber lived 430 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:18 Peleg lived 30 years and fathered Reu.
01Gn 11:19 After he fathered Reu, Peleg lived 209 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:20 Reu lived 32 years and fathered Serug.
01Gn 11:21 After he fathered Serug, Reu lived 207 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:22 Serug lived 30 years and fathered Nahor.
01Gn 11:23 After he fathered Nahor, Serug lived 200 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:24 Nahor lived 29 years and fathered Terah.
01Gn 11:25 After he fathered Terah, Nahor lived 119 years and fathered [other] sons and daughters.
01Gn 11:26 Terah lived 70 years and fathered Abram, Nahor, and Haran.
01Gn 11:27 These are the family records of Terah. Terah fathered Abram, Nahor, and Haran, and Haran fathered Lot.
01Gn 11:28 Haran died in his native land, in Ur of the Chaldeans, during his father Terah's lifetime.
01Gn 11:29 Abram and Nahor took wives: Abram's wife was named Sarai, and Nahor's wife was named Milcah. She was the daughter of Haran, the father of both Milcah and Iscah.
01Gn 11:30 Sarai was barren; she had no child.
01Gn 11:31 Terah took his son Abram, his grandson Lot (Haran's son), and his daughter-in-law Sarai, his son Abram's wife, and they set out together from Ur of the Chaldeans to go to the land of Canaan. But when they came to Haran, they settled there.
01Gn 11:32 Terah lived 205 years and died in Haran.
01Gn 12:1 The LORD said to Abram: Go out from your land, your relatives, and your father's house to the land that I will show you.
01Gn 12:2 I will make you into a great nation, I will bless you, I will make your name great, and you will be a blessing.
01Gn 12:3 I will bless those who bless you, I will curse those who treat you with contempt, and all the peoples on earth will be blessed through you.
01Gn 12:4 So Abram went, as the LORD had told him, and Lot went with him. Abram was 75 years old when he left Haran.
01Gn 12:5 He took his wife Sarai, his nephew Lot, all the possessions they had accumulated, and the people he had acquired in Haran, and they set out for the land of Canaan. When they came to the land of Canaan,
01Gn 12:6 Abram passed through the land to the site of Shechem, at the oak of Moreh. At that time the Canaanites were in the land.
01Gn 12:7 But the LORD appeared to Abram and said, "I will give this land to your offspring." So he built an altar there to the LORD who had appeared to him.
01Gn 12:8 From there he moved on to the hill country east of Bethel and pitched his tent, with Bethel on the west and Ai on the east. There he built an altar to the LORD and worshiped Him.
01Gn 12:9 Then Abram journeyed by stages to the Negev.
01Gn 12:10 There was a famine in the land, so Abram went down to Egypt to live there for a while because the famine in the land was severe.
01Gn 12:11 When he was about to enter Egypt, he said to his wife Sarai, "Look, I know what a beautiful woman you are.
01Gn 12:12 When the Egyptians see you, they will say, 'This is his wife.' They will kill me but let you live.
01Gn 12:13 Please say you're my sister so it will go well for me because of you, and my life will be spared on your account."
01Gn 12:14 When Abram entered Egypt, the Egyptians saw that the woman was very beautiful.
01Gn 12:15 Pharaoh's officials saw her and praised her to Pharaoh, so the woman was taken to Pharaoh's house.
01Gn 12:16 He treated Abram well because of her, and Abram acquired flocks and herds, male and female donkeys, male and female slaves, and camels.
01Gn 12:17 But the LORD struck Pharaoh and his house with severe plagues because of Abram's wife Sarai.
01Gn 12:18 So Pharaoh sent for Abram and said, "What have you done to me? Why didn't you tell me she was your wife?
01Gn 12:19 Why did you say, 'She's my sister,' so that I took her as my wife? Now, here's your wife. Take her and go!"
01Gn 12:20 Then Pharaoh gave [his] men orders about him, and they sent him away, with his wife and all he had.
01Gn 13:1 Then Abram went up from Egypt to the Negev-- he, his wife, and all he had, and Lot with him.
01Gn 13:2 Abram was very rich in livestock, silver, and gold.
01Gn 13:3 He went by stages from the Negev to Bethel, to the place between Bethel and Ai where his tent had formerly been,
01Gn 13:4 to the site where he had built the altar. And Abram worshiped the LORD there.
01Gn 13:5 Now Lot, who was traveling with Abram, also had flocks, herds, and tents.
01Gn 13:6 But the land was unable to support them as long as they stayed together, for they had so many possessions that they could not stay together,
01Gn 13:7 and there was quarreling between the herdsmen of Abram's livestock and the herdsmen of Lot's livestock. At that time the Canaanites and the Perizzites were living in the land.
01Gn 13:8 Then Abram said to Lot, "Please, let's not have quarreling between you and me, or between your herdsmen and my herdsmen, since we are relatives.
01Gn 13:9 Isn't the whole land before you? Separate from me: if [you go] to the left, I will go to the right; if [you go] to the right, I will go to the left."
01Gn 13:10 Lot looked out and saw that the entire Jordan Valley as far as Zoar was well-watered everywhere like the LORD's garden and the land of Egypt. This was before God destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah.
01Gn 13:11 So Lot chose the entire Jordan Valley for himself. Then Lot journeyed eastward, and they separated from each other.
01Gn 13:12 Abram lived in the land of Canaan, but Lot lived in the cities of the valley and set up his tent near Sodom.
01Gn 13:13 Now the men of Sodom were evil, sinning greatly against the LORD.
01Gn 13:14 After Lot had separated from him, the LORD said to Abram, "Look from the place where you are. Look north and south, east and west,
01Gn 13:15 for I will give you and your offspring forever all the land that you see.
01Gn 13:16 I will make your offspring like the dust of the earth, so that if one could count the dust of the earth, then your offspring could be counted.
01Gn 13:17 Get up and walk from one end of the land to the other, for I will give it to you."
01Gn 13:18 So Abram moved his tent and went to live beside the oaks of Mamre at Hebron, where he built an altar to the LORD.
01Gn 14:1 In those days Amraphel king of Shinar, Arioch king of Ellasar, Chedorlaomer king of Elam, and Tidal king of Goiim
01Gn 14:2 waged war against Bera king of Sodom, Birsha king of Gomorrah, Shinab king of Admah, and Shemeber king of Zeboiim, as well as the king of Bela (that is, Zoar).
01Gn 14:3 All of these came as allies to the Valley of Siddim (that is, the Dead Sea).
01Gn 14:4 They were subject to Chedorlaomer for 12 years, but in the thirteenth year they rebelled.
01Gn 14:5 In the fourteenth year Chedorlaomer and the kings who were with him came and defeated the Rephaim in Ashteroth-karnaim, the Zuzim in Ham, the Emim in Shaveh-kiriathaim,
01Gn 14:6 and the Horites in the mountains of Seir, as far as El-paran by the wilderness.
01Gn 14:7 Then they came back to invade En-mishpat (that is, Kadesh), and they defeated all the territory of the Amalekites, as well as the Amorites who lived in Hazazon-tamar.
01Gn 14:8 Then the king of Sodom, the king of Gomorrah, the king of Admah, the king of Zeboiim, and the king of Bela (that is, Zoar) went out and lined up for battle in the Valley of Siddim
01Gn 14:9 against Chedorlaomer king of Elam, Tidal king of Goiim, Amraphel king of Shinar, and Arioch king of Ellasar-- four kings against five.
01Gn 14:10 Now the Valley of Siddim contained many asphalt pits, and [as] the kings of Sodom and Gomorrah fled, [some] fell into them, but the rest fled to the mountains.
01Gn 14:11 The [four kings] took all the goods of Sodom and Gomorrah and all their food and went on.
01Gn 14:12 They also took Abram's nephew Lot and his possessions, for he was living in Sodom, and they went on.
01Gn 14:13 One of the survivors came and told Abram the Hebrew, who was at the oaks belonging to Mamre the Amorite, the brother of Eshcol and the brother of Aner. They were bound by a treaty with Abram.
01Gn 14:14 When Abram heard that his relative had been taken prisoner, he assembled his 318 trained men, born in his household, and they went in pursuit as far as Dan.
01Gn 14:15 And he and his servants deployed against them by night, attacked them, and pursued them as far as Hobah to the north of Damascus.
01Gn 14:16 He brought back all the goods and also his relative Lot and his goods, as well as the women and the [other] people.
01Gn 14:17 After Abram returned from defeating Chedorlaomer and the kings who were with him, the king of Sodom went out to meet him in the Valley of Shaveh (that is, the King's Valley).
01Gn 14:18 Then Melchizedek, king of Salem, brought out bread and wine; he was a priest to God Most High.
01Gn 14:19 He blessed him and said: Abram is blessed by God Most High, Creator of heaven and earth,
01Gn 14:20 and give praise to God Most High who has handed over your enemies to you. And Abram gave him a tenth of everything.
01Gn 14:21 Then the king of Sodom said to Abram, "Give me the people, but take the possessions for yourself."
01Gn 14:22 But Abram said to the king of Sodom, "I have raised my hand in an oath to the LORD, God Most High, Creator of heaven and earth,
01Gn 14:23 that I will not take a thread or sandal strap or anything that belongs to you, so you can never say, 'I made Abram rich.'
01Gn 14:24 I will take nothing except what the servants have eaten. But as for the share of the men who came with me-- Aner, Eshcol, and Mamre-- they can take their share."
01Gn 15:1 After these events, the word of the LORD came to Abram in a vision: Do not be afraid, Abram. I am your shield; your reward will be very great.
01Gn 15:2 But Abram said, "Lord God, what can You give me, since I am childless and the heir of my house is Eliezer of Damascus?"
01Gn 15:3 Abram continued, "Look, You have given me no offspring, so a slave born in my house will be my heir."
01Gn 15:4 Now the word of the LORD came to him: "This one will not be your heir; instead, one who comes from your own body will be your heir."
01Gn 15:5 He took him outside and said, "Look at the sky and count the stars, if you are able to count them." Then He said to him, "Your offspring will be that [numerous]."
01Gn 15:6 Abram believed the LORD, and He credited it to him as righteousness.
01Gn 15:7 He also said to him, "I am the LORD who brought you from Ur of the Chaldeans to give you this land to possess."
01Gn 15:8 But he said, "Lord God, how can I know that I will possess it?"
01Gn 15:9 He said to him, "Bring me a three-year-old cow, a three-year-old female goat, a three-year-old ram, a turtledove, and a young pigeon."
01Gn 15:10 So he brought all these to Him, split them down the middle, and laid the pieces opposite each other, but he did not cut up the birds.
01Gn 15:11 Birds of prey came down on the carcasses, but Abram drove them away.
01Gn 15:12 As the sun was setting, a deep sleep fell on Abram, and suddenly a terror and great darkness descended on him.
01Gn 15:13 Then the LORD said to Abram, "Know this for certain: Your offspring will be strangers in a land that does not belong to them; they will be enslaved and oppressed 400 years.
01Gn 15:14 However, I will judge the nation they serve, and afterwards they will go out with many possessions.
01Gn 15:15 But you will go to your fathers in peace and be buried at a ripe old age.
01Gn 15:16 In the fourth generation they will return here, for the iniquity of the Amorites has not yet reached its full measure."
01Gn 15:17 When the sun had set and it was dark, a smoking fire pot and a flaming torch appeared and passed between the divided [animals].
01Gn 15:18 On that day the LORD made a covenant with Abram, saying, "I give this land to your offspring, from the brook of Egypt to the Euphrates River:
01Gn 15:19 [the land of] the Kenites, Kenizzites, Kadmonites,
01Gn 15:20 Hittites, Perizzites, Rephaim,
01Gn 15:21 Amorites, Canaanites, Girgashites, and Jebusites."
01Gn 16:1 Abram's wife Sarai had not borne him children. She owned an Egyptian slave named Hagar.
01Gn 16:2 Sarai said to Abram, "Since the LORD has prevented me from bearing children, go to my slave; perhaps I can have children by her." And Abram agreed to what Sarai said.
01Gn 16:3 So Abram's wife Sarai took Hagar, her Egyptian slave, and gave her to her husband Abram as a wife for him. [This happened] after Abram had lived in the land of Canaan 10 years.
01Gn 16:4 He slept with Hagar, and she became pregnant. When she realized that she was pregnant, she looked down on her mistress.
01Gn 16:5 Then Sarai said to Abram, "You are responsible for my suffering! I put my slave in your arms, and ever since she saw that she was pregnant, she has looked down on me. May the LORD judge between me and you."
01Gn 16:6 Abram replied to Sarai, "Here, your slave is in your hands; do whatever you want with her." Then Sarai mistreated her so much that she ran away from her.
01Gn 16:7 The Angel of the LORD found her by a spring of water in the wilderness, the spring on the way to Shur.
01Gn 16:8 He said, "Hagar, slave of Sarai, where have you come from, and where are you going?" She replied, "I'm running away from my mistress Sarai."
01Gn 16:9 Then the Angel of the LORD said to her, "You must go back to your mistress and submit to her mistreatment."
01Gn 16:10 The Angel of the LORD also said to her, "I will greatly multiply your offspring, and they will be too many to count."
01Gn 16:11 Then the Angel of the LORD said to her: You have conceived and will have a son. You will name him Ishmael, for the LORD has heard your [cry of] affliction.
01Gn 16:12 This man will be [like] a wild ass. His hand will be against everyone, and everyone's hand will be against him; he will live at odds with all his brothers.
01Gn 16:13 So she named the LORD who spoke to her: The God Who Sees, for she said, "Have I really seen here the One who sees me?"
01Gn 16:14 That is why she named the spring, "A Well of the Living One Who Sees Me." It is located between Kadesh and Bered.
01Gn 16:15 So Hagar gave birth to Abram's son, and Abram gave the name Ishmael to the son Hagar had.
01Gn 16:16 Abram was 86 years old when Hagar bore Ishmael to him.
01Gn 17:1 When Abram was 99 years old, the LORD appeared to him, saying, "I am God Almighty. Live in My presence and be devout.
01Gn 17:2 I will establish My covenant between Me and you, and I will multiply you greatly."
01Gn 17:3 Then Abram fell to the ground, and God spoke with him:
01Gn 17:4 "As for Me, My covenant is with you, and you will become the father of many nations.
01Gn 17:5 Your name will no longer be Abram, but your name will be Abraham, for I will make you the father of many nations.
01Gn 17:6 I will make you extremely fruitful and will make nations and kings come from you.
01Gn 17:7 I will keep My covenant between Me and you, and your offspring after you throughout their generations, as an everlasting covenant to be your God and the [God] of your offspring after you.
01Gn 17:8 And to you and your offspring after you I will give the land where you are residing-- all the land of Canaan-- as an eternal possession, and I will be their God."
01Gn 17:9 God also said to Abraham, "As for you, you and your offspring after you throughout their generations are to keep My covenant.
01Gn 17:10 This is My covenant, which you are to keep, between Me and you and your offspring after you: Every one of your males must be circumcised.
01Gn 17:11 You must circumcise the flesh of your foreskin to serve as a sign of the covenant between Me and you.
01Gn 17:12 Throughout your generations, every male among you at eight days old is to be circumcised. This includes a slave born in your house and one purchased with money from any foreigner. The one who is not your offspring,
01Gn 17:13 a slave born in your house, as well as one purchased with money, must be circumcised. My covenant will be in your flesh as an everlasting covenant.
01Gn 17:14 If any male is not circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin, that man will be cut off from his people; he has broken My covenant."
01Gn 17:15 God said to Abraham, "As for your wife Sarai, do not call her Sarai, for Sarah will be her name.
01Gn 17:16 I will bless her; indeed, I will give you a son by her. I will bless her, and she will produce nations; kings of peoples will come from her."
01Gn 17:17 Abraham fell to the ground, laughed, and thought in his heart, "Can a child be born to a hundred-year-old man? Can Sarah, a ninety-year-old woman, give birth?"
01Gn 17:18 So Abraham said to God, "If only Ishmael could live in Your presence!"
01Gn 17:19 But God said, "No. Your wife Sarah will bear you a son, and you will name him Isaac. I will confirm My covenant with him as an everlasting covenant for his offspring after him.
01Gn 17:20 As for Ishmael, I have heard you. I will certainly bless him; I will make him fruitful and will multiply him greatly. He will father 12 tribal leaders, and I will make him into a great nation.
01Gn 17:21 But I will confirm My covenant with Isaac, whom Sarah will bear to you at this time next year."
01Gn 17:22 When He finished talking with him, God withdrew from Abraham.
01Gn 17:23 Then Abraham took his son Ishmael and all the slaves born in his house or purchased with his money-- every male among the members of Abraham's household-- and he circumcised the flesh of their foreskin on that very day, just as God had said to him.
01Gn 17:24 Abraham was 99 years old when the flesh of his foreskin was circumcised,
01Gn 17:25 and his son Ishmael was 13 years old when the flesh of his foreskin was circumcised.
01Gn 17:26 On that same day Abraham and his son Ishmael were circumcised.
01Gn 17:27 And all the men of his household-- both slaves born in his house and those purchased with money from a foreigner-- were circumcised with him.
01Gn 18:1 Then the LORD appeared to Abraham at the oaks of Mamre while he was sitting in the entrance of his tent during the heat of the day.
01Gn 18:2 He looked up, and he saw three men standing near him. When he saw them, he ran from the entrance of the tent to meet them and bowed to the ground.
01Gn 18:3 Then he said, "My lord, if I have found favor in your sight, please do not go on past your servant.
01Gn 18:4 Let a little water be brought, that you may wash your feet and rest yourselves under the tree.
01Gn 18:5 I will bring a bit of bread so that you may strengthen yourselves. This is why you have passed your servant's [way]. Later, you can continue on." "Yes," they replied, "do as you have said."
01Gn 18:6 So Abraham hurried into the tent and said to Sarah, "Quick! Knead three measures of fine flour and make bread."
01Gn 18:7 Meanwhile, Abraham ran to the herd and got a tender, choice calf. He gave it to a young man, who hurried to prepare it.
01Gn 18:8 Then Abraham took curds and milk, and the calf that he had prepared, and set [them] before the men. He served them as they ate under the tree.
01Gn 18:9 "Where is your wife Sarah?" they asked him. "There, in the tent," he answered.
01Gn 18:10 The LORD said, "I will certainly come back to you in about a year's time, and your wife Sarah will have a son!" Now Sarah was listening at the entrance of the tent behind him.
01Gn 18:11 Abraham and Sarah were old and getting on in years. Sarah had passed the age of childbearing.
01Gn 18:12 So she laughed to herself: "After I have become shriveled up and my lord is old, will I have delight?"
01Gn 18:13 But the LORD asked Abraham, "Why did Sarah laugh, saying, 'Can I really have a baby when I'm old?'
01Gn 18:14 Is anything impossible for the LORD? At the appointed time I will come back to you, and in about a year she will have a son."
01Gn 18:15 Sarah denied it. "I did not laugh," she said, because she was afraid. But He replied, "No, you did laugh."
01Gn 18:16 The men got up from there and looked out over Sodom, and Abraham was walking with them to see them off.
01Gn 18:17 Then the LORD said, "Should I hide from Abraham what I am about to do?
01Gn 18:18 Abraham is to become a great and powerful nation, and all the nations of the earth will be blessed through him.
01Gn 18:19 For I have chosen him so that he will command his children and his house after him to keep the way of the LORD by doing what is right and just. This is how the LORD will fulfill to Abraham what He promised him."
01Gn 18:20 Then the LORD said, "The outcry against Sodom and Gomorrah is immense, and their sin is extremely serious.
01Gn 18:21 I will go down to see if what they have done justifies the cry that has come up to Me. If not, I will find out."
01Gn 18:22 The men turned from there and went toward Sodom while Abraham remained standing before the LORD.
01Gn 18:23 Abraham stepped forward and said, "Will You really sweep away the righteous with the wicked?
01Gn 18:24 What if there are 50 righteous people in the city? Will You really sweep it away instead of sparing the place for the sake of the 50 righteous people who are in it?
01Gn 18:25 You could not possibly do such a thing: to kill the righteous with the wicked, treating the righteous and the wicked alike. You could not possibly do that! Won't the Judge of all the earth do what is just?"
01Gn 18:26 The LORD said, "If at Sodom I find 50 righteous people in the city, I will spare the whole place for their sake."
01Gn 18:27 Then Abraham answered, "Since I have ventured to speak to the Lord-- even though I am dust and ashes--
01Gn 18:28 suppose the 50 righteous lack five. Will you destroy the whole city for lack of five?" He replied, "I will not destroy [it] if I find 45 there."
01Gn 18:29 Then he spoke to Him again, "Suppose 40 are found there?" He answered, "I will not do [it] on account of 40."
01Gn 18:30 Then he said, "Let the Lord not be angry, and I will speak further. Suppose 30 are found there?" He answered, "I will not do [it] if I find 30 there."
01Gn 18:31 Then he said, "Since I have ventured to speak to the Lord, suppose 20 are found there?" He replied, "I will not destroy [it] on account of 20."
01Gn 18:32 Then he said, "Let the Lord not be angry, and I will speak one more time. Suppose 10 are found there?" He answered, "I will not destroy [it] on account of 10."
01Gn 18:33 When the LORD had finished speaking with Abraham, He departed, and Abraham returned to his place.
01Gn 19:1 The two angels entered Sodom in the evening as Lot was sitting at Sodom's gate. When Lot saw [them], he got up to meet them. He bowed [with his] face to the ground
01Gn 19:2 and said, "My lords, turn aside to your servant's house, wash your feet, and spend the night. Then you can get up early and go on your way." "No," they said. "We would rather spend the night in the square."
01Gn 19:3 But he urged them so strongly that they followed him and went into his house. He prepared a feast and baked unleavened bread for them, and they ate.
01Gn 19:4 Before they went to bed, the men of the city of Sodom, both young and old, the whole population, surrounded the house.
01Gn 19:5 They called out to Lot and said, "Where are the men who came to you tonight? Send them out to us so we can have sex with them!"
01Gn 19:6 Lot went out to them at the entrance and shut the door behind him.
01Gn 19:7 He said, "Don't do [this] evil, my brothers.
01Gn 19:8 Look, I've got two daughters who haven't had sexual relations with a man. I'll bring them out to you, and you can do whatever you want to them. However, don't do anything to these men, because they have come under the protection of my roof."
01Gn 19:9 "Get out of the way!" they said, adding, "This one came here as a foreigner, but he's acting like a judge! Now we'll do more harm to you than to them." They put pressure on Lot and came up to break down the door.
01Gn 19:10 But the angels reached out, brought Lot into the house with them, and shut the door.
01Gn 19:11 They struck the men who were at the door of the house, both young and old, with a blinding light so that they were unable to find the door.
01Gn 19:12 Then the angels said to Lot, "Do you have anyone else here: a son-in-law, your sons and daughters, or anyone else in the city who belongs to you? Get them out of this place,
01Gn 19:13 for we are about to destroy this place because the outcry against its people is great before the LORD, and the LORD has sent us to destroy it."
01Gn 19:14 So Lot went out and spoke to his sons-in-law, who were going to marry his daughters. "Get up," he said. "Get out of this place, for the LORD is about to destroy the city!" But his sons-in-law thought he was joking.
01Gn 19:15 At the crack of dawn the angels urged Lot on: "Get up! Take your wife and your two daughters who are here, or you will be swept away in the punishment of the city."
01Gn 19:16 But he hesitated, so because of the LORD's compassion for him, the men grabbed his hand, his wife's hand, and the hands of his two daughters. And they brought him out and left him outside the city.
01Gn 19:17 As soon as the angels got them outside, one of them said, "Run for your lives! Don't look back and don't stop anywhere on the plain! Run to the mountains, or you will be swept away!"
01Gn 19:18 But Lot said to them, "No, Lord-- please.
01Gn 19:19 Your servant has indeed found favor in Your sight, and You have shown me great kindness by saving my life. But I can't run to the mountains; the disaster will overtake me, and I will die.
01Gn 19:20 Look, this town is close enough for me to run to. It is a small place. Please let me go there-- it's only a small place, isn't it?-- so that I can survive."
01Gn 19:21 And he said to him, "All right, I'll grant your request about this matter too, and will not overthrow the town you mentioned.
01Gn 19:22 Hurry up! Run there, for I cannot do anything until you get there." Therefore the name of the city is Zoar.
01Gn 19:23 The sun had risen over the land when Lot reached Zoar.
01Gn 19:24 Then the LORD rained burning sulfur on Sodom and Gomorrah from the LORD out of the sky.
01Gn 19:25 He overthrew these cities, the entire plain, all the inhabitants of the cities, and whatever grew on the ground.
01Gn 19:26 But his wife looked back and became a pillar of salt.
01Gn 19:27 Early in the morning Abraham went to the place where he had stood before the LORD.
01Gn 19:28 He looked down toward Sodom and Gomorrah and all the land of the plain, and he saw that smoke was going up from the land like the smoke of a furnace.
01Gn 19:29 So it was, when God destroyed the cities of the plain, He remembered Abraham and brought Lot out of the middle of the upheaval when He overthrew the cities where Lot had lived.
01Gn 19:30 Lot departed from Zoar and lived in the mountains along with his two daughters, because he was afraid to live in Zoar. Instead, he and his two daughters lived in a cave.
01Gn 19:31 Then the firstborn said to the younger, "Our father is old, and there is no man in the land to sleep with us [as is] the custom of all the land.
01Gn 19:32 Come, let's get our father to drink wine so that we can sleep with him and preserve our father's line."
01Gn 19:33 So they got their father to drink wine that night, and the firstborn came and slept with her father; he did not know when she lay down or when she got up.
01Gn 19:34 The next day the firstborn said to the younger, "Look, I slept with my father last night. Let's get him to drink wine again tonight so you can go sleep with him and we can preserve our father's line."
01Gn 19:35 That night they again got their father to drink wine, and the younger went and slept with him; he did not know when she lay down or when she got up.
01Gn 19:36 So both of Lot's daughters became pregnant by their father.
01Gn 19:37 The firstborn gave birth to a son and named him Moab. He is the father of the Moabites of today.
01Gn 19:38 The younger also gave birth to a son, and she named him Ben-ammi. He is the father of the Ammonites of today.
01Gn 20:1 From there Abraham traveled to the region of the Negev and settled between Kadesh and Shur. While he lived in Gerar,
01Gn 20:2 Abraham said about his wife Sarah, "She is my sister." So Abimelech king of Gerar had Sarah brought to him.
01Gn 20:3 But God came to Abimelech in a dream by night and said to him, "You are about to die because of the woman you have taken, for she is a married woman."
01Gn 20:4 Now Abimelech had not approached her, so he said, "Lord, would you destroy a nation even though it is innocent?
01Gn 20:5 Didn't he himself say to me, 'She is my sister'? And she herself said, 'He is my brother.' I did this with a clear conscience and clean hands."
01Gn 20:6 Then God said to him in the dream, "Yes, I know that you did this with a clear conscience. I have also kept you from sinning against Me. Therefore I have not let you touch her.
01Gn 20:7 Now return the man's wife, for he is a prophet, and he will pray for you and you will live. But if you do not return her, know that you will certainly die, you and all who are yours."
01Gn 20:8 Early in the morning Abimelech got up, called all his servants together, and personally told them all these things; and the men were terrified.
01Gn 20:9 Then Abimelech called Abraham in and said to him, "What have you done to us? How did I sin against you that you have brought such enormous guilt on me and on my kingdom? You have done things to me that should never be done."
01Gn 20:10 Abimelech also said to Abraham, "What did you intend when you did this thing?"
01Gn 20:11 Abraham replied, "I thought, 'There is absolutely no fear of God in this place. They will kill me because of my wife.'
01Gn 20:12 Besides, she really is my sister, the daughter of my father though not the daughter of my mother, and she became my wife.
01Gn 20:13 So when God had me wander from my father's house, I said to her: Show your loyalty to me wherever we go, and say about me: 'He's my brother.'"
01Gn 20:14 Then Abimelech took sheep and cattle and male and female slaves, gave them to Abraham, and returned his wife Sarah to him.
01Gn 20:15 Abimelech said, "Look, my land is before you. Settle wherever you want."
01Gn 20:16 And to Sarah he said, "Look, I am giving your brother 1,000 pieces of silver. It is a verification of your honor to all who are with you. You are fully vindicated."
01Gn 20:17 Then Abraham prayed to God, and God healed Abimelech, his wife, and his female slaves so that they could bear children,
01Gn 20:18 for the LORD had completely closed all the wombs in Abimelech's household on account of Sarah, Abraham's wife.
01Gn 21:1 The LORD came to Sarah as He had said, and the LORD did for Sarah what He had promised.
01Gn 21:2 Sarah became pregnant and bore a son to Abraham in his old age, at the appointed time God had told him.
01Gn 21:3 Abraham named his son who was born to him-- the one Sarah bore to him-- Isaac.
01Gn 21:4 When his son Isaac was eight days old, Abraham circumcised him, as God had commanded him.
01Gn 21:5 Abraham was 100 years old when his son Isaac was born to him.
01Gn 21:6 Sarah said, "God has made me laugh, and everyone who hears will laugh with me."
01Gn 21:7 She also said, "Who would have told Abraham that Sarah would nurse children? Yet I have borne him a son in his old age."
01Gn 21:8 The child grew and was weaned, and Abraham held a great feast on the day Isaac was weaned.
01Gn 21:9 But Sarah saw the son mocking-- the one Hagar the Egyptian had borne to Abraham.
01Gn 21:10 So she said to Abraham, "Drive out this slave with her son, for the son of this slave will not be a co-heir with my son Isaac!"
01Gn 21:11 Now this was a very difficult thing for Abraham because of his son.
01Gn 21:12 But God said to Abraham, "Do not be concerned about the boy and your slave. Whatever Sarah says to you, listen to her, because your offspring will be traced through Isaac.
01Gn 21:13 But I will also make a nation of the slave's son because he is your offspring."
01Gn 21:14 Early in the morning Abraham got up, took bread and a waterskin, [put them] on Hagar's shoulders, and sent her and the boy away. She left and wandered in the Wilderness of Beer-sheba.
01Gn 21:15 When the water in the skin was gone, she left the boy under one of the bushes.
01Gn 21:16 Then she went and sat down nearby, about a bowshot away, for she said, "I can't [bear to] watch the boy die!" So as she sat nearby, she wept loudly.
01Gn 21:17 God heard the voice of the boy, and the angel of God called to Hagar from heaven and said to her, "What's wrong, Hagar? Don't be afraid, for God has heard the voice of the boy from the place where he is.
01Gn 21:18 Get up, help the boy up, and sustain him, for I will make him a great nation."
01Gn 21:19 Then God opened her eyes, and she saw a well of water. So she went and filled the waterskin and gave the boy a drink.
01Gn 21:20 God was with the boy, and he grew; he settled in the wilderness and became an archer.
01Gn 21:21 He settled in the Wilderness of Paran, and his mother got a wife for him from the land of Egypt.
01Gn 21:22 At that time Abimelech, with Phicol the commander of his army, said to Abraham, "God is with you in everything you do.
01Gn 21:23 Now swear to me here by God that you will not break an agreement with me or with my children and descendants. As I have kept faith with you, so you will keep faith with me and with the country where you are a resident alien."
01Gn 21:24 And Abraham said, "I swear [it]."
01Gn 21:25 But Abraham complained to Abimelech because of the water well that Abimelech's servants had seized.
01Gn 21:26 Abimelech replied, "I don't know who did this thing. You didn't report anything to me, so I hadn't heard about it until today."
01Gn 21:27 Then Abraham took sheep and cattle and gave them to Abimelech, and the two of them made a covenant.
01Gn 21:28 But Abraham had set apart seven ewe lambs from the flock.
01Gn 21:29 And Abimelech said to Abraham, "Why have you set apart these seven ewe lambs?"
01Gn 21:30 He replied, "You are to accept the seven ewe lambs from my hand so that this act will serve as my witness that I dug this well."
01Gn 21:31 Therefore that place was called Beer-sheba because it was there that the two of them swore an oath.
01Gn 21:32 After they had made a covenant at Beer-sheba, Abimelech and Phicol, the commander of his army, left and returned to the land of the Philistines.
01Gn 21:33 Abraham planted a tamarisk tree in Beer-sheba, and there he worshiped the LORD, the Everlasting God.
01Gn 21:34 And Abraham lived as a foreigner in the land of the Philistines for many days.
01Gn 22:1 After these things God tested Abraham and said to him, "Abraham!" "Here I am," he answered.
01Gn 22:2 "Take your son," He said, "your only [son] Isaac, whom you love, go to the land of Moriah, and offer him there as a burnt offering on one of the mountains I will tell you about."
01Gn 22:3 So early in the morning Abraham got up, saddled his donkey, and took with him two of his young men and his son Isaac. He split wood for a burnt offering and set out to go to the place God had told him about.
01Gn 22:4 On the third day Abraham looked up and saw the place in the distance.
01Gn 22:5 Then Abraham said to his young men, "Stay here with the donkey. The boy and I will go over there to worship; then we'll come back to you."
01Gn 22:6 Abraham took the wood for the burnt offering and laid it on his son Isaac. In his hand he took the fire and the sacrificial knife, and the two of them walked on together.
01Gn 22:7 Then Isaac spoke to his father Abraham and said, "My father." And he replied, "Here I am, my son." Isaac said, "The fire and the wood are here, but where is the lamb for the burnt offering?"
01Gn 22:8 Abraham answered, "God Himself will provide the lamb for the burnt offering, my son." Then the two of them walked on together.
01Gn 22:9 When they arrived at the place that God had told him about, Abraham built the altar there and arranged the wood. He bound his son Isaac and placed him on the altar, on top of the wood.
01Gn 22:10 Then Abraham reached out and took the knife to slaughter his son.
01Gn 22:11 But the Angel of the LORD called to him from heaven and said, "Abraham, Abraham!" He replied, "Here I am."
01Gn 22:12 Then He said, "Do not lay a hand on the boy or do anything to him. For now I know that you fear God, since you have not withheld your only son from Me."
01Gn 22:13 Abraham looked up and saw a ram caught by its horns in the thicket. So Abraham went and took the ram and offered it as a burnt offering in place of his son.
01Gn 22:14 And Abraham named that place The LORD Will Provide, so today it is said: "It will be provided on the LORD's mountain."
01Gn 22:15 Then the Angel of the LORD called to Abraham a second time from heaven
01Gn 22:16 and said, "By Myself I have sworn, says the LORD: Because you have done this thing and have not withheld your only son,
01Gn 22:17 I will indeed bless you and make your offspring as numerous as the stars in the sky and the sand on the seashore. Your offspring will possess the gates of their enemies.
01Gn 22:18 And all the nations of the earth will be blessed by your offspring because you have obeyed My command."
01Gn 22:19 Abraham went back to his young men, and they got up and went together to Beer-sheba. And Abraham settled in Beer-sheba.
01Gn 22:20 Now after these things Abraham was told, "Milcah also has borne sons to your brother Nahor:
01Gn 22:21 Uz his firstborn, his brother Buz, Kemuel the father of Aram,
01Gn 22:22 Chesed, Hazo, Pildash, Jidlaph, and Bethuel."
01Gn 22:23 And Bethuel fathered Rebekah. Milcah bore these eight to Nahor, Abraham's brother.
01Gn 22:24 His concubine, whose name was Reumah, also bore Tebah, Gaham, Tahash, and Maacah.
01Gn 23:1 Now Sarah lived 127 years; [these were all] the years of her life.
01Gn 23:2 Sarah died in Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron) in the land of Canaan, and Abraham went in to mourn for Sarah and to weep for her.
01Gn 23:3 Then Abraham got up from beside his dead [wife] and spoke to the Hittites:
01Gn 23:4 "I am a resident alien among you. Give me a burial site among you so that I can bury my dead."
01Gn 23:5 The Hittites replied to Abraham,
01Gn 23:6 "Listen to us, lord. You are God's chosen one among us. Bury your dead in our finest burial place. None of us will withhold from you his burial place for burying your dead."
01Gn 23:7 Then Abraham rose and bowed down to the Hittites, the people of the land.
01Gn 23:8 He said to them, "If you are willing [for me] to bury my dead, listen to me and ask Ephron son of Zohar on my behalf
01Gn 23:9 to give me the cave of Machpelah that belongs to him; it is at the end of his field. Let him give it to me in your presence, for the full price, as a burial place."
01Gn 23:10 Ephron was present with the Hittites. So in the presence of all the Hittites who came to the gate of his city, Ephron the Hittite answered Abraham:
01Gn 23:11 "No, my lord. Listen to me. I give you the field, and I give you the cave that is in it. I give it to you in the presence of my people. Bury your dead."
01Gn 23:12 Abraham bowed down to the people of the land
01Gn 23:13 and said to Ephron in the presence of the people of the land, "Please listen to me. Let me pay the price of the field. Accept it from me, and let me bury my dead there."
01Gn 23:14 Ephron answered Abraham and said to him,
01Gn 23:15 "My lord, listen to me. Land worth 400 shekels of silver-- what is that between you and me? Bury your dead."
01Gn 23:16 Abraham agreed with Ephron, and Abraham weighed out to Ephron the silver that he had agreed to in the hearing of the Hittites: 400 shekels of silver at the current commercial rate.
01Gn 23:17 So Ephron's field at Machpelah near Mamre-- the field with its cave and all the trees anywhere within the boundaries of the field-- became
01Gn 23:18 Abraham's possession in the presence of all the Hittites who came to the gate of his city.
01Gn 23:19 After this, Abraham buried his wife Sarah in the cave of the field at Machpelah near Mamre (that is, Hebron) in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 23:20 The field with its cave passed from the Hittites to Abraham as a burial place.
01Gn 24:1 Abraham was now old, getting on in years, and the LORD had blessed him in everything.
01Gn 24:2 Abraham said to his servant, the elder of his household who managed all he owned, "Place your hand under my thigh,
01Gn 24:3 and I will have you swear by the LORD, God of heaven and God of earth, that you will not take a wife for my son from the daughters of the Canaanites among whom I live,
01Gn 24:4 but will go to my land and my family to take a wife for my son Isaac."
01Gn 24:5 The servant said to him, "Suppose the woman is unwilling to follow me to this land? Should I have your son go back to the land you came from?"
01Gn 24:6 Abraham answered him, "Make sure that you don't take my son back there.
01Gn 24:7 The LORD, the God of heaven, who took me from my father's house and from my native land, who spoke to me and swore to me, 'I will give this land to your offspring'-- He will send His angel before you, and you can take a wife for my son from there.
01Gn 24:8 If the woman is unwilling to follow you, then you are free from this oath to me, but don't let my son go back there."
01Gn 24:9 So the servant placed his hand under his master Abraham's thigh and swore an oath to him concerning this matter.
01Gn 24:10 The servant took 10 of his master's camels and departed with all kinds of his master's goods in hand. Then he set out for the town of Nahor, Aram-naharaim.
01Gn 24:11 He made the camels kneel beside a well of water outside the town at evening. [This was] the time when the women went out to draw water.
01Gn 24:12 "LORD, God of my master Abraham," he prayed, "grant me success today, and show kindness to my master Abraham.
01Gn 24:13 I am standing here at the spring where the daughters of the men of the town are coming out to draw water.
01Gn 24:14 Let the girl to whom I say, 'Please lower your water jug so that I may drink,' and who responds, 'Drink, and I'll water your camels also'-- let her be the one You have appointed for Your servant Isaac. By this I will know that You have shown kindness to my master."
01Gn 24:15 Before he had finished speaking, there was Rebekah-- daughter of Bethuel son of Milcah, the wife of Abraham's brother Nahor-- coming with a jug on her shoulder.
01Gn 24:16 Now the girl was very beautiful, a young woman who had not known a man intimately. She went down to the spring, filled her jug, and came up.
01Gn 24:17 Then the servant ran to meet her and said, "Please let me have a little water from your jug."
01Gn 24:18 She replied, "Drink, my lord." She quickly lowered her jug to her hand and gave him a drink.
01Gn 24:19 When she had finished giving him a drink, she said, "I'll also draw water for your camels until they have had enough to drink."
01Gn 24:20 She quickly emptied her jug into the trough and hurried to the well again to draw water. She drew water for all his camels
01Gn 24:21 while the man silently watched her to see whether or not the LORD had made his journey a success.
01Gn 24:22 After the camels had finished drinking, the man took a gold ring weighing half a shekel, and for her wrists two bracelets weighing 10 shekels of gold.
01Gn 24:23 "Whose daughter are you?" he asked. "Please tell me, is there room in your father's house for us to spend the night?"
01Gn 24:24 She answered him, "I am the daughter of Bethuel son of Milcah, whom she bore to Nahor."
01Gn 24:25 She also said to him, "We have plenty of straw and feed, and a place to spend the night."
01Gn 24:26 Then the man bowed down, worshiped the LORD,
01Gn 24:27 and said, "Praise the LORD, the God of my master Abraham, who has not withheld His kindness and faithfulness from my master. As for me, the LORD has led me on the journey to the house of my master's relatives."
01Gn 24:28 The girl ran and told her mother's household about these things.
01Gn 24:29 Now Rebekah had a brother named Laban, and Laban ran out to the man at the spring.
01Gn 24:30 As soon as he had seen the ring, and the bracelets on his sister's wrists, and when he had heard his sister Rebekah's words-- "The man said this to me!"-- he went to the man. He was standing there by the camels at the spring.
01Gn 24:31 Laban said, "Come, you who are blessed by the LORD. Why are you standing out here? I have prepared the house and a place for the camels."
01Gn 24:32 So the man came to the house, and the camels were unloaded. Straw and feed were given to the camels, and water was brought to wash his feet and the feet of the men with him.
01Gn 24:33 A meal was set before him, but he said, "I will not eat until I have said what I have to say." So Laban said, "Speak on."
01Gn 24:34 "I am Abraham's servant," he said.
01Gn 24:35 "The LORD has greatly blessed my master, and he has become rich. He has given him sheep and cattle, silver and gold, male and female slaves, and camels and donkeys.
01Gn 24:36 Sarah, my master's wife, bore a son to my master in her old age, and he has given him everything he owns.
01Gn 24:37 My master put me under this oath: 'You will not take a wife for my son from the daughters of the Canaanites in whose land I live
01Gn 24:38 but will go to my father's household and to my family to take a wife for my son.'
01Gn 24:39 But I said to my master, 'Suppose the woman will not come back with me?'
01Gn 24:40 He said to me, 'The LORD before whom I have walked will send His angel with you and make your journey a success, and you will take a wife for my son from my family and from my father's household.
01Gn 24:41 Then you will be free from my oath if you go to my family and they do not give [her] to you-- you will be free from my oath.'
01Gn 24:42 "Today when I came to the spring, I prayed: LORD, God of my master Abraham, if only You will make my journey successful!
01Gn 24:43 I am standing here at a spring. Let the virgin who comes out to draw water, and I say to her: Please let me drink a little water from your jug,
01Gn 24:44 and who responds to me, 'Drink, and I'll draw water for your camels also'-- let her be the woman the LORD has appointed for my master's son.
01Gn 24:45 "Before I had finished praying in my heart, there was Rebekah coming with her jug on her shoulder, and she went down to the spring and drew water. So I said to her: Please let me have a drink.
01Gn 24:46 She quickly lowered her jug from her [shoulder] and said, 'Drink, and I'll water your camels also.' So I drank, and she also watered the camels.
01Gn 24:47 Then I asked her: Whose daughter are you? She responded, 'The daughter of Bethuel son of Nahor, whom Milcah bore to him.' So I put the ring on her nose and the bracelets on her wrists.
01Gn 24:48 Then I bowed down, worshiped the LORD, and praised the LORD, the God of my master Abraham, who guided me on the right way to take the daughter of my master's brother for his son.
01Gn 24:49 Now, if you are going to show kindness and faithfulness to my master, tell me; if not, tell me, and I will go elsewhere."
01Gn 24:50 Laban and Bethuel answered, "This is from the LORD; we have no choice in the matter.
01Gn 24:51 Rebekah is here in front of you. Take [her] and go, and let her be a wife for your master's son, just as the LORD has spoken."
01Gn 24:52 When Abraham's servant heard their words, he bowed to the ground before the LORD.
01Gn 24:53 Then he brought out objects of silver and gold, and garments, and gave [them] to Rebekah. He also gave precious gifts to her brother and her mother.
01Gn 24:54 Then he and the men with him ate and drank and spent the night. When they got up in the morning, he said, "Send me to my master."
01Gn 24:55 But her brother and mother said, "Let the girl stay with us for about 10 days. Then she can go."
01Gn 24:56 But he responded to them, "Do not delay me, since the LORD has made my journey a success. Send me away so that I may go to my master."
01Gn 24:57 So they said, "Let's call the girl and ask her opinion."
01Gn 24:58 They called Rebekah and said to her, "Will you go with this man?" She replied, "I will go."
01Gn 24:59 So they sent away their sister Rebekah and her nurse, and Abraham's servant and his men.
01Gn 24:60 They blessed Rebekah, saying to her: Our sister, may you become thousands upon ten thousands. May your offspring possess the gates of their enemies.
01Gn 24:61 Then Rebekah and her young women got up, mounted the camels, and followed the man. So the servant took Rebekah and left.
01Gn 24:62 Now Isaac was returning from Beer-lahai-roi, for he was living in the Negev region.
01Gn 24:63 In the early evening, Isaac went out to walk in the field, and looking up, he saw camels coming.
01Gn 24:64 Rebekah looked up, and when she saw Isaac, she got down from her camel
01Gn 24:65 and asked the servant, "Who is that man in the field coming to meet us?" The servant answered, "It is my master." So she took her veil and covered herself.
01Gn 24:66 Then the servant told Isaac everything he had done.
01Gn 24:67 And Isaac brought her into the tent of his mother Sarah and took Rebekah to be his wife. Isaac loved her, and he was comforted after his mother's [death].
01Gn 25:1 Now Abraham took another wife, whose name was Keturah,
01Gn 25:2 and she bore him Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah.
01Gn 25:3 Jokshan fathered Sheba and Dedan. Dedan's sons were the Asshurim, Letushim, and Leummim.
01Gn 25:4 And Midian's sons were Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida, and Eldaah. All these were sons of Keturah.
01Gn 25:5 Abraham gave everything he owned to Isaac.
01Gn 25:6 And Abraham gave gifts to the sons of his concubines, but while he was still alive he sent them eastward, away from his son Isaac, to the land of the East.
01Gn 25:7 This is the length of Abraham's life: 175 years.
01Gn 25:8 He took his last breath and died at a ripe old age, old and contented, and he was gathered to his people.
01Gn 25:9 His sons Isaac and Ishmael buried him in the cave of Machpelah near Mamre, in the field of Ephron son of Zohar the Hittite.
01Gn 25:10 This was the field that Abraham bought from the Hittites. Abraham was buried there with his wife Sarah.
01Gn 25:11 After Abraham's death, God blessed his son Isaac, who lived near Beer-lahai-roi.
01Gn 25:12 These are the family records of Abraham's son Ishmael, whom Hagar the Egyptian, Sarah's slave, bore to Abraham.
01Gn 25:13 These are the names of Ishmael's sons; their names according to the family records are: Nebaioth, Ishmael's firstborn, then Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam,
01Gn 25:14 Mishma, Dumah, Massa,
01Gn 25:15 Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah.
01Gn 25:16 These are Ishmael's sons, and these are their names by their villages and encampments: 12 leaders of their clans.
01Gn 25:17 This is the length of Ishmael's life: 137 years. He took his last breath and died, and was gathered to his people.
01Gn 25:18 And they settled from Havilah to Shur, which is opposite Egypt as you go toward Asshur. He lived in opposition to all his brothers.
01Gn 25:19 These are the family records of Isaac son of Abraham. Abraham fathered Isaac.
01Gn 25:20 Isaac was 40 years old when he took as his wife Rebekah daughter of Bethuel the Aramean from Paddan-aram, and sister of Laban the Aramean.
01Gn 25:21 Isaac prayed to the LORD on behalf of his wife because she was barren. The LORD heard his prayer, and his wife Rebekah conceived.
01Gn 25:22 But the children inside her struggled with each other, and she said, "Why is this happening to me?" So she went to inquire of the LORD.
01Gn 25:23 And the LORD said to her: Two nations are in your womb; two people will [come] from you and be separated. One people will be stronger than the other, and the older will serve the younger.
01Gn 25:24 When her time came to give birth, there were indeed twins in her womb.
01Gn 25:25 The first one came out reddish, covered with hair like a fur coat, and they named him Esau.
01Gn 25:26 After this, his brother came out grasping Esau's heel with his hand. So he was named Jacob. Isaac was 60 years old when they were born.
01Gn 25:27 When the boys grew up, Esau became an expert hunter, an outdoorsman, but Jacob was a quiet man who stayed at home.
01Gn 25:28 Isaac loved Esau because he had a taste for wild game, but Rebekah loved Jacob.
01Gn 25:29 Once when Jacob was cooking a stew, Esau came in from the field, exhausted.
01Gn 25:30 He said to Jacob, "Let me eat some of that red stuff, because I'm exhausted." That is why he was [also] named Edom.
01Gn 25:31 Jacob replied, "First sell me your birthright."
01Gn 25:32 "Look," said Esau, "I'm about to die, so what good is a birthright to me?"
01Gn 25:33 Jacob said, "Swear to me first." So he swore to Jacob and sold his birthright to him.
01Gn 25:34 Then Jacob gave bread and lentil stew to Esau; he ate, drank, got up, and went away. So Esau despised his birthright.
01Gn 26:1 There was another famine in the land in addition to the one that had occurred in Abraham's time. And Isaac went to Abimelech, king of the Philistines, at Gerar.
01Gn 26:2 The LORD appeared to him and said, "Do not go down to Egypt. Live in the land that I tell you about;
01Gn 26:3 stay in this land as a foreigner, and I will be with you and bless you. For I will give all these lands to you and your offspring, and I will confirm the oath that I swore to your father Abraham.
01Gn 26:4 I will make your offspring as numerous as the stars of the sky, I will give your offspring all these lands, and all the nations of the earth will be blessed by your offspring,
01Gn 26:5 because Abraham listened to My voice and kept My mandate, My commands, My statutes, and My instructions."
01Gn 26:6 So Isaac settled in Gerar.
01Gn 26:7 When the men of the place asked about his wife, he said, "She is my sister," for he was afraid to say "my wife," [thinking], "The men of the place will kill me on account of Rebekah, for she is a beautiful woman."
01Gn 26:8 When Isaac had been there for some time, Abimelech king of the Philistines looked down from the window and was surprised to see Isaac caressing his wife Rebekah.
01Gn 26:9 Abimelech sent for Isaac and said, "So she is really your wife! How could you say, 'She's my sister'?" Isaac answered him, "Because I thought I might die on account of her."
01Gn 26:10 Then Abimelech said, "What is this you've done to us? One of the people could easily have slept with your wife, and you would have brought guilt on us."
01Gn 26:11 So Abimelech warned all the people with these words: "Whoever harms this man or his wife will certainly die."
01Gn 26:12 Isaac sowed seed in that land, and in that year he reaped a hundred times [what was sown]. The LORD blessed him,
01Gn 26:13 and the man became rich and kept getting richer until he was very wealthy.
01Gn 26:14 He had flocks of sheep, herds of cattle, and many slaves, and the Philistines were envious of him.
01Gn 26:15 The Philistines stopped up all the wells that his father's slaves had dug in the days of his father Abraham, filling them with dirt.
01Gn 26:16 And Abimelech said to Isaac, "Leave us, for you are much too powerful for us."
01Gn 26:17 So Isaac left there, camped in the valley of Gerar, and lived there.
01Gn 26:18 Isaac reopened the water wells that had been dug in the days of his father Abraham and that the Philistines had stopped up after Abraham died. He gave them the same names his father had given them.
01Gn 26:19 Moreover, Isaac's slaves dug in the valley and found a well of spring water there.
01Gn 26:20 But the herdsmen of Gerar quarreled with Isaac's herdsmen and said, "The water is ours!" So he named the well Quarrel because they quarreled with him.
01Gn 26:21 Then they dug another well and quarreled over that one also, so he named it Hostility.
01Gn 26:22 He moved from there and dug another, and they did not quarrel over it. He named it Open Spaces and said, "For now the LORD has made room for us, and we will be fruitful in the land."
01Gn 26:23 From there he went up to Beer-sheba,
01Gn 26:24 and the LORD appeared to him that night and said, "I am the God of your father Abraham. Do not be afraid, for I am with you. I will bless you and multiply your offspring because of My servant Abraham."
01Gn 26:25 So he built an altar there, worshiped the LORD, and pitched his tent there. Isaac's slaves also dug a well there.
01Gn 26:26 Then Abimelech came to him from Gerar with Ahuzzath his adviser and Phicol the commander of his army.
01Gn 26:27 Isaac said to them, "Why have you come to me? You hated me and sent me away from you."
01Gn 26:28 They replied, "We have clearly seen how the LORD has been with you. We think there should be an oath between two parties-- between us and you. Let us make a covenant with you:
01Gn 26:29 You will not harm us, just as we have not harmed you but have only done what was good to you, sending you away in peace. You are now blessed by the LORD."
01Gn 26:30 So he prepared a banquet for them, and they ate and drank.
01Gn 26:31 They got up early in the morning and swore an oath to each other. Then Isaac sent them on their way, and they left him in peace.
01Gn 26:32 On that same day Isaac's slaves came to tell him about the well they had dug, saying to him, "We have found water!"
01Gn 26:33 He called it Oath. Therefore the name of the city is Beer-sheba to this day.
01Gn 26:34 When Esau was 40 years old, he took as his wives Judith daughter of Beeri the Hittite, and Basemath daughter of Elon the Hittite.
01Gn 26:35 They made life bitter for Isaac and Rebekah.
01Gn 27:1 When Isaac was old and his eyes were so weak that he could not see, he called his older son Esau and said to him, "My son." And he answered, "Here I am."
01Gn 27:2 He said, "Look, I am old and do not know the day of my death.
01Gn 27:3 Take your [hunting] gear, your quiver and bow, and go out in the field to hunt some game for me.
01Gn 27:4 Then make me the delicious food that I love and bring it to me to eat, so that I can bless you before I die."
01Gn 27:5 Now Rebekah was listening to what Isaac said to his son Esau. So while Esau went to the field to hunt some game to bring in,
01Gn 27:6 Rebekah said to her son Jacob, "Listen! I heard your father talking with your brother Esau. He said,
01Gn 27:7 'Bring me some game and make some delicious food for me to eat so that I can bless you in the LORD's presence before I die.'
01Gn 27:8 Now obey every order I give you, my son.
01Gn 27:9 Go to the flock and bring me two choice young goats, and I will make them into a delicious meal for your father-- the kind he loves.
01Gn 27:10 Then take it to your father to eat so that he may bless you before he dies."
01Gn 27:11 Jacob answered Rebekah his mother, "Look, my brother Esau is a hairy man, but I am a man with smooth skin.
01Gn 27:12 Suppose my father touches me. Then I will seem to be deceiving him, and I will bring a curse rather than a blessing on myself."
01Gn 27:13 His mother said to him, "Your curse be on me, my son. Just obey me and go get them for me."
01Gn 27:14 So he went and got them and brought them to his mother, and his mother made the delicious food his father loved.
01Gn 27:15 Then Rebekah took the best clothes of her older son Esau, which were there at the house, and had her younger son Jacob wear them.
01Gn 27:16 She put the goatskins on his hands and the smooth part of his neck.
01Gn 27:17 Then she handed the delicious food and the bread she had made to her son Jacob.
01Gn 27:18 When he came to his father, he said, "My father." And he answered, "Here I am. Who are you, my son?"
01Gn 27:19 Jacob replied to his father, "I am Esau, your firstborn. I have done as you told me. Please sit up and eat some of my game so that you may bless me."
01Gn 27:20 But Isaac said to his son, "How did you ever find it so quickly, my son?" He replied, "Because the LORD your God worked it out for me."
01Gn 27:21 Then Isaac said to Jacob, "Please come closer so I can touch you, my son. Are you really my son Esau, or not?"
01Gn 27:22 So Jacob came closer to his father Isaac. When he touched him, he said, "The voice is the voice of Jacob, but the hands are the hands of Esau."
01Gn 27:23 He did not recognize him, because his hands were hairy like those of his brother Esau; so he blessed him.
01Gn 27:24 Again he asked, "Are you really my son Esau?" And he replied, "I am."
01Gn 27:25 Then he said, "Serve me, and let me eat some of my son's game so that I can bless you." Jacob brought it to him, and he ate; he brought him wine, and he drank.
01Gn 27:26 Then his father Isaac said to him, "Please come closer and kiss me, my son."
01Gn 27:27 So he came closer and kissed him. When Isaac smelled his clothes, he blessed him and said: Ah, the smell of my son is like the smell of a field that the LORD has blessed.
01Gn 27:28 May God give to you-- from the dew of the sky and from the richness of the land-- an abundance of grain and new wine.
01Gn 27:29 May peoples serve you and nations bow down to you. Be master over your brothers; may your mother's sons bow down to you. Those who curse you will be cursed, and those who bless you will be blessed.
01Gn 27:30 As soon as Isaac had finished blessing Jacob and Jacob had left the presence of his father Isaac, his brother Esau arrived from the hunt.
01Gn 27:31 He had also made some delicious food and brought it to his father. Then he said to his father, "Let my father get up and eat some of his son's game, so that you may bless me."
01Gn 27:32 But his father Isaac said to him, "Who are you?" He answered, "I am Esau your firstborn son."
01Gn 27:33 Isaac began to tremble uncontrollably. "Who was it then," he said, "who hunted game and brought it to me? I ate it all before you came in, and I blessed him. Indeed, he will be blessed!"
01Gn 27:34 When Esau heard his father's words, he cried out with a loud and bitter cry and said to his father, "Bless me-- me too, my father!"
01Gn 27:35 But he replied, "Your brother came deceitfully and took your blessing."
01Gn 27:36 So he said, "Isn't he rightly named Jacob? For he has cheated me twice now. He took my birthright, and look, now he has taken my blessing." Then he asked, "Haven't you saved a blessing for me?"
01Gn 27:37 But Isaac answered Esau: "Look, I have made him a master over you, have given him all of his relatives as his servants, and have sustained him with grain and new wine. What then can I do for you, my son?"
01Gn 27:38 Esau said to his father, "Do you only have one blessing, my father? Bless me-- me too, my father!" And Esau wept loudly.
01Gn 27:39 Then his father Isaac answered him: Look, your dwelling place will be away from the richness of the land, away from the dew of the sky above.
01Gn 27:40 You will live by your sword, and you will serve your brother. But when you rebel, you will break his yoke from your neck.
01Gn 27:41 Esau held a grudge against Jacob because of the blessing his father had given him. And Esau determined in his heart: "The days of mourning for my father are approaching; then I will kill my brother Jacob."
01Gn 27:42 When the words of her older son Esau were reported to Rebekah, she summoned her younger son Jacob and said to him, "Listen, your brother Esau is consoling himself by planning to kill you.
01Gn 27:43 So now, my son, listen to me. Flee at once to my brother Laban in Haran,
01Gn 27:44 and stay with him for a few days until your brother's anger subsides--
01Gn 27:45 until your brother's rage turns away from you and he forgets what you have done to him. Then I will send for you and bring you back from there. Why should I lose you both in one day?"
01Gn 27:46 So Rebekah said to Isaac, "I'm sick of my life because of these Hittite women. If Jacob marries a Hittite woman like one of them, what good is my life?"
01Gn 28:1 Isaac summoned Jacob, blessed him, and commanded him: "Don't take a wife from the Canaanite women.
01Gn 28:2 Go at once to Paddan-aram, to the house of Bethuel, your mother's father. Marry one of the daughters of Laban, your mother's brother.
01Gn 28:3 May God Almighty bless you and make you fruitful and multiply you so that you become an assembly of peoples.
01Gn 28:4 May God give you and your offspring the blessing of Abraham so that you may possess the land where you live as an alien, the land God gave to Abraham."
01Gn 28:5 So Isaac sent Jacob to Paddan-aram, to Laban son of Bethuel the Aramean, the brother of Rebekah, the mother of Jacob and Esau.
01Gn 28:6 Esau noticed that Isaac blessed Jacob and sent him to Paddan-aram to get a wife there. When he blessed him, Isaac commanded Jacob not to marry a Canaanite woman.
01Gn 28:7 And Jacob listened to his father and mother and went to Paddan-aram.
01Gn 28:8 Esau realized that his father Isaac disapproved of the Canaanite women,
01Gn 28:9 so Esau went to Ishmael and married, in addition to his other wives, Mahalath daughter of Ishmael, Abraham's son. She was the sister of Nebaioth.
01Gn 28:10 Jacob left Beer-sheba and went toward Haran.
01Gn 28:11 He reached a certain place and spent the night there because the sun had set. He took one of the stones from the place, put it there at his head, and lay down in that place.
01Gn 28:12 And he dreamed: A stairway was set on the ground with its top reaching heaven, and God's angels were going up and down on it.
01Gn 28:13 The LORD was standing there beside him, saying, "I am the LORD, the God of your father Abraham and the God of Isaac. I will give you and your offspring the land that you are now sleeping on.
01Gn 28:14 Your offspring will be like the dust of the earth, and you will spread out toward the west, the east, the north, and the south. All the peoples on earth will be blessed through you and your offspring.
01Gn 28:15 Look, I am with you and will watch over you wherever you go. I will bring you back to this land, for I will not leave you until I have done what I have promised you."
01Gn 28:16 When Jacob awoke from his sleep, he said, "Surely the LORD is in this place, and I did not know it."
01Gn 28:17 He was afraid and said, "What an awesome place this is! This is none other than the house of God. This is the gate of heaven."
01Gn 28:18 Early in the morning Jacob took the stone that was near his head and set it up as a marker. He poured oil on top of it
01Gn 28:19 and named the place Bethel, though previously the city was named Luz.
01Gn 28:20 Then Jacob made a vow: "If God will be with me and watch over me on this journey, if He provides me with food to eat and clothing to wear,
01Gn 28:21 and if I return safely to my father's house, then the LORD will be my God.
01Gn 28:22 This stone that I have set up as a marker will be God's house, and I will give to You a tenth of all that You give me."
01Gn 29:1 Jacob resumed his journey and went to the eastern country.
01Gn 29:2 He looked and saw a well in a field. Three flocks of sheep were lying there beside it because the sheep were watered from this well. A large stone covered the opening of the well.
01Gn 29:3 When all the flocks were gathered there, the [shepherds] would roll the stone from the opening of the well and water the sheep. The stone was then placed back on the well's opening.
01Gn 29:4 Jacob asked the men at the well, "My brothers! Where are you from?" "We're from Haran," they answered.
01Gn 29:5 "Do you know Laban son of Nahor?" Jacob asked them. They answered, "We know [him]."
01Gn 29:6 "Is he well?" Jacob asked. "Yes," they said, "and here is his daughter Rachel, coming with his sheep."
01Gn 29:7 Then Jacob said, "Look, it is still broad daylight. It's not time for the animals to be gathered. Water the flock, then go out and let them graze."
01Gn 29:8 But they replied, "We can't, until all the flocks have been gathered and the stone is rolled from the well's opening. Then we will water the sheep."
01Gn 29:9 While he was still speaking with them, Rachel came with her father's sheep, for she was a shepherdess.
01Gn 29:10 As soon as Jacob saw his uncle Laban's daughter Rachel with his sheep, he went up and rolled the stone from the opening and watered his uncle Laban's sheep.
01Gn 29:11 Then Jacob kissed Rachel and wept loudly.
01Gn 29:12 He told Rachel that he was her father's relative, Rebekah's son. She ran and told her father.
01Gn 29:13 When Laban heard the news about his sister's son Jacob, he ran to meet him, hugged him, and kissed him. Then he took him to his house, and Jacob told him all that had happened.
01Gn 29:14 Laban said to him, "Yes, you are my own flesh and blood." After Jacob had stayed with him a month,
01Gn 29:15 Laban said to him, "Just because you're my relative, should you work for me for nothing? Tell me what your wages should be."
01Gn 29:16 Now Laban had two daughters: the older was named Leah, and the younger was named Rachel.
01Gn 29:17 Leah had delicate eyes, but Rachel was shapely and beautiful.
01Gn 29:18 Jacob loved Rachel, so he answered Laban, "I'll work for you seven years for your younger daughter Rachel."
01Gn 29:19 Laban replied, "Better that I give her to you than to some other man. Stay with me."
01Gn 29:20 So Jacob worked seven years for Rachel, and they seemed like only a few days to him because of his love for her.
01Gn 29:21 Then Jacob said to Laban, "Give me my wife, for my time is completed. I want to sleep with her."
01Gn 29:22 So Laban invited all the men of the place to a feast.
01Gn 29:23 That evening, Laban took his daughter Leah and gave her to Jacob, and he slept with her.
01Gn 29:24 And Laban gave his slave Zilpah to his daughter Leah as her slave.
01Gn 29:25 When morning came, there was Leah! So he said to Laban, "What is this you have done to me? Wasn't it for Rachel that I worked for you? Why have you deceived me?"
01Gn 29:26 Laban answered, "It is not the custom in this place to give the younger [daughter in marriage] before the firstborn.
01Gn 29:27 Complete this week [of wedding celebration], and we will also give you this [younger] one in return for working yet another seven years for me."
01Gn 29:28 And Jacob did just that. He finished the week [of celebration], and Laban gave him his daughter Rachel as his wife.
01Gn 29:29 And Laban gave his slave Bilhah to his daughter Rachel as her slave.
01Gn 29:30 Jacob slept with Rachel also, and indeed, he loved Rachel more than Leah. And he worked for Laban another seven years.
01Gn 29:31 When the LORD saw that Leah was unloved, He opened her womb; but Rachel was barren.
01Gn 29:32 Leah conceived, gave birth to a son, and named him Reuben, for she said, "The LORD has seen my affliction; surely my husband will love me now."
01Gn 29:33 She conceived again, gave birth to a son, and said, "The LORD heard that I am unloved and has given me this [son] also." So she named him Simeon.
01Gn 29:34 She conceived again, gave birth to a son, and said, "At last, my husband will become attached to me because I have borne him three sons." Therefore he was named Levi.
01Gn 29:35 And she conceived again, gave birth to a son, and said, "This time I will praise the LORD." Therefore she named him Judah. Then Leah stopped having children.
01Gn 30:1 When Rachel saw that she was not bearing Jacob [any children], she envied her sister. "Give me sons, or I will die!" she said to Jacob.
01Gn 30:2 Jacob became angry with Rachel and said, "Am I in God's place, who has withheld children from you?"
01Gn 30:3 Then she said, "Here is my slave Bilhah. Go sleep with her, and she'll bear [children] for me so that through her I too can build [a family]."
01Gn 30:4 So Rachel gave her slave Bilhah to Jacob as a wife, and he slept with her.
01Gn 30:5 Bilhah conceived and bore Jacob a son.
01Gn 30:6 Rachel said, "God has vindicated me; yes, He has heard me and given me a son," and she named him Dan.
01Gn 30:7 Rachel's slave Bilhah conceived again and bore Jacob a second son.
01Gn 30:8 Rachel said, "In [my] wrestlings with God, I have wrestled with my sister and won," and she named him Naphtali.
01Gn 30:9 When Leah saw that she had stopped having children, she took her slave Zilpah and gave her to Jacob as a wife.
01Gn 30:10 Leah's slave Zilpah bore Jacob a son.
01Gn 30:11 Then Leah said, "What good fortune!" and she named him Gad.
01Gn 30:12 When Leah's slave Zilpah bore Jacob a second son,
01Gn 30:13 Leah said, "I am happy that the women call me happy," so she named him Asher.
01Gn 30:14 Reuben went out during the wheat harvest and found some mandrakes in the field. When he brought them to his mother Leah, Rachel asked, "Please give me some of your son's mandrakes."
01Gn 30:15 But Leah replied to her, "Isn't it enough that you have taken my husband? Now you also want to take my son's mandrakes?" "Well," Rachel said, "you can sleep with him tonight in exchange for your son's mandrakes."
01Gn 30:16 When Jacob came in from the field that evening, Leah went out to meet him and said, "You must come with me, for I have hired you with my son's mandrakes." So Jacob slept with her that night.
01Gn 30:17 God listened to Leah, and she conceived and bore Jacob a fifth son.
01Gn 30:18 Leah said, "God has rewarded me for giving my slave to my husband," and she named him Issachar.
01Gn 30:19 Then Leah conceived again and bore Jacob a sixth son.
01Gn 30:20 "God has given me a good gift," Leah said. "This time my husband will honor me because I have borne him six sons," and she named him Zebulun.
01Gn 30:21 Later, Leah bore a daughter and named her Dinah.
01Gn 30:22 Then God remembered Rachel. He listened to her and opened her womb.
01Gn 30:23 She conceived and bore a son, and said, "God has taken away my shame."
01Gn 30:24 She named him Joseph: "May the LORD add another son to me."
01Gn 30:25 After Rachel gave birth to Joseph, Jacob said to Laban, "Send me on my way so that I can return to my homeland.
01Gn 30:26 Give me my wives and my children that I have worked for, and let me go. You know how hard I have worked for you."
01Gn 30:27 But Laban said to him, "If I have found favor in your sight, [stay.] I have learned by divination that the LORD has blessed me because of you."
01Gn 30:28 Then Laban said, "Name your wages, and I will pay them."
01Gn 30:29 So Jacob said to him, "You know what I have done for you and your herds.
01Gn 30:30 For you had very little before I came, but now your wealth has increased. The LORD has blessed you because of me. And now, when will I also do something for my own family?"
01Gn 30:31 Laban asked, "What should I give you?" And Jacob said, "You don't need to give me anything. If you do this one thing for me, I will continue to shepherd and keep your flock.
01Gn 30:32 Let me go through all your sheep today and remove every sheep that is speckled or spotted, every dark-colored sheep among the lambs, and the spotted and speckled among the female goats. [Such] will be my wages.
01Gn 30:33 In the future when you come to check on my wages, my honesty will testify for me. [If I have] any female goats that are not speckled or spotted, or any lambs that are not black, they will be considered stolen."
01Gn 30:34 "Good," said Laban. "Let it be as you have said."
01Gn 30:35 That day Laban removed the streaked and spotted male goats and all the speckled and spotted female goats-- every one that had any white on it-- and every dark-colored sheep among the lambs, and he placed his sons in charge of them.
01Gn 30:36 He put a three-day journey between himself and Jacob. Jacob, meanwhile, was shepherding the rest of Laban's flock.
01Gn 30:37 Jacob then took branches of fresh poplar, almond, and plane wood, and peeled [the bark], exposing white stripes on the branches.
01Gn 30:38 He set the peeled branches in the troughs in front of the sheep-- in the water channels where the sheep came to drink. And the sheep bred when they came to drink.
01Gn 30:39 The flocks bred in front of the branches and bore streaked, speckled, and spotted young.
01Gn 30:40 Jacob separated the lambs and made the flocks face the streaked and the completely dark sheep in Laban's flocks. Then he set his own stock apart and didn't put them with Laban's sheep.
01Gn 30:41 Whenever the stronger of the flock were breeding, Jacob placed the branches in the troughs, in full view of the flocks, and they would breed in front of the branches.
01Gn 30:42 As for the weaklings of the flocks, he did not put out the branches. So it turned out that the weak sheep belonged to Laban and the stronger ones to Jacob.
01Gn 30:43 And the man became very rich. He had many flocks, male and female slaves, and camels and donkeys.
01Gn 31:1 Now Jacob heard what Laban's sons were saying: "Jacob has taken all that was our father's and has built this wealth from what belonged to our father."
01Gn 31:2 And Jacob saw from Laban's face that his attitude toward him was not the same.
01Gn 31:3 Then the LORD said to him, "Go back to the land of your fathers and to your family, and I will be with you."
01Gn 31:4 Jacob had Rachel and Leah called to the field [where] his flocks were.
01Gn 31:5 He said to them, "I can see from your father's face that his attitude toward me is not the same, but the God of my father has been with me.
01Gn 31:6 You know that I've worked hard for your father
01Gn 31:7 and that he has cheated me and changed my wages 10 times. But God has not let him harm me.
01Gn 31:8 If he said, 'The spotted sheep will be your wages,' then all the sheep were born spotted. If he said, 'The streaked sheep will be your wages,' then all the sheep were born streaked.
01Gn 31:9 God has taken your father's herds and given them to me.
01Gn 31:10 "When the flocks were breeding, I saw in a dream that the streaked, spotted, and speckled males were mating with the females.
01Gn 31:11 In that dream the Angel of God said to me, 'Jacob!' and I said: Here I am.
01Gn 31:12 And He said, 'Look up and see: all the males that are mating with the flocks are streaked, spotted, and speckled, for I have seen all that Laban has been doing to you.
01Gn 31:13 I am the God of Bethel, where you poured oil on the stone marker and made a solemn vow to Me. Get up, leave this land, and return to your native land.'"
01Gn 31:14 Then Rachel and Leah answered him, "Do we have any portion or inheritance in our father's household?
01Gn 31:15 Are we not regarded by him as outsiders? For he has sold us and has certainly spent our money.
01Gn 31:16 In fact, all the wealth that God has taken from our father belongs to us and to our children. So do whatever God has said to you."
01Gn 31:17 Then Jacob got up and put his children and wives on the camels.
01Gn 31:18 He took all the livestock and possessions he had acquired in Paddan-aram, and he drove his herds to go to the land of his father Isaac in Canaan.
01Gn 31:19 When Laban had gone to shear his sheep, Rachel stole her father's household idols.
01Gn 31:20 And Jacob deceived Laban the Aramean, not telling him that he was fleeing.
01Gn 31:21 He fled with all his possessions, crossed the Euphrates, and headed for the hill country of Gilead.
01Gn 31:22 On the third day Laban was told that Jacob had fled.
01Gn 31:23 So he took his relatives with him, pursued Jacob for seven days, and overtook him at Mount Gilead.
01Gn 31:24 But God came to Laban the Aramean in a dream at night. "Watch yourself!" God warned him. "Don't say anything to Jacob, either good or bad."
01Gn 31:25 When Laban overtook Jacob, Jacob had pitched his tent in the hill country, and Laban and his brothers also pitched [their tents] in the hill country of Gilead.
01Gn 31:26 Then Laban said to Jacob, "What have you done? You have deceived me and taken my daughters away like prisoners of war!
01Gn 31:27 Why did you secretly flee from me, deceive me, and not tell me? I would have sent you away with joy and singing, with tambourines and lyres,
01Gn 31:28 but you didn't even let me kiss my grandchildren and my daughters. You have acted foolishly.
01Gn 31:29 I could do you great harm, but last night the God of your father said to me: 'Watch yourself. Don't say anything to Jacob, either good or bad.'
01Gn 31:30 Now you have gone off because you long for your father-- but why have you stolen my gods?"
01Gn 31:31 Jacob answered, "I was afraid, for I thought you would take your daughters from me by force.
01Gn 31:32 If you find your gods with anyone [here], he will not live! Before our relatives, point out anything that is yours and take it." Jacob did not know that Rachel had stolen [the idols].
01Gn 31:33 So Laban went into Jacob's tent, then Leah's tent, and then the tents of the two female slaves, but he found nothing. Then he left Leah's tent and entered Rachel's.
01Gn 31:34 Now Rachel had taken Laban's household idols, put them in the saddlebag of the camel, and sat on them. Laban searched the whole tent but found nothing.
01Gn 31:35 She said to her father, "Sir, don't be angry that I cannot stand up in your presence; I am having my monthly period." So Laban searched, but could not find the household idols.
01Gn 31:36 Then Jacob became incensed and brought charges against Laban. "What is my crime?" he said to Laban. "What is my sin, that you have pursued me?
01Gn 31:37 You've searched all my possessions! Have you found anything of yours? Put it here before my relatives and yours, and let them decide between the two of us.
01Gn 31:38 I've been with you these 20 years. Your ewes and female goats have not miscarried, and I have not eaten the rams from your flock.
01Gn 31:39 I did not bring you any of the flock torn by wild beasts; I myself bore the loss. You demanded [payment] from me for what was stolen by day or by night.
01Gn 31:40 There I was-- the heat consumed me by day and the frost by night, and sleep fled from my eyes.
01Gn 31:41 For 20 years I have worked in your household-- 14 years for your two daughters and six years for your flocks-- and you have changed my wages 10 times!
01Gn 31:42 If the God of my father, the God of Abraham, the Fear of Isaac, had not been with me, certainly now you would have sent me off empty-handed. But God has seen my affliction and my hard work, and He issued His verdict last night."
01Gn 31:43 Then Laban answered Jacob, "The daughters are my daughters; the sons, my sons; and the flocks, my flocks! Everything you see is mine! But what can I do today for these daughters of mine or for the children they have borne?
01Gn 31:44 Come now, let's make a covenant, you and I. Let it be a witness between the two of us."
01Gn 31:45 So Jacob picked out a stone and set it up as a marker.
01Gn 31:46 Then Jacob said to his relatives, "Gather stones." And they took stones and made a mound, then ate there by the mound.
01Gn 31:47 Laban named the mound Jegar-sahadutha, but Jacob named it Galeed.
01Gn 31:48 Then Laban said, "This mound is a witness between me and you today." Therefore the place was called Galeed,
01Gn 31:49 and [also] Mizpah, for he said, "May the LORD watch between you and me when we are out of each other's sight.
01Gn 31:50 If you mistreat my daughters or take other wives, though no one is with us, understand that God will be a witness between you and me."
01Gn 31:51 Laban also said to Jacob, "Look at this mound and the marker I have set up between you and me.
01Gn 31:52 This mound is a witness and the marker is a witness that I will not pass beyond this mound to you, and you will not pass beyond this mound and this marker to do me harm.
01Gn 31:53 The God of Abraham, and the gods of Nahor-- the gods of their father-- will judge between us." And Jacob swore by the Fear of his father Isaac.
01Gn 31:54 Then Jacob offered a sacrifice on the mountain and invited his relatives to eat a meal. So they ate a meal and spent the night on the mountain.
01Gn 31:55  Laban got up early in the morning, kissed his grandsons and daughters, and blessed them. Then Laban left to return home.
01Gn 32:1 Jacob went on his way, and God's angels met him.
01Gn 32:2 When he saw them, Jacob said, "This is God's camp." So he called that place Mahanaim.
01Gn 32:3 Jacob sent messengers ahead of him to his brother Esau in the land of Seir, the country of Edom.
01Gn 32:4 He commanded them, "You are to say to my lord Esau, 'This is what your servant Jacob says. I have been staying with Laban and have been delayed until now.
01Gn 32:5 I have oxen, donkeys, flocks, male and female slaves. I have sent [this message] to inform my lord, in order to seek your favor.'"
01Gn 32:6 When the messengers returned to Jacob, they said, "We went to your brother Esau; he is coming to meet you-- and he has 400 men with him."
01Gn 32:7 Jacob was greatly afraid and distressed; he divided the people with him into two camps, along with the flocks, cattle, and camels.
01Gn 32:8 He thought, "If Esau comes to one camp and attacks it, the remaining one can escape."
01Gn 32:9 Then Jacob said, "God of my father Abraham and God of my father Isaac, the LORD who said to me, 'Go back to your land and to your family, and I will cause you to prosper,'
01Gn 32:10 I am unworthy of all the kindness and faithfulness You have shown Your servant. Indeed, I crossed over this Jordan with my staff, and now I have become two camps.
01Gn 32:11 Please rescue me from the hand of my brother Esau, for I am afraid of him; otherwise, he may come and attack me, the mothers, and their children.
01Gn 32:12 You have said, 'I will cause you to prosper, and I will make your offspring like the sand of the sea, which cannot be counted.'"
01Gn 32:13 He spent the night there and took part of what he had brought with him as a gift for his brother Esau:
01Gn 32:14 200 female goats, 20 male goats, 200 ewes, 20 rams,
01Gn 32:15 30 milk camels with their young, 40 cows, 10 bulls, 20 female donkeys, and 10 male donkeys.
01Gn 32:16 He entrusted them to his slaves as separate herds and said to them, "Go on ahead of me, and leave some distance between the herds."
01Gn 32:17 And he told the first one: "When my brother Esau meets you and asks, 'Who do you belong to? Where are you going? And whose [animals] are these ahead of you?'
01Gn 32:18 then tell him, 'They belong to your servant Jacob. They are a gift sent to my lord Esau. And look, he is behind us.'"
01Gn 32:19 He also told the second one, the third, and everyone who was walking behind the animals, "Say the same thing to Esau when you find him.
01Gn 32:20 You are to also say, 'Look, your servant Jacob is right behind us.' " For he thought, "I want to appease Esau with the gift that is going ahead of me. After that, I can face him, and perhaps he will forgive me."
01Gn 32:21 So the gift was sent on ahead of him while he remained in the camp that night.
01Gn 32:22 During the night Jacob got up and took his two wives, his two female slaves, and his 11 sons, and crossed the ford of Jabbok.
01Gn 32:23 He took them and brought them across the stream, along with all his possessions.
01Gn 32:24 Jacob was left alone, and a man wrestled with him until daybreak.
01Gn 32:25 When the man saw that He could not defeat him, He struck Jacob's hip as they wrestled and dislocated his hip socket.
01Gn 32:26 Then He said to Jacob, "Let Me go, for it is daybreak." But Jacob said, "I will not let You go unless You bless me."
01Gn 32:27 "What is your name?" the man asked. "Jacob!" he replied.
01Gn 32:28 "Your name will no longer be Jacob," He said. "It will be Israel because you have struggled with God and with men and have prevailed."
01Gn 32:29 Then Jacob asked Him, "Please tell me Your name." But He answered, "Why do you ask My name?" And He blessed him there.
01Gn 32:30 Jacob then named the place Peniel, "For," [he said,] "I have seen God face to face, and I have been delivered."
01Gn 32:31 The sun shone on him as he passed by Penuel-- limping on his hip.
01Gn 32:32 That is why, to this day, the Israelites don't eat the thigh muscle that is at the hip socket: because He struck Jacob's hip socket at the thigh muscle.
01Gn 33:1 Now Jacob looked up and saw Esau coming toward him with 400 men. So he divided the children among Leah, Rachel, and the two female slaves.
01Gn 33:2 He put the female slaves first, Leah and her sons next, and Rachel and Joseph last.
01Gn 33:3 He himself went on ahead and bowed to the ground seven times until he approached his brother.
01Gn 33:4 But Esau ran to meet him, hugged him, threw his arms around him, and kissed him. Then they wept.
01Gn 33:5 When Esau looked up and saw the women and children, he asked, "Who are these with you?" He answered, "The children God has graciously given your servant."
01Gn 33:6 Then the female slaves and their children approached [him] and bowed down.
01Gn 33:7 Leah and her children also approached and bowed down, and then Joseph and Rachel approached and bowed down.
01Gn 33:8 So Esau said, "What do you mean by this whole procession I met?" "To find favor with you, my lord," he answered.
01Gn 33:9 "I have enough, my brother," Esau replied. "Keep what you have."
01Gn 33:10 But Jacob said, "No, please! If I have found favor with you, take this gift from my hand. For indeed, I have seen your face, [and it is] like seeing God's face, since you have accepted me.
01Gn 33:11 Please take my present that was brought to you, because God has been gracious to me and I have everything I need." So Jacob urged him until he accepted.
01Gn 33:12 Then Esau said, "Let's move on, and I'll go ahead of you."
01Gn 33:13 Jacob replied, "My lord knows that the children are weak, and I have nursing sheep and cattle. If they are driven hard for one day, the whole herd will die.
01Gn 33:14 Let my lord go ahead of his servant. I will continue on slowly, at a pace suited to the livestock and the children, until I come to my lord at Seir."
01Gn 33:15 Esau said, "Let me leave some of my people with you." But he replied, "Why do that? Please indulge me, my lord."
01Gn 33:16 On that day Esau started on his way back to Seir,
01Gn 33:17 but Jacob went on to Succoth. He built a house for himself and stalls for his cattle; that is why the place was called Succoth.
01Gn 33:18 After Jacob came from Paddan-aram, he arrived safely at the Canaanite city of Shechem and camped in front of the city.
01Gn 33:19 He purchased a section of the field from the sons of Hamor, Shechem's father, for 100 qesitahs, where he had pitched his tent.
01Gn 33:20 And he set up an altar there and called it "God, the God of Israel."
01Gn 34:1 Dinah, Leah's daughter whom she bore to Jacob, went out to see some of the young women of the area.
01Gn 34:2 When Shechem son of Hamor the Hivite, a prince of the region, saw her, he took her and raped her.
01Gn 34:3 He became infatuated with Dinah, daughter of Jacob. He loved the young girl and spoke tenderly to her.
01Gn 34:4 "Get me this girl as a wife," he told his father Hamor.
01Gn 34:5 Jacob heard that Shechem had defiled his daughter Dinah, but since his sons were with his cattle in the field, he remained silent until they returned.
01Gn 34:6 Meanwhile, Shechem's father Hamor came to speak with Jacob.
01Gn 34:7 Jacob's sons returned from the field when they heard [about the incident] and were deeply grieved and angry. For Shechem had committed an outrage against Israel by sleeping with Jacob's daughter, and such a thing should not be done.
01Gn 34:8 Hamor said to Jacob's sons, "My son Shechem is strongly attracted to your daughter. Please give her to him as a wife.
01Gn 34:9 Intermarry with us; give your daughters to us, and take our daughters for yourselves.
01Gn 34:10 Live with us. The land is before you. Settle here, move about, and acquire property in it."
01Gn 34:11 Then Shechem said to Dinah's father and brothers, "Grant me this favor, and I'll give you whatever you say.
01Gn 34:12 Set for me the compensation and the gift; I'll give you whatever you ask me. Just give the girl to be my wife!"
01Gn 34:13 But Jacob's sons answered Shechem and his father Hamor deceitfully because he had defiled their sister Dinah.
01Gn 34:14 "We cannot do this thing," they said to them. "Giving our sister to an uncircumcised man is a disgrace to us.
01Gn 34:15 We will agree with you only on this condition: if all your males are circumcised as we are.
01Gn 34:16 Then we will give you our daughters, take your daughters for ourselves, live with you, and become one people.
01Gn 34:17 But if you will not listen to us and be circumcised, then we will take our daughter and go."
01Gn 34:18 Their words seemed good in the eyes of Hamor and his son Shechem.
01Gn 34:19 The young man did not delay doing this, because he was delighted with Jacob's daughter. Now he was the most important in all his father's house.
01Gn 34:20 So Hamor and his son Shechem went to the gate of their city and spoke to the men there.
01Gn 34:21 "These men are peaceful toward us," they said. "Let them live in our land and move about in it, for indeed, the region is large enough for them. Let us take their daughters as our wives and give our daughters to them.
01Gn 34:22 But the men will agree to live with us and be one people only on this condition: if all our men are circumcised as they are.
01Gn 34:23 Won't their herds, their possessions, and all their livestock become ours? Only let us agree with them, and they will live with us."
01Gn 34:24 All the able-bodied men listened to Hamor and his son Shechem, and all the able-bodied men were circumcised.
01Gn 34:25 On the third day, when they were still in pain, two of Jacob's sons, Simeon and Levi, Dinah's brothers, took their swords, went into the unsuspecting city, and killed every male.
01Gn 34:26 They killed Hamor and his son Shechem with their swords, took Dinah from Shechem's house, and went away.
01Gn 34:27 Jacob's [other] sons came to the slaughter and plundered the city because their sister had been defiled.
01Gn 34:28 They took their sheep, cattle, donkeys, and whatever was in the city and in the field.
01Gn 34:29 They captured all their possessions, children, and wives, and plundered everything in the houses.
01Gn 34:30 Then Jacob said to Simeon and Levi, "You have brought trouble on me, making me odious to the inhabitants of the land, the Canaanites and the Perizzites. We are few in number; if they unite against me and attack me, I and my household will be destroyed."
01Gn 34:31 But they answered, "Should he have treated our sister like a prostitute?"
01Gn 35:1 God said to Jacob, "Get up! Go to Bethel and settle there. Build an altar there to the God who appeared to you when you fled from your brother Esau."
01Gn 35:2 So Jacob said to his family and all who were with him, "Get rid of the foreign gods that are among you. Purify yourselves and change your clothes.
01Gn 35:3 We must get up and go to Bethel. I will build an altar there to the God who answered me in my day of distress. He has been with me everywhere I have gone."
01Gn 35:4 Then they gave Jacob all their foreign gods and their earrings, and Jacob hid them under the oak near Shechem.
01Gn 35:5 When they set out, a terror from God came over the cities around them, and they did not pursue Jacob's sons.
01Gn 35:6 So Jacob and all who were with him came to Luz (that is, Bethel) in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 35:7 Jacob built an altar there and called the place God of Bethel because it was there that God had revealed Himself to him when he was fleeing from his brother.
01Gn 35:8 Deborah, Rebekah's nurse, died and was buried under the oak south of Bethel. So Jacob named it Oak of Weeping.
01Gn 35:9 God appeared to Jacob again after he returned from Paddan-aram, and He blessed him.
01Gn 35:10 God said to him: Your name is Jacob; you will no longer be named Jacob, but Israel will be your name. So He named him Israel.
01Gn 35:11 God also said to him: I am God Almighty. Be fruitful and multiply. A nation, indeed an assembly of nations, will come from you, and kings will descend from you.
01Gn 35:12 The land that I gave to Abraham and Isaac I will give to you. And I will give the land to your descendants after you.
01Gn 35:13 Then God withdrew from him at the place where He had spoken to him.
01Gn 35:14 Jacob set up a marker at the place where He had spoken to him-- a stone marker. He poured a drink offering on it and anointed it with oil.
01Gn 35:15 Jacob named the place where God had spoken with him Bethel.
01Gn 35:16 They set out from Bethel. When they were still some distance from Ephrath, Rachel began to give birth, and her labor was difficult.
01Gn 35:17 During her difficult labor, the midwife said to her, "Don't be afraid, for this is another son for you."
01Gn 35:18 With her last breath-- for she was dying-- she named him Ben-oni, but his father called him Benjamin.
01Gn 35:19 So Rachel died and was buried on the way to Ephrath (that is, Bethlehem).
01Gn 35:20 Jacob set up a marker on her grave; it is the marker at Rachel's grave to this day.
01Gn 35:21 Israel set out again and pitched his tent beyond the tower at Eder.
01Gn 35:22 While Israel was living in that region, Reuben went in and slept with his father's concubine Bilhah, and Israel heard about it. Jacob had 12 sons:
01Gn 35:23 Leah's sons were Reuben (Jacob's firstborn), Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, and Zebulun.
01Gn 35:24 Rachel's sons were Joseph and Benjamin.
01Gn 35:25 The sons of Rachel's slave Bilhah were Dan and Naphtali.
01Gn 35:26 The sons of Leah's slave Zilpah were Gad and Asher. These are the sons of Jacob, who were born to him in Paddan-aram.
01Gn 35:27 Jacob came to his father Isaac at Mamre in Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron), where Abraham and Isaac had stayed.
01Gn 35:28 Isaac lived 180 years.
01Gn 35:29 He took his last breath and died, and was gathered to his people, old and full of days. His sons Esau and Jacob buried him.
01Gn 36:1 These are the family records of Esau (that is, Edom).
01Gn 36:2 Esau took his wives from the Canaanite women: Adah daughter of Elon the Hittite, Oholibamah daughter of Anah and granddaughter of Zibeon the Hivite;
01Gn 36:3 and Basemath daughter of Ishmael and sister of Nebaioth.
01Gn 36:4 Adah bore Eliphaz to Esau, Basemath bore Reuel,
01Gn 36:5 and Oholibamah bore Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. These were Esau's sons, who were born to him in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 36:6 Esau took his wives, sons, daughters, and all the people of his household, as well as his herds, all his livestock, and all the property he had acquired in Canaan; he went to a land away from his brother Jacob.
01Gn 36:7 For their possessions were too many [for them] to live together, and because of their herds, the land where they stayed could not support them.
01Gn 36:8 So Esau (that is, Edom) lived in the mountains of Seir.
01Gn 36:9 These are the family records of Esau, father of the Edomites in the mountains of Seir.
01Gn 36:10 These are the names of Esau's sons: Eliphaz son of Esau's wife Adah, and Reuel son of Esau's wife Basemath.
01Gn 36:11 The sons of Eliphaz were Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, and Kenaz.
01Gn 36:12 Timna, a concubine of Esau's son Eliphaz, bore Amalek to Eliphaz. These were the sons of Esau's wife Adah.
01Gn 36:13 These are Reuel's sons: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah. These were the sons of Esau's wife Basemath.
01Gn 36:14 These are the sons of Esau's wife Oholibamah daughter of Anah and granddaughter of Zibeon: She bore Jeush, Jalam, and Korah to Edom.
01Gn 36:15 These are the chiefs of Esau's sons: the sons of Eliphaz, Esau's firstborn: Chiefs Teman, Omar, Zepho, Kenaz,
01Gn 36:16 Korah, Gatam, and Amalek. These are the chiefs of Eliphaz in the land of Edom. These are the sons of Adah.
01Gn 36:17 These are the sons of Reuel, Esau's son: Chiefs Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah. These are the chiefs of Reuel in the land of Edom. These are the sons of Esau's wife Basemath.
01Gn 36:18 These are the sons of Esau's wife Oholibamah: Chiefs Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. These are the chiefs of Esau's wife Oholibamah daughter of Anah.
01Gn 36:19 These are the sons of Esau (that is, Edom), and these are their chiefs.
01Gn 36:20 These are the sons of Seir the Horite, the inhabitants of the land: Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah,
01Gn 36:21 Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan. These are the chiefs of the Horites, the sons of Seir, in the land of Edom.
01Gn 36:22 The sons of Lotan were Hori and Heman. Timna was Lotan's sister.
01Gn 36:23 These are Shobal's sons: Alvan, Manahath, Ebal, Shepho, and Onam.
01Gn 36:24 These are Zibeon's sons: Aiah and Anah. This was the Anah who found the hot springs in the wilderness while he was pasturing the donkeys of his father Zibeon.
01Gn 36:25 These are the children of Anah: Dishon and Oholibamah daughter of Anah.
01Gn 36:26 These are Dishon's sons: Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran, and Cheran.
01Gn 36:27 These are Ezer's sons: Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan.
01Gn 36:28 These are Dishan's sons: Uz and Aran.
01Gn 36:29 These are the chiefs of the Horites: Chiefs Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah,
01Gn 36:30 Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan. These are the chiefs of the Horites, according to their divisions, in the land of Seir.
01Gn 36:31 These are the kings who ruled in the land of Edom before any king ruled over the Israelites:
01Gn 36:32 Bela son of Beor ruled in Edom; the name of his city was Dinhabah.
01Gn 36:33 When Bela died, Jobab son of Zerah from Bozrah ruled in his place.
01Gn 36:34 When Jobab died, Husham from the land of the Temanites ruled in his place.
01Gn 36:35 When Husham died, Hadad son of Bedad ruled in his place. He defeated Midian in the field of Moab; the name of his city was Avith.
01Gn 36:36 When Hadad died, Samlah from Masrekah ruled in his place.
01Gn 36:37 When Samlah died, Shaul from Rehoboth-on-the-River ruled in his place.
01Gn 36:38 When Shaul died, Baal-hanan son of Achbor ruled in his place.
01Gn 36:39 When Baal-hanan son of Achbor died, Hadar ruled in his place. His city was Pau, and his wife's name was Mehetabel daughter of Matred daughter of Me-zahab.
01Gn 36:40 These are the names of Esau's chiefs, according to their families and their localities, by their names: Chiefs Timna, Alvah, Jetheth,
01Gn 36:41 Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon,
01Gn 36:42 Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar,
01Gn 36:43 Magdiel, and Iram. These are Edom's chiefs, according to their settlements in the land they possessed. Esau was father of the Edomites.
01Gn 37:1 Jacob lived in the land where his father had stayed, the land of Canaan.
01Gn 37:2 These are the family records of Jacob. At 17 years of age, Joseph tended sheep with his brothers. The young man [was working] with the sons of Bilhah and Zilpah, his father's wives, and he brought a bad report about them to their father.
01Gn 37:3 Now Israel loved Joseph more than his other sons because Joseph was a son [born to him] in his old age, and he made a robe of many colors for him.
01Gn 37:4 When his brothers saw that their father loved him more than all his brothers, they hated him and could not bring themselves to speak peaceably to him.
01Gn 37:5 Then Joseph had a dream. When he told it to his brothers, they hated him even more.
01Gn 37:6 He said to them, "Listen to this dream I had:
01Gn 37:7 There we were, binding sheaves of grain in the field. Suddenly my sheaf stood up, and your sheaves gathered around it and bowed down to my sheaf."
01Gn 37:8 "Are you really going to reign over us?" his brothers asked him. "Are you really going to rule us?" So they hated him even more because of his dream and what he had said.
01Gn 37:9 Then he had another dream and told it to his brothers. "Look," he said, "I had another dream, and this time the sun, moon, and 11 stars were bowing down to me."
01Gn 37:10 He told his father and brothers, but his father rebuked him. "What kind of dream is this that you have had?" he said. "Are your mother and brothers and I going to bow down to the ground before you?"
01Gn 37:11 His brothers were jealous of him, but his father kept the matter [in mind].
01Gn 37:12 His brothers had gone to pasture their father's flocks at Shechem.
01Gn 37:13 Israel said to Joseph, "Your brothers, you know, are pasturing [the flocks] at Shechem. Get ready. I'm sending you to them." "I'm ready," Joseph replied.
01Gn 37:14 Then Israel said to him, "Go and see how your brothers and the flocks are doing, and bring word back to me." So he sent him from the valley of Hebron, and he went to Shechem.
01Gn 37:15 A man found him there, wandering in the field, and asked him, "What are you looking for?"
01Gn 37:16 "I'm looking for my brothers," Joseph said. "Can you tell me where they are pasturing [their flocks]?"
01Gn 37:17 "They've moved on from here," the man said. "I heard them say, 'Let's go to Dothan.' " So Joseph set out after his brothers and found them at Dothan.
01Gn 37:18 They saw him in the distance, and before he had reached them, they plotted to kill him.
01Gn 37:19 They said to one another, "Here comes that dreamer!
01Gn 37:20 Come on, let's kill him and throw him into one of the pits. We can say that a vicious animal ate him. Then we'll see what becomes of his dreams!"
01Gn 37:21 When Reuben heard this, he tried to save him from them. He said, "Let's not take his life."
01Gn 37:22 Reuben also said to them, "Don't shed blood. Throw him into this pit in the wilderness, but don't lay a hand on him"-- intending to rescue him from their hands and return him to his father.
01Gn 37:23 When Joseph came to his brothers, they stripped off his robe, the robe of many colors that he had on.
01Gn 37:24 Then they took him and threw him into the pit. The pit was empty; there was no water in it.
01Gn 37:25 Then they sat down to eat a meal. They looked up, and there was a caravan of Ishmaelites coming from Gilead. Their camels were carrying aromatic gum, balsam, and resin, going down to Egypt.
01Gn 37:26 Then Judah said to his brothers, "What do we gain if we kill our brother and cover up his blood?
01Gn 37:27 Come, let's sell him to the Ishmaelites and not lay a hand on him, for he is our brother, our [own] flesh." His brothers agreed.
01Gn 37:28 When Midianite traders passed by, they pulled Joseph out of the pit and sold him for 20 pieces of silver to the Ishmaelites, who took Joseph to Egypt.
01Gn 37:29 When Reuben returned to the pit and saw that Joseph was not there, he tore his clothes.
01Gn 37:30 He went back to his brothers and said, "The boy is gone! What am I going to do?"
01Gn 37:31 So they took Joseph's robe, slaughtered a young goat, and dipped the robe in its blood.
01Gn 37:32 They sent the robe of many colors to their father and said, "We found this. Examine it. Is it your son's robe or not?"
01Gn 37:33 His father recognized it. "It is my son's robe," he said. "A vicious animal has devoured him. Joseph has been torn to pieces!"
01Gn 37:34 Then Jacob tore his clothes, put sackcloth around his waist, and mourned for his son many days.
01Gn 37:35 All his sons and daughters tried to comfort him, but he refused to be comforted. "No," he said. "I will go down to Sheol to my son, mourning." And his father wept for him.
01Gn 37:36 Meanwhile, the Midianites sold Joseph in Egypt to Potiphar, an officer of Pharaoh and the captain of the guard.
01Gn 38:1 At that time Judah left his brothers and settled near an Adullamite named Hirah.
01Gn 38:2 There Judah saw the daughter of a Canaanite named Shua; he took her as a wife and slept with her.
01Gn 38:3 She conceived and gave birth to a son, and he named him Er.
01Gn 38:4 She conceived again, gave birth to a son, and named him Onan.
01Gn 38:5 She gave birth to another son and named him Shelah. It was at Chezib that she gave birth to him.
01Gn 38:6 Judah got a wife for Er, his firstborn, and her name was Tamar.
01Gn 38:7 Now Er, Judah's firstborn, was evil in the LORD's sight, and the LORD put him to death.
01Gn 38:8 Then Judah said to Onan, "Sleep with your brother's wife. Perform your duty as her brother-in-law and produce offspring for your brother."
01Gn 38:9 But Onan knew that the offspring would not be his; so whenever he slept with his brother's wife, he released his semen on the ground so that he would not produce offspring for his brother.
01Gn 38:10 What he did was evil in the LORD's sight, so He put him to death also.
01Gn 38:11 Then Judah said to his daughter-in-law Tamar, "Remain a widow in your father's house until my son Shelah grows up." For he thought, "He might die too, like his brother." So Tamar went to live in her father's house.
01Gn 38:12 After a long time Judah's wife, the daughter of Shua, died. When Judah had finished mourning, he and his friend Hirah the Adullamite went up to Timnah to the sheepshearers.
01Gn 38:13 Tamar was told, "Your father-in-law is going up to Timnah to shear his sheep."
01Gn 38:14 So she took off her widow's clothes, veiled [her face], covered herself, and sat at the entrance to Enaim, which is on the way to Timnah. For she saw that, though Shelah had grown up, she had not been given to him as a wife.
01Gn 38:15 When Judah saw her, he thought she was a prostitute, for she had covered her face.
01Gn 38:16 He went over to her and said, "Come, let me sleep with you," for he did not know that she was his daughter-in-law. She said, "What will you give me for sleeping with me?"
01Gn 38:17 "I will send you a young goat from my flock," he replied. But she said, "Only if you leave something [with me] until you send it."
01Gn 38:18 "What should I give you?" he asked. She answered, "Your signet ring, your cord, and the staff in your hand." So he gave them to her and slept with her, and she got pregnant by him.
01Gn 38:19 She got up and left, then removed her veil and put her widow's clothes back on.
01Gn 38:20 When Judah sent the young goat by his friend the Adullamite in order to get back the items he had left with the woman, he could not find her.
01Gn 38:21 He asked the men of the place, "Where is the cult prostitute who was beside the road at Enaim?" "There has been no cult prostitute here," they answered.
01Gn 38:22 So the Adullamite returned to Judah, saying, "I couldn't find her, and furthermore, the men of the place said, 'There has been no cult prostitute here.'"
01Gn 38:23 Judah replied, "Let her keep [the items] for herself; otherwise we will become a laughingstock. After all, I did send this young goat, but you couldn't find [her]."
01Gn 38:24 About three months later Judah was told, "Your daughter-in-law has been acting like a prostitute, and now she is pregnant." "Bring her out!" Judah said. "Let her be burned [to death]!"
01Gn 38:25 As she was being brought out, she sent her father-in-law [this message]: "I am pregnant by the man to whom these items belong." And she added, "Examine them. Whose signet ring, cord, and staff are these?"
01Gn 38:26 Judah recognized [them] and said, "She is more in the right than I, since I did not give her to my son Shelah." And he did not know her intimately again.
01Gn 38:27 When the time came for her to give birth, there were twins in her womb.
01Gn 38:28 As she was giving birth, one of them put out his hand, and the midwife took it and tied a scarlet [thread] around it, announcing, "This one came out first."
01Gn 38:29 But then he pulled his hand back, and his brother came out. Then she said, "You have broken out [first]!" So he was named Perez.
01Gn 38:30 Then his brother, who had the scarlet [thread] tied to his hand, came out, and was named Zerah.
01Gn 39:1 Now Joseph had been taken to Egypt. An Egyptian [named] Potiphar, an officer of Pharaoh and the captain of the guard, bought him from the Ishmaelites who had brought him there.
01Gn 39:2 The LORD was with Joseph, and he became a successful man, serving in the household of his Egyptian master.
01Gn 39:3 When his master saw that the LORD was with him and that the LORD made everything he did successful,
01Gn 39:4 Joseph found favor in his master's sight and became his personal attendant. Potiphar also put him in charge of his household and placed all that he owned under his authority.
01Gn 39:5 From the time that he put him in charge of his household and of all that he owned, the LORD blessed the Egyptian's house because of Joseph. The LORD's blessing was on all that he owned, in his house and in his fields.
01Gn 39:6 He left all that he owned under Joseph's authority; he did not concern himself with anything except the food he ate. Now Joseph was well-built and handsome.
01Gn 39:7 After some time his master's wife looked longingly at Joseph and said, "Sleep with me."
01Gn 39:8 But he refused and said to his master's wife, "Look, my master does not concern himself with anything in his house, and he has put all that he owns under my authority.
01Gn 39:9 No one in this house is greater than I am. He has withheld nothing from me except you, because you are his wife. So how could I do such a great evil and sin against God?"
01Gn 39:10 Although she spoke to Joseph day after day, he refused to go to bed with her.
01Gn 39:11 Now one day he went into the house to do his work, and none of the household servants was there.
01Gn 39:12 She grabbed him by his garment and said, "Sleep with me!" But leaving his garment in her hand, he escaped and ran outside.
01Gn 39:13 When she realized that he had left his garment with her and had run outside,
01Gn 39:14 she called the household servants. "Look," she said to them, "my husband brought a Hebrew man to us to make fun of us. He came to me so he could sleep with me, and I screamed as loud as I could.
01Gn 39:15 When he heard me screaming for help, he left his garment with me and ran outside."
01Gn 39:16 She put Joseph's garment beside her until his master came home.
01Gn 39:17 Then she told him the same story: "The Hebrew slave you brought to us came to me to make fun of me,
01Gn 39:18 but when I screamed for help, he left his garment with me and ran outside."
01Gn 39:19 When his master heard the story his wife told him-- "These are the things your slave did to me"-- he was furious
01Gn 39:20 and had him thrown into prison, where the king's prisoners were confined. So Joseph was there in prison.
01Gn 39:21 But the LORD was with Joseph and extended kindness to him. He granted him favor in the eyes of the prison warden.
01Gn 39:22 The warden put all the prisoners who were in the prison under Joseph's authority, and he was responsible for everything that was done there.
01Gn 39:23 The warden did not bother with anything under Joseph's authority, because the LORD was with him, and the LORD made everything that he did successful.
01Gn 40:1 After this, the king of Egypt's cupbearer and his baker offended their master, the king of Egypt.
01Gn 40:2 Pharaoh was angry with his two officers, the chief cupbearer and the chief baker,
01Gn 40:3 and put them in custody in the house of the captain of the guard, in the prison where Joseph was confined.
01Gn 40:4 The captain of the guard assigned Joseph to them, and he became their personal attendant. And they were in custody for some time.
01Gn 40:5 The cupbearer and the baker of the king of Egypt, who were confined in the prison, each had a dream. Both had a dream on the same night, and each dream had its own meaning.
01Gn 40:6 When Joseph came to them in the morning, he saw that they looked distraught.
01Gn 40:7 So he asked Pharaoh's officers who were in custody with him in his master's house, "Why are your faces sad today?"
01Gn 40:8 "We had dreams," they said to him, "but there is no one to interpret them." Then Joseph said to them, "Don't interpretations belong to God? Tell me [your dreams]."
01Gn 40:9 So the chief cupbearer told his dream to Joseph: "In my dream there was a vine in front of me.
01Gn 40:10 On the vine were three branches. As soon as it budded, its blossoms came out and its clusters ripened into grapes.
01Gn 40:11 Pharaoh's cup was in my hand, and I took the grapes, squeezed them into Pharaoh's cup, and placed the cup in Pharaoh's hand."
01Gn 40:12 "This is its interpretation," Joseph said to him. "The three branches are three days.
01Gn 40:13 In just three days Pharaoh will lift up your head and restore you to your position. You will put Pharaoh's cup in his hand the way you used to when you were his cupbearer.
01Gn 40:14 But when all goes well for you, remember that I was with you. Please show kindness to me by mentioning me to Pharaoh, and get me out of this prison.
01Gn 40:15 For I was kidnapped from the land of the Hebrews, and even here I have done nothing that they should put me in the dungeon."
01Gn 40:16 When the chief baker saw that the interpretation was positive, he said to Joseph, "I also had a dream. Three baskets of white bread were on my head.
01Gn 40:17 In the top basket were all sorts of baked goods for Pharaoh, but the birds were eating them out of the basket on my head."
01Gn 40:18 "This is its interpretation," Joseph replied. "The three baskets are three days.
01Gn 40:19 In just three days Pharaoh will lift up your head-- from off you-- and hang you on a tree. Then the birds will eat the flesh from your body."
01Gn 40:20 On the third day, which was Pharaoh's birthday, he gave a feast for all his servants. He lifted up the heads of the chief cupbearer and the chief baker:
01Gn 40:21 he restored the chief cupbearer to his position as cupbearer, and he placed the cup in Pharaoh's hand;
01Gn 40:22 but he hanged the chief baker, just as Joseph had explained to them.
01Gn 40:23 Yet the chief cupbearer did not remember Joseph; he forgot him.
01Gn 41:1 Two years later Pharaoh had a dream: He was standing beside the Nile,
01Gn 41:2 when seven healthy-looking, well-fed cows came up from the Nile and began to graze among the reeds.
01Gn 41:3 After them, seven other cows, sickly and thin, came up from the Nile and stood beside those cows along the bank of the Nile.
01Gn 41:4 The sickly, thin cows ate the healthy, well-fed cows. Then Pharaoh woke up.
01Gn 41:5 He fell asleep and dreamed a second time: Seven heads of grain, full and good, came up on one stalk.
01Gn 41:6 After them, seven heads of grain, thin and scorched by the east wind, sprouted up.
01Gn 41:7 The thin heads of grain swallowed up the seven full, good ones. Then Pharaoh woke up, and it was only a dream.
01Gn 41:8 When morning came, he was troubled, so he summoned all the magicians of Egypt and all its wise men. Pharaoh told them his dreams, but no one could interpret them for him.
01Gn 41:9 Then the chief cupbearer said to Pharaoh, "Today I remember my faults.
01Gn 41:10 Pharaoh had been angry with his servants, and he put me and the chief baker in the custody of the captain of the guard.
01Gn 41:11 He and I had dreams on the same night; each dream had its own meaning.
01Gn 41:12 Now a young Hebrew, a slave of the captain of the guards, was with us there. We told him our dreams, he interpreted our dreams for us, and each had its own interpretation.
01Gn 41:13 It turned out just the way he interpreted them to us: I was restored to my position, and the other man was hanged."
01Gn 41:14 Then Pharaoh sent for Joseph, and they quickly brought him from the dungeon. He shaved, changed his clothes, and went to Pharaoh.
01Gn 41:15 Pharaoh said to Joseph, "I have had a dream, and no one can interpret it. But I have heard it said about you that you can hear a dream and interpret it."
01Gn 41:16 "I am not able to," Joseph answered Pharaoh. "It is God who will give Pharaoh a favorable answer."
01Gn 41:17 So Pharaoh said to Joseph: "In my dream I was standing on the bank of the Nile,
01Gn 41:18 when seven well-fed, healthy-looking cows came up from the Nile and began to graze among the reeds.
01Gn 41:19 After them, seven other cows-- ugly, very sickly, and thin-- came up. I've never seen such ugly ones as these in all the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:20 Then the thin, ugly cows ate the first seven well-fed cows.
01Gn 41:21 When they had devoured them, you could not tell that they had devoured them; their appearance was as bad as it had been before. Then I woke up.
01Gn 41:22 In my dream I had also seen seven heads of grain, full and good, coming up on one stalk.
01Gn 41:23 After them, seven heads of grain-- withered, thin, and scorched by the east wind-- sprouted up.
01Gn 41:24 The thin heads of grain swallowed the seven full ones. I told this to the magicians, but no one can tell me what it means."
01Gn 41:25 Then Joseph said to Pharaoh, "Pharaoh's dreams mean the same thing. God has revealed to Pharaoh what He is about to do.
01Gn 41:26 The seven good cows are seven years, and the seven good heads are seven years. The dreams mean the same thing.
01Gn 41:27 The seven thin, ugly cows that came up after them are seven years, and the seven worthless, scorched heads of grain are seven years of famine.
01Gn 41:28 "It is just as I told Pharaoh: God has shown Pharaoh what He is about to do.
01Gn 41:29 Seven years of great abundance are coming throughout the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:30 After them, seven years of famine will take place, and all the abundance in the land of Egypt will be forgotten. The famine will devastate the land.
01Gn 41:31 The abundance in the land will not be remembered because of the famine that follows it, for the famine will be very severe.
01Gn 41:32 Because the dream was given twice to Pharaoh, it means that the matter has been determined by God, and He will soon carry it out.
01Gn 41:33 "So now, let Pharaoh look for a discerning and wise man and set him over the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:34 Let Pharaoh do this: Let him appoint overseers over the land and take one-fifth [of the harvest] of the land of Egypt during the seven years of abundance.
01Gn 41:35 Let them gather all the [excess] food during these good years that are coming, store the grain under Pharaoh's authority as food in the cities, and preserve [it].
01Gn 41:36 The food will be a reserve for the land during the seven years of famine that will take place in the land of Egypt. Then the country will not be wiped out by the famine."
01Gn 41:37 The proposal pleased Pharaoh and all his servants.
01Gn 41:38 Then Pharaoh said to his servants, "Can we find anyone like this, a man who has the spirit of God in him?"
01Gn 41:39 So Pharaoh said to Joseph, "Since God has made all this known to you, there is no one as intelligent and wise as you.
01Gn 41:40 You will be over my house, and all my people will obey your commands. Only with regard to the throne will I be greater than you."
01Gn 41:41 Pharaoh also said to Joseph, "See, I am placing you over all the land of Egypt."
01Gn 41:42 Pharaoh removed his signet ring from his hand and put it on Joseph's hand, clothed him with fine linen garments, and placed a gold chain around his neck.
01Gn 41:43 He had Joseph ride in his second chariot, and [servants] called out before him, "Abrek!" So he placed him over all the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:44 Pharaoh said to Joseph, "I am Pharaoh, but without your permission no one will be able to raise his hand or foot in all the land of Egypt."
01Gn 41:45 Pharaoh gave Joseph the name Zaphenath-paneah and gave him a wife, Asenath daughter of Potiphera, priest at On. And Joseph went throughout the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:46 Joseph was 30 years old when he entered the service of Pharaoh king of Egypt. Joseph left Pharaoh's presence and traveled throughout the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:47 During the seven years of abundance the land produced outstanding harvests.
01Gn 41:48 Joseph gathered all the [excess] food in the land of Egypt during the seven years and placed it in the cities. He placed the food in every city from the fields around it.
01Gn 41:49 So Joseph stored up grain in such abundance-- like the sand of the sea-- that he stopped measuring it because it was beyond measure.
01Gn 41:50 Two sons were born to Joseph before the years of famine arrived. Asenath daughter of Potiphera, priest at On, bore [them] to him.
01Gn 41:51 Joseph named the firstborn Manasseh, meaning, "God has made me forget all my hardship in my father's house."
01Gn 41:52 And the second son he named Ephraim, meaning, "God has made me fruitful in the land of my affliction."
01Gn 41:53 Then the seven years of abundance in the land of Egypt came to an end,
01Gn 41:54 and the seven years of famine began, just as Joseph had said. There was famine in every country, but throughout the land of Egypt there was food.
01Gn 41:55 Extreme hunger came to all the land of Egypt, and the people cried out to Pharaoh for food. Pharaoh told all Egypt, "Go to Joseph and do whatever he tells you."
01Gn 41:56 Because the famine had spread across the whole country, Joseph opened up [all the storehouses] and sold grain to the Egyptians, for the famine was severe in the land of Egypt.
01Gn 41:57 The whole world came to Joseph in Egypt to buy grain, for the famine was severe all over the earth.
01Gn 42:1 When Jacob learned that there was grain in Egypt, he said to his sons, "Why do you keep looking at each other?
01Gn 42:2 Listen," he went on, "I have heard there is grain in Egypt. Go down there and buy some for us so that we will live and not die."
01Gn 42:3 So 10 of Joseph's brothers went down to buy grain from Egypt.
01Gn 42:4 But Jacob did not send Joseph's brother Benjamin with his brothers, for he thought, "Something might happen to him."
01Gn 42:5 The sons of Israel were among those who came to buy grain, for the famine was in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 42:6 Joseph was in charge of the country; he sold grain to all its people. His brothers came and bowed down before him with their faces to the ground.
01Gn 42:7 When Joseph saw his brothers, he recognized them, but he treated them like strangers and spoke harshly to them. "Where do you come from?" he asked. "From the land of Canaan to buy food," they replied.
01Gn 42:8 Although Joseph recognized his brothers, they did not recognize him.
01Gn 42:9 Joseph remembered his dreams about them and said to them, "You are spies. You have come to see the weakness of the land."
01Gn 42:10 "No, my lord. Your servants have come to buy food," they said.
01Gn 42:11 "We are all sons of one man. We are honest; your servants are not spies."
01Gn 42:12 "No," he said to them. "You have come to see the weakness of the land."
01Gn 42:13 But they replied, "We, your servants, were 12 brothers, the sons of one man in the land of Canaan. The youngest is now with our father, and one is no longer living."
01Gn 42:14 Then Joseph said to them, "I have spoken: 'You are spies!'
01Gn 42:15 This is how you will be tested: As surely as Pharaoh lives, you will not leave this place unless your youngest brother comes here.
01Gn 42:16 Send one of your number to get your brother. The rest of you will be imprisoned so that your words can be tested to see if they are true. If they are not, then as surely as Pharaoh lives, you are spies!"
01Gn 42:17 So Joseph imprisoned them together for three days.
01Gn 42:18 On the third day Joseph said to them, "I fear God-- do this and you will live.
01Gn 42:19 If you are honest men, let one of you be confined to the guardhouse, while the rest of you go and take grain [to relieve] the hunger of your households.
01Gn 42:20 Bring your youngest brother to me so that your words can be confirmed; then you won't die." And they consented to this.
01Gn 42:21 Then they said to each other, "It is plain that we are being punished for what we did to our brother. We saw his deep distress when he pleaded with us, but we would not listen. That is why this trouble has come to us."
01Gn 42:22 But Reuben replied: "Didn't I tell you not to harm the boy? But you wouldn't listen. Now we must account for his blood!"
01Gn 42:23 They did not realize that Joseph understood them, since there was an interpreter between them.
01Gn 42:24 He turned away from them and wept. Then he turned back and spoke to them. He took Simeon from them and had him bound before their eyes.
01Gn 42:25 Joseph then gave orders to fill their containers with grain, return each man's money to his sack, and give them provisions for their journey. This order was carried out.
01Gn 42:26 They loaded the grain on their donkeys and left there.
01Gn 42:27 At the place where they lodged for the night, one of them opened his sack to get feed for his donkey, and he saw his money there at the top of the bag.
01Gn 42:28 He said to his brothers, "My money has been returned! It's here in my bag." Their hearts sank. Trembling, they turned to one another and said, "What is this that God has done to us?"
01Gn 42:29 When they reached their father Jacob in the land of Canaan, they told him all that had happened to them:
01Gn 42:30 "The man who is the lord of the country spoke harshly to us and accused us of spying on the country.
01Gn 42:31 But we told him: We are honest men and not spies.
01Gn 42:32 We were 12 brothers, sons of the same father. One is no longer living, and the youngest is now with our father in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 42:33 The man who is the lord of the country said to us, 'This is how I will know if you are honest men: Leave one brother with me, take [food to relieve] the hunger of your households, and go.
01Gn 42:34 Bring back your youngest brother to me, and I will know that you are not spies but honest men. I will then give your brother back to you, and you can trade in the country.'"
01Gn 42:35 As they began emptying their sacks, there in each man's sack was his bag of money! When they and their father saw their bags of money, they were afraid.
01Gn 42:36 Their father Jacob said to them, "You have deprived me of my sons. Joseph is gone and Simeon is gone. Now you want to take Benjamin. Everything happens to me!"
01Gn 42:37 Then Reuben said to his father, "You can kill my two sons if I don't bring him back to you. Put him in my care, and I will return him to you."
01Gn 42:38 But Jacob answered, "My son will not go down with you, for his brother is dead and he alone is left. If anything happens to him on your journey, you will bring my gray hairs down to Sheol in sorrow."
01Gn 43:1 Now the famine in the land was severe.
01Gn 43:2 When they had used up the grain they had brought back from Egypt, their father said to them, "Go back and buy us some food."
01Gn 43:3 But Judah said to him, "The man specifically warned us: 'You will not see me again unless your brother is with you.'
01Gn 43:4 If you will send our brother with us, we will go down and buy food for you.
01Gn 43:5 But if you will not send him, we will not go, for the man said to us, 'You will not see me again unless your brother is with you.'"
01Gn 43:6 "Why did you cause me so much trouble?" Israel asked. "Why did you tell the man that you had another brother?"
01Gn 43:7 They answered, "The man kept asking about us and our family: 'Is your father still alive? Do you have [another] brother?' And we answered him accordingly. How could we know that he would say, 'Bring your brother here'?"
01Gn 43:8 Then Judah said to his father Israel, "Send the boy with me. We will be on our way so that we may live, and not die-- neither we, nor you, nor our children.
01Gn 43:9 I will be responsible for him. You can hold me personally accountable! If I do not bring him back to you and set him before you, I will be guilty before you forever.
01Gn 43:10 If we had not wasted time, we could have come back twice by now."
01Gn 43:11 Then their father Israel said to them, "If it must be so, then do this: Put some of the best products of the land in your packs and take them down to the man as a gift-- some balsam and some honey, aromatic gum and resin, pistachios and almonds.
01Gn 43:12 Take twice as much money with you. Return the money that was returned [to you] in the top of your bags. Perhaps it was a mistake.
01Gn 43:13 Take your brother also, and go back at once to the man.
01Gn 43:14 May God Almighty cause the man to be merciful to you so that he will release your other brother and Benjamin to you. As for me, if I am deprived of my sons, then I am deprived."
01Gn 43:15 The men took this gift, double the amount of money, and Benjamin. They made their way down to Egypt and stood before Joseph.
01Gn 43:16 When Joseph saw Benjamin with them, he said to his steward, "Take the men to [my] house. Slaughter an animal and prepare it, for they will eat with me at noon."
01Gn 43:17 The man did as Joseph had said and brought them to Joseph's house.
01Gn 43:18 But the men were afraid because they were taken to Joseph's house. They said, "We have been brought here because of the money that was returned in our bags the first time. They intend to overpower us, seize us, make us slaves, and take our donkeys."
01Gn 43:19 So they approached Joseph's steward and spoke to him at the doorway of the house.
01Gn 43:20 They said, "Sir, we really did come down here the first time only to buy food.
01Gn 43:21 When we came to the place where we lodged for the night and opened our bags of grain, each one's money was at the top of his bag! It was the full amount of our money, and we have brought it back with us.
01Gn 43:22 We have brought additional money with us to buy food. We don't know who put our money in the bags."
01Gn 43:23 Then the steward said, "May you be well. Don't be afraid. Your God and the God of your father must have put treasure in your bags. I received your money." Then he brought Simeon out to them.
01Gn 43:24 The man brought the men into Joseph's house, gave them water to wash their feet, and got feed for their donkeys.
01Gn 43:25 Since the men had heard that they were going to eat a meal there, they prepared their gift for Joseph's arrival at noon.
01Gn 43:26 When Joseph came home, they brought him the gift they had carried into the house, and they bowed to the ground before him.
01Gn 43:27 He asked if they were well, and he said, "How is your elderly father that you told me about? Is he still alive?"
01Gn 43:28 They answered, "Your servant our father is well. He is still alive." And they bowed down to honor him.
01Gn 43:29 When he looked up and saw his brother Benjamin, his mother's son, he asked, "Is this your youngest brother that you told me about?" Then he said, "May God be gracious to you, my son."
01Gn 43:30 Joseph hurried out because he was overcome with emotion for his brother, and he was about to weep. He went into an inner room to weep.
01Gn 43:31 Then he washed his face and came out. Regaining his composure, he said, "Serve the meal."
01Gn 43:32 They served him by himself, his brothers by themselves, and the Egyptians who were eating with him by themselves, because Egyptians could not eat with Hebrews, since that is abhorrent to them.
01Gn 43:33 They were seated before him in order by age, from the firstborn to the youngest. The men looked at each other in astonishment.
01Gn 43:34 Portions were served to them from Joseph's table, and Benjamin's portion was five times larger than any of theirs. They drank, and they got drunk with Joseph.
01Gn 44:1 Then Joseph commanded his steward: "Fill the men's bags with as much food as they can carry, and put each one's money at the top of his bag.
01Gn 44:2 Put my cup, the silver one, at the top of the youngest one's bag, along with his grain money." So he did as Joseph told him.
01Gn 44:3 At morning light, the men were sent off with their donkeys.
01Gn 44:4 They had not gone very far from the city when Joseph said to his steward, "Get up. Pursue the men, and when you overtake them, say to them, 'Why have you repaid evil for good?
01Gn 44:5 Isn't this the cup that my master drinks from and uses for divination? What you have done is wrong!'"
01Gn 44:6 When he overtook them, he said these words to them.
01Gn 44:7 They said to him, "Why does my lord say these things? Your servants could not possibly do such a thing.
01Gn 44:8 We even brought back to you from the land of Canaan the money we found at the top of our bags. How could we steal gold and silver from your master's house?
01Gn 44:9 If any of us is found to have it, he must die, and we also will become my lord's slaves."
01Gn 44:10 The steward replied, "What you have said is proper, but only the one who is found to have it will be my slave, and the rest of you will be blameless."
01Gn 44:11 So each one quickly lowered his sack to the ground and opened it.
01Gn 44:12 The steward searched, beginning with the oldest and ending with the youngest, and the cup was found in Benjamin's sack.
01Gn 44:13 Then they tore their clothes, and each one loaded his donkey and returned to the city.
01Gn 44:14 When Judah and his brothers reached Joseph's house, he was still there. They fell to the ground before him.
01Gn 44:15 "What is this you have done?" Joseph said to them. "Didn't you know that a man like me could uncover the truth by divination?"
01Gn 44:16 "What can we say to my lord?" Judah replied. "How can we plead? How can we justify ourselves? God has exposed your servants' iniquity. We are now my lord's slaves-- both we and the one in whose possession the cup was found."
01Gn 44:17 Then Joseph said, "I swear that I will not do this. The man in whose possession the cup was found will be my slave. The rest of you can go in peace to your father."
01Gn 44:18 But Judah approached him and said, "Sir, please let your servant speak personally to my lord. Do not be angry with your servant, for you are like Pharaoh.
01Gn 44:19 My lord asked his servants, 'Do you have a father or a brother?'
01Gn 44:20 and we answered my lord, 'We have an elderly father and a young brother, the child of his old age. The boy's brother is dead. He is the only one of his mother's sons left, and his father loves him.'
01Gn 44:21 Then you said to your servants, 'Bring him to me so that I can see him.'
01Gn 44:22 But we said to my lord, 'The boy cannot leave his father. If he were to leave, his father would die.'
01Gn 44:23 Then you said to your servants, 'If your younger brother does not come down with you, you will not see me again.'
01Gn 44:24 "This is what happened when we went back to your servant my father: We reported your words to him.
01Gn 44:25 But our father said, 'Go again, and buy us some food.'
01Gn 44:26 We told him, 'We cannot go down unless our younger brother goes with us. But if our younger brother isn't with us, we cannot see the man.'
01Gn 44:27 Your servant my father said to us, 'You know that my wife bore me two sons.
01Gn 44:28 One left-- I said that he must have been torn to pieces-- and I have never seen him again.
01Gn 44:29 If you also take this one from me and anything happens to him, you will bring my gray hairs down to Sheol in sorrow.'
01Gn 44:30 "So, if I come to your servant my father and the boy is not with us-- his life is wrapped up with the boy's life--
01Gn 44:31 when he sees that the boy is not with us, he will die. Then your servants will have brought the gray hairs of your servant our father down to Sheol in sorrow.
01Gn 44:32 Your servant became accountable to my father for the boy, saying, 'If I do not return him to you, I will always bear the guilt for sinning against [you,] my father.'
01Gn 44:33 Now please let your servant remain here as my lord's slave, in place of the boy. Let him go back with his brothers.
01Gn 44:34 For how can I go back to my father without the boy? I could not bear to see the grief that would overwhelm my father."
01Gn 45:1 Joseph could no longer keep his composure in front of all his attendants, so he called out, "Send everyone away from me!" No one was with him when he revealed his identity to his brothers.
01Gn 45:2 But he wept so loudly that the Egyptians heard it, and also Pharaoh's household heard it.
01Gn 45:3 Joseph said to his brothers, "I am Joseph! Is my father still living?" But his brothers were too terrified to answer him.
01Gn 45:4 Then Joseph said to his brothers, "Please, come near me," and they came near. "I am Joseph, your brother," he said, "the one you sold into Egypt.
01Gn 45:5 And now don't be worried or angry with yourselves for selling me here, because God sent me ahead of you to preserve life.
01Gn 45:6 For the famine has been in the land these two years, and there will be five more years without plowing or harvesting.
01Gn 45:7 God sent me ahead of you to establish you as a remnant within the land and to keep you alive by a great deliverance.
01Gn 45:8 Therefore it was not you who sent me here, but God. He has made me a father to Pharaoh, lord of his entire household, and ruler over all the land of Egypt.
01Gn 45:9 "Return quickly to my father and say to him, 'This is what your son Joseph says: "God has made me lord of all Egypt. Come down to me without delay.
01Gn 45:10 You can settle in the land of Goshen and be near me-- you, your children, and grandchildren, your sheep, cattle, and all you have.
01Gn 45:11 There I will sustain you, for there will be five more years of famine. Otherwise, you, your household, and everything you have will become destitute."'
01Gn 45:12 Look! Your eyes and my brother Benjamin's eyes can see that it is I [, Joseph,] who am speaking to you.
01Gn 45:13 Tell my father all about my glory in Egypt and about all you have seen. And bring my father here quickly."
01Gn 45:14 Then Joseph threw his arms around Benjamin and wept, and Benjamin wept on his shoulder.
01Gn 45:15 Joseph kissed each of his brothers as he wept, and afterward his brothers talked with him.
01Gn 45:16 When the news reached Pharaoh's house, "Joseph's brothers have come," Pharaoh and his servants were pleased.
01Gn 45:17 Pharaoh said to Joseph, "Tell your brothers, 'Do this: Load your animals and go on back to the land of Canaan.
01Gn 45:18 Get your father and your households, and come back to me. I will give you the best of the land of Egypt, and you can eat from the richness of the land.'
01Gn 45:19 You are also commanded, 'Do this: Take wagons from the land of Egypt for your young children, your wives, and bring your father here.
01Gn 45:20 Do not be concerned about your belongings, for the best of all the land of Egypt is yours.'"
01Gn 45:21 The sons of Israel did this. Joseph gave them wagons as Pharaoh had commanded, and he gave them provisions for the journey.
01Gn 45:22 He gave each of the brothers changes of clothes, but he gave Benjamin 300 pieces of silver and five changes of clothes.
01Gn 45:23 He sent his father the following: 10 donkeys carrying the best products of Egypt, and 10 female donkeys carrying grain, food, and provisions for his father on the journey.
01Gn 45:24 So Joseph sent his brothers on their way, and as they were leaving, he said to them, "Don't argue on the way."
01Gn 45:25 So they went up from Egypt and came to their father Jacob in the land of Canaan.
01Gn 45:26 They said, "Joseph is still alive, and he is ruler over all the land of Egypt!" Jacob was stunned, for he did not believe them.
01Gn 45:27 But when they told Jacob all that Joseph had said to them, and when he saw the wagons that Joseph had sent to transport him, the spirit of their father Jacob revived.
01Gn 45:28 Then Israel said, "Enough! My son Joseph is still alive. I will go to see him before I die."
01Gn 46:1 Israel set out with all that he had and came to Beer-sheba, and he offered sacrifices to the God of his father Isaac.
01Gn 46:2 That night God spoke to Israel in a vision: "Jacob, Jacob!" He said. And Jacob replied, "Here I am."
01Gn 46:3 God said, "I am God, the God of your father. Do not be afraid to go down to Egypt, for I will make you a great nation there.
01Gn 46:4 I will go down with you to Egypt, and I will also bring you back. Joseph will put his hands on your eyes."
01Gn 46:5 Jacob left Beer-sheba. The sons of Israel took their father Jacob in the wagons Pharaoh had sent to carry him, along with their children and their wives.
01Gn 46:6 They also took their cattle and possessions they had acquired in the land of Canaan. Then Jacob and all his children with him went to Egypt.
01Gn 46:7 His sons and grandsons, his daughters and granddaughters, indeed all his offspring, he brought with him to Egypt.
01Gn 46:8 These are the names of the Israelites, Jacob and his descendants, who went to Egypt: Jacob's firstborn: Reuben.
01Gn 46:9 Reuben's sons: Hanoch, Pallu, Hezron, and Carmi.
01Gn 46:10 Simeon's sons: Jemuel, Jamin, Ohad, Jachin, Zohar, and Shaul, the son of a Canaanite woman.
01Gn 46:11 Levi's sons: Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.
01Gn 46:12 Judah's sons: Er, Onan, Shelah, Perez, and Zerah; but Er and Onan died in the land of Canaan. Perez's sons: Hezron and Hamul.
01Gn 46:13 Issachar's sons: Tola, Puvah, Jashub, and Shimron.
01Gn 46:14 Zebulun's sons: Sered, Elon, and Jahleel.
01Gn 46:15 These were Leah's sons born to Jacob in Paddan-aram, as well as his daughter Dinah. The total number of persons: 33.
01Gn 46:16 Gad's sons: Ziphion, Haggi, Shuni, Ezbon, Eri, Arodi, and Areli.
01Gn 46:17 Asher's sons: Imnah, Ishvah, Ishvi, Beriah, and their sister Serah. Beriah's sons were Heber and Malchiel.
01Gn 46:18 These were the sons of Zilpah-- whom Laban gave to his daughter Leah-- that she bore to Jacob: 16 persons.
01Gn 46:19 The sons of Jacob's wife Rachel: Joseph and Benjamin.
01Gn 46:20 Manasseh and Ephraim were born to Joseph in the land of Egypt. They were born to him by Asenath daughter of Potiphera, a priest at On.
01Gn 46:21 Benjamin's sons: Bela, Becher, Ashbel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi, Rosh, Muppim, Huppim, and Ard.
01Gn 46:22 These were Rachel's sons who were born to Jacob: 14 persons.
01Gn 46:23 Dan's son: Hashum.
01Gn 46:24 Naphtali's sons: Jahzeel, Guni, Jezer, and Shillem.
01Gn 46:25 These were the sons of Bilhah, whom Laban gave to his daughter Rachel. She bore to Jacob: seven persons.
01Gn 46:26 The total number of persons belonging to Jacob-- his direct descendants, not including the wives of Jacob's sons-- who came to Egypt: 66.
01Gn 46:27 And Joseph's sons who were born to him in Egypt: two persons. All those of Jacob's household who had come to Egypt: 70 persons.
01Gn 46:28 Now Jacob had sent Judah ahead of him to Joseph to prepare for his arrival at Goshen. When they came to the land of Goshen,
01Gn 46:29 Joseph hitched [the horses to] his chariot and went up to Goshen to meet his father Israel. Joseph presented himself to him, threw his arms around him, and wept for a long time.
01Gn 46:30 Then Israel said to Joseph, "At last I can die, now that I have seen your face [and know] you are still alive!"
01Gn 46:31 Joseph said to his brothers and to his father's household, "I will go up and inform Pharaoh, telling him: My brothers and my father's household, who were in the land of Canaan, have come to me.
01Gn 46:32 The men are shepherds; indeed they raise livestock. They have brought their sheep and cattle and all that they have.
01Gn 46:33 When Pharaoh addresses you and asks, 'What is your occupation?'
01Gn 46:34 you are to say, 'Your servants, both we and our fathers, have raised livestock from our youth until now.' Then you will be allowed to settle in the land of Goshen, since all shepherds are abhorrent to Egyptians."
01Gn 47:1 So Joseph went and informed Pharaoh: "My father and my brothers, with their sheep and cattle and all that they have, have come from the land of Canaan and are now in the land of Goshen."
01Gn 47:2 He took five of his brothers and presented them before Pharaoh.
01Gn 47:3 Then Pharaoh asked his brothers, "What is your occupation?" And they said to Pharaoh, "Your servants, both we and our fathers, are shepherds."
01Gn 47:4 Then they said to Pharaoh, "We have come to live in the land for a while because there is no grazing land for your servants' sheep, since the famine in the land of Canaan has been severe. So now, please let your servants settle in the land of Goshen."
01Gn 47:5 Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, "[Now that] your father and brothers have come to you,
01Gn 47:6 the land of Egypt is open before you; settle your father and brothers in the best part of the land. They can live in the land of Goshen. If you know of any capable men among them, put them in charge of my livestock."
01Gn 47:7 Joseph then brought his father Jacob and presented him before Pharaoh, and Jacob blessed Pharaoh.
01Gn 47:8 Then Pharaoh said to Jacob, "How many years have you lived?"
01Gn 47:9 Jacob said to Pharaoh, "My pilgrimage has lasted 130 years. My years have been few and hard, and they have not surpassed the years of my fathers during their pilgrimages."
01Gn 47:10 So Jacob blessed Pharaoh and departed from Pharaoh's presence.
01Gn 47:11 Then Joseph settled his father and brothers in the land of Egypt and gave them property in the best part of the land, the land of Rameses, as Pharaoh had commanded.
01Gn 47:12 And Joseph provided his father, his brothers, and all his father's household with food for their dependents.
01Gn 47:13 But there was no food in that entire region, for the famine was very severe. The land of Egypt and the land of Canaan were exhausted by the famine.
01Gn 47:14 Joseph collected all the money to be found in the land of Egypt and the land of Canaan in exchange for the grain they were purchasing, and he brought the money to Pharaoh's house.
01Gn 47:15 When the money from the land of Egypt and the land of Canaan was gone, all the Egyptians came to Joseph and said, "Give us food. Why should we die here in front of you? The money is gone!"
01Gn 47:16 But Joseph said, "Give me your livestock. Since the money is gone, I will give you food in exchange for your livestock."
01Gn 47:17 So they brought their livestock to Joseph, and he gave them food in exchange for the horses, the herds of sheep, the herds of cattle, and the donkeys. That year he provided them with food in exchange for all their livestock.
01Gn 47:18 When that year was over, they came the next year and said to him, "We cannot hide from our lord that the money is gone and that all our livestock belongs to our lord. There is nothing left for our lord except our bodies and our land.
01Gn 47:19 Why should we perish here in front of you-- both us and our land? Buy us and our land in exchange for food. Then we with our land will become Pharaoh's slaves. Give us seed so that we can live and not die, and so that the land won't become desolate."
01Gn 47:20 In this way, Joseph acquired all the land in Egypt for Pharaoh, because every Egyptian sold his field since the famine was so severe for them. The land became Pharaoh's,
01Gn 47:21 and Joseph moved the people to the cities from one end of Egypt to the other.
01Gn 47:22 The only land he didn't acquire was that of the priests, for it was their allotment from Pharaoh. They lived off the allotment Pharaoh had given them; therefore they did not sell their land.
01Gn 47:23 Then Joseph said to the people, "Understand today that I have acquired you and your land for Pharaoh. Here is seed for you. Sow it in the land.
01Gn 47:24 At harvest, you are to give a fifth of it to Pharaoh, and four-fifths will be yours as seed for the field and as food for yourselves, your households, and your dependents."
01Gn 47:25 And they said, "You have saved our lives. We have found favor in our lord's eyes and will be Pharaoh's slaves."
01Gn 47:26 So Joseph made it a law, still in effect today in the land of Egypt, that a fifth [of the produce] belongs to Pharaoh. Only the priests' land does not belong to Pharaoh.
01Gn 47:27 Israel settled in the land of Egypt, in the region of Goshen. They acquired property in it and became fruitful and very numerous.
01Gn 47:28 Now Jacob lived in the land of Egypt 17 years, and his life span was 147 years.
01Gn 47:29 When the time drew near for him to die, he called his son Joseph and said to him, "If I have found favor in your eyes, put your hand under my thigh [and promise me] that you will deal with me in faithful love. Do not bury me in Egypt.
01Gn 47:30 When I lie down with my fathers, carry me away from Egypt and bury me in their burial place." Joseph answered, "I will do what you have asked."
01Gn 47:31 And Jacob said, "Swear to me." So Joseph swore to him. Then Israel bowed [in thanks] at the head of his bed.
01Gn 48:1 Some time after this, Joseph was told, "Your father is weaker." So he set out with his two sons, Manasseh and Ephraim.
01Gn 48:2 When Jacob was told, "Your son Joseph has come to you," Israel summoned his strength and sat up in bed.
01Gn 48:3 Jacob said to Joseph, " God Almighty appeared to me at Luz in the land of Canaan and blessed me.
01Gn 48:4 He said to me, 'I will make you fruitful and numerous; I will make many nations [come from] you, and I will give this land as an eternal possession to your descendants to come.'
01Gn 48:5 Your two sons born to you in the land of Egypt before I came to you in Egypt are now mine. Ephraim and Manasseh belong to me just as Reuben and Simeon do.
01Gn 48:6 Children born to you after them will be yours and will be recorded under the names of their brothers with regard to their inheritance.
01Gn 48:7 When I was returning from Paddan, to my sorrow Rachel died along the way, some distance from Ephrath in the land of Canaan. I buried her there along the way to Ephrath," (that is, Bethlehem).
01Gn 48:8 When Israel saw Joseph's sons, he said, "Who are these?"
01Gn 48:9 And Joseph said to his father, "They are my sons God has given me here." So Jacob said, "Bring them to me and I will bless them."
01Gn 48:10 Now Jacob's eyesight was poor because of old age; he could hardly see. Joseph brought them to him, and he kissed and embraced them.
01Gn 48:11 Israel said to Joseph, "I never expected to see your face [again], but now God has even let me see your offspring."
01Gn 48:12 Then Joseph took them from his [father's] knees and bowed with his face to the ground.
01Gn 48:13 Then Joseph took them both-- with his right hand Ephraim toward Israel's left, and with his left hand Manasseh toward Israel's right-- and brought them to Israel.
01Gn 48:14 But Israel stretched out his right hand and put it on the head of Ephraim, the younger, and crossing his hands, put his left on Manasseh's head, although Manasseh was the firstborn.
01Gn 48:15 Then he blessed Joseph and said: The God before whom my fathers Abraham and Isaac walked, the God who has been my shepherd all my life to this day,
01Gn 48:16 the Angel who has redeemed me from all harm-- may He bless these boys. And may they be called by my name and the names of my fathers Abraham and Isaac, and may they grow to be numerous within the land.
01Gn 48:17 When Joseph saw that his father had placed his right hand on Ephraim's head, he thought it was a mistake and took his father's hand to move it from Ephraim's head to Manasseh's.
01Gn 48:18 Joseph said to his father, "Not that way, my father! This one is the firstborn. Put your right hand on his head."
01Gn 48:19 But his father refused and said, "I know, my son, I know! He too will become a tribe, and he too will be great; nevertheless, his younger brother will be greater than he, and his offspring will become a populous nation."
01Gn 48:20 So he blessed them that day with these words: Israel will invoke blessings by you, saying, "May God make you like Ephraim and Manasseh," putting Ephraim before Manasseh.
01Gn 48:21 Then Israel said to Joseph, "Look! I am about to die, but God will be with you and will bring you back to the land of your fathers.
01Gn 48:22 Over and above what I am giving your brothers, I am giving you the one mountain slope that I took from the hand of the Amorites with my sword and bow."
01Gn 49:1 Then Jacob called his sons and said, "Gather around, and I will tell you what will happen to you in the days to come.
01Gn 49:2 Come together and listen, sons of Jacob; listen to your father Israel:
01Gn 49:3 Reuben, you are my firstborn, my strength and the firstfruits of my virility, excelling in prominence, excelling in power.
01Gn 49:4 Turbulent as water, you will no longer excel, because you got into your father's bed and you defiled it-- he got into my bed.
01Gn 49:5 Simeon and Levi are brothers; their knives are vicious weapons.
01Gn 49:6 May I never enter their council; may I never join their assembly. For in their anger they kill men, and on a whim they hamstring oxen.
01Gn 49:7 Their anger is cursed, for it is strong, and their fury, for it is cruel! I will disperse them throughout Jacob and scatter them throughout Israel.
01Gn 49:8 Judah, your brothers will praise you. Your hand will be on the necks of your enemies; your father's sons will bow down to you.
01Gn 49:9 Judah is a young lion-- my son, you return from the kill-- he crouches; he lies down like a lion and like a lioness-- who wants to rouse him?
01Gn 49:10 The scepter will not depart from Judah, or the staff from between his feet, until He whose right it is comes and the obedience of the peoples belongs to Him.
01Gn 49:11 He ties his donkey to a vine, and the colt of his donkey to the choice vine. He washes his clothes in wine, and his robes in the blood of grapes.
01Gn 49:12 His eyes are darker than wine, and his teeth are whiter than milk.
01Gn 49:13 Zebulun will live by the seashore and will be a harbor for ships, and his territory will be next to Sidon.
01Gn 49:14 Issachar is a strong donkey lying down between the saddlebags.
01Gn 49:15 He saw that his resting place was good and that the land was pleasant, so he leaned his shoulder to bear a load and became a forced laborer.
01Gn 49:16 Dan will judge his people as one of the tribes of Israel.
01Gn 49:17 He will be a snake by the road, a viper beside the path, that bites the horses' heels so that its rider falls backwards.
01Gn 49:18 I wait for Your salvation, LORD.
01Gn 49:19 Gad will be attacked by [marauding] bands, but he will attack their heels.
01Gn 49:20 Asher's food will be rich, and he will produce royal delicacies.
01Gn 49:21 Naphtali is a doe set free that bears beautiful fawns.
01Gn 49:22 Joseph is a fruitful vine, a fruitful vine beside a spring; its branches climb over the wall.
01Gn 49:23 The archers attacked him, shot at him, and were hostile toward him.
01Gn 49:24 Yet his bow remained steady, and his strong arms were made agile by the hands of the Mighty One of Jacob, by the name of the Shepherd, the Rock of Israel,
01Gn 49:25 by the God of your father who helps you, and by the Almighty who blesses you with blessings of the heavens above, blessings of the deep that lies below, and blessings of the breasts and the womb.
01Gn 49:26 The blessings of your father excel the blessings of my ancestors and the bounty of the eternal hills. May they rest on the head of Joseph, on the crown of the prince of his brothers.
01Gn 49:27 Benjamin is a wolf; he tears [his prey.] In the morning he devours the prey, and in the evening he divides the plunder."
01Gn 49:28 These are the tribes of Israel, 12 in all, and this was what their father said to them. He blessed them, and he blessed each one with a suitable blessing.
01Gn 49:29 Then he commanded them: "I am about to be gathered to my people. Bury me with my fathers in the cave in the field of Ephron the Hittite.
01Gn 49:30 The cave is in the field of Machpelah, near Mamre, in the land of Canaan. This is the field Abraham purchased from Ephron the Hittite as a burial site.
01Gn 49:31 Abraham and his wife Sarah are buried there, Isaac and his wife Rebekah are buried there, and I buried Leah there.
01Gn 49:32 The field and the cave in it [were purchased] from the Hittites."
01Gn 49:33 When Jacob had finished instructing his sons, he drew his feet into the bed and died. He was gathered to his people.
01Gn 50:1 Then Joseph, leaning over his father's face, wept and kissed him.
01Gn 50:2 He commanded his servants who were physicians to embalm his father. So they embalmed Israel.
01Gn 50:3 They took 40 days to complete this, for embalming takes that long, and the Egyptians mourned for him 70 days.
01Gn 50:4 When the days of mourning were over, Joseph said to Pharaoh's household, "If I have found favor with you, please tell Pharaoh that
01Gn 50:5 my father made me take an oath, saying, 'I am about to die. You must bury me there in the tomb that I hewed out for myself in the land of Canaan.' Now let me go and bury my father. Then I will return."
01Gn 50:6 So Pharaoh said, "Go and bury your father in keeping with your oath."
01Gn 50:7 Then Joseph went to bury his father, and all Pharaoh's servants, the elders of his household, and all the elders of the land of Egypt went with him,
01Gn 50:8 along with all Joseph's household, his brothers, and his father's household. Only their children, their sheep, and their cattle were left in the land of Goshen.
01Gn 50:9 Horses and chariots went up with him; it was a very impressive procession.
01Gn 50:10 When they reached the threshing floor of Atad, which is across the Jordan, they lamented and wept loudly, and Joseph mourned seven days for his father.
01Gn 50:11 When the Canaanite inhabitants of the land saw the mourning at the threshing floor of Atad, they said, "This is a solemn mourning on the part of the Egyptians." Therefore the place is named Abel-mizraim. It is across the Jordan.
01Gn 50:12 So Jacob's sons did for him what he had commanded them.
01Gn 50:13 They carried him to the land of Canaan and buried him in the cave at Machpelah in the field near Mamre, which Abraham had purchased as a burial site from Ephron the Hittite.
01Gn 50:14 After Joseph buried his father, he returned to Egypt with his brothers and all who had gone with him to bury his father.
01Gn 50:15 When Joseph's brothers saw that their father was dead, they said to one another, "If Joseph is holding a grudge against us, he will certainly repay us for all the wrong we caused him."
01Gn 50:16 So they sent this message to Joseph, "Before he died your father gave a command:
01Gn 50:17 'Say this to Joseph: Please forgive your brothers' transgression and their sin-- the wrong they caused you.' Therefore, please forgive the transgression of the servants of the God of your father." Joseph wept when their message came to him.
01Gn 50:18 Then his brothers also came to him, bowed down before him, and said, "We are your slaves!"
01Gn 50:19 But Joseph said to them, "Don't be afraid. Am I in the place of God?
01Gn 50:20 You planned evil against me; God planned it for good to bring about the present result-- the survival of many people.
01Gn 50:21 Therefore don't be afraid. I will take care of you and your little ones." And he comforted them and spoke kindly to them.
01Gn 50:22 Joseph and his father's household remained in Egypt. Joseph lived 110 years.
01Gn 50:23 He saw Ephraim's sons to the third generation; the sons of Manasseh's son Machir were recognized by Joseph.
01Gn 50:24 Joseph said to his brothers, "I am about to die, but God will certainly come to your aid and bring you up from this land to the land He promised Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob."
01Gn 50:25 So Joseph made the Israelites take an oath: "When God comes to your aid, you are to carry my bones up from here."
01Gn 50:26 Joseph died at the age of 110. They embalmed him and placed him in a coffin in Egypt.
