02Ex 1:1 These are the names of the sons of Israel who came to Egypt with Jacob; each came with his family:
02Ex 1:2 Reuben, Simeon, Levi, and Judah;
02Ex 1:3 Issachar, Zebulun, and Benjamin;
02Ex 1:4 Dan and Naphtali; Gad and Asher.
02Ex 1:5 The total number of Jacob's descendants was 70; Joseph was already in Egypt.
02Ex 1:6 Then Joseph and all his brothers and all that generation died.
02Ex 1:7 But the Israelites were fruitful, increased rapidly, multiplied, and became extremely numerous so that the land was filled with them.
02Ex 1:8 A new king, who had not known Joseph, came to power in Egypt.
02Ex 1:9 He said to his people, "Look, the Israelite people are more numerous and powerful than we are.
02Ex 1:10 Let us deal shrewdly with them; otherwise they will multiply [further], and if war breaks out, they may join our enemies, fight against us, and leave the country."
02Ex 1:11 So the Egyptians assigned taskmasters over the Israelites to oppress them with forced labor. They built Pithom and Rameses as supply cities for Pharaoh.
02Ex 1:12 But the more they oppressed them, the more they multiplied and spread so that the Egyptians came to dread the Israelites.
02Ex 1:13 They worked the Israelites ruthlessly
02Ex 1:14 and made their lives bitter with difficult labor in brick and mortar, and in all kinds of fieldwork. They ruthlessly imposed all this work on them.
02Ex 1:15 Then the king of Egypt said to the Hebrew midwives, one of whom was named Shiphrah and the other Puah,
02Ex 1:16 "When you help the Hebrew women give birth, observe them as they deliver. If the child is a son, kill him, but if it's a daughter, she may live."
02Ex 1:17 The Hebrew midwives, however, feared God and did not do as the king of Egypt had told them; they let the boys live.
02Ex 1:18 So the king of Egypt summoned the midwives and asked them, "Why have you done this and let the boys live?"
02Ex 1:19 The midwives said to Pharaoh, "The Hebrew women are not like the Egyptian women, for they are vigorous and give birth before a midwife can get to them."
02Ex 1:20 So God was good to the midwives, and the people multiplied and became very numerous.
02Ex 1:21 Since the midwives feared God, He gave them families.
02Ex 1:22 Pharaoh then commanded all his people: "You must throw every son born to the Hebrews into the Nile, but let every daughter live."
02Ex 2:1 Now a man from the family of Levi married a Levite woman.
02Ex 2:2 The woman became pregnant and gave birth to a son; when she saw that he was beautiful, she hid him for three months.
02Ex 2:3 But when she could no longer hide him, she got a papyrus basket for him and coated it with asphalt and pitch. She placed the child in it and set it among the reeds by the bank of the Nile.
02Ex 2:4 Then his sister stood at a distance in order to see what would happen to him.
02Ex 2:5 Pharaoh's daughter went down to bathe at the Nile while her servant girls walked along the riverbank. Seeing the basket among the reeds, she sent her slave girl to get it.
02Ex 2:6 When she opened it, she saw the child-- a little boy, crying. She felt sorry for him and said, "This is one of the Hebrew boys."
02Ex 2:7 Then his sister said to Pharaoh's daughter, "Should I go and call a woman from the Hebrews to nurse the boy for you?"
02Ex 2:8 "Go." Pharaoh's daughter told her. So the girl went and called the boy's mother.
02Ex 2:9 Then Pharaoh's daughter said to her, "Take this child and nurse him for me, and I will pay your wages." So the woman took the boy and nursed him.
02Ex 2:10 When the child grew older, she brought him to Pharaoh's daughter, and he became her son. She named him Moses, "Because," she said, "I drew him out of the water."
02Ex 2:11 Years later, after Moses had grown up, he went out to his own people and observed their forced labor. He saw an Egyptian beating a Hebrew, one of his people.
02Ex 2:12 Looking all around and seeing no one, he struck the Egyptian dead and hid him in the sand.
02Ex 2:13 The next day he went out and saw two Hebrews fighting. He asked the one in the wrong, "Why are you attacking your neighbor?"
02Ex 2:14 "Who made you a leader and judge over us?" the man replied. "Are you planning to kill me as you killed the Egyptian?" Then Moses became afraid and thought: What I did is certainly known.
02Ex 2:15 When Pharaoh heard about this, he tried to kill Moses. But Moses fled from Pharaoh and went to live in the land of Midian, and sat down by a well.
02Ex 2:16 Now the priest of Midian had seven daughters. They came to draw water and filled the troughs to water their father's flock.
02Ex 2:17 Then some shepherds arrived and drove them away, but Moses came to their rescue and watered their flock.
02Ex 2:18 When they returned to their father Reuel he asked, "Why have you come back so quickly today?"
02Ex 2:19 They answered, "An Egyptian rescued us from the shepherds. He even drew water for us and watered the flock."
02Ex 2:20 "So where is he?" he asked his daughters. "Why then did you leave the man behind? Invite him to eat dinner."
02Ex 2:21 Moses agreed to stay with the man, and he gave his daughter Zipporah to Moses [in marriage].
02Ex 2:22 She gave birth to a son whom he named Gershom, for he said, "I have become a stranger in a foreign land."
02Ex 2:23 After a long time, the king of Egypt died. The Israelites groaned because of their difficult labor, and they cried out; and their cry for help ascended to God because of the difficult labor.
02Ex 2:24 So God heard their groaning, and He remembered His covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.
02Ex 2:25 God saw the Israelites, and He took notice.
02Ex 3:1 Meanwhile Moses was shepherding the flock of his father-in-law Jethro, the priest of Midian. He led the flock to the far side of the wilderness and came to Horeb, the mountain of God.
02Ex 3:2 Then the Angel of the LORD appeared to him in a flame of fire within a bush. As Moses looked, he saw that the bush was on fire but was not consumed.
02Ex 3:3 So Moses thought: I must go over and look at this remarkable sight. Why isn't the bush burning up?
02Ex 3:4 When the LORD saw that he had gone over to look, God called out to him from the bush, "Moses, Moses!" "Here I am," he answered.
02Ex 3:5 "Do not come closer," He said. "Take your sandals off your feet, for the place where you are standing is holy ground."
02Ex 3:6 Then He continued, "I am the God of your father, the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob." Moses hid his face because he was afraid to look at God.
02Ex 3:7 Then the LORD said, "I have observed the misery of My people in Egypt, and have heard them crying out because of their oppressors, and I know about their sufferings.
02Ex 3:8 I have come down to rescue them from the power of the Egyptians and to bring them from that land to a good and spacious land, a land flowing with milk and honey-- the territory of the Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites.
02Ex 3:9 The Israelites' cry for help has come to Me, and I have also seen the way the Egyptians are oppressing them.
02Ex 3:10 Therefore, go. I am sending you to Pharaoh so that you may lead My people, the Israelites, out of Egypt."
02Ex 3:11 But Moses asked God, "Who am I that I should go to Pharaoh and that I should bring the Israelites out of Egypt?"
02Ex 3:12 He answered, "I will certainly be with you, and this will be the sign to you that I have sent you: when you bring the people out of Egypt, you will all worship God at this mountain."
02Ex 3:13 Then Moses asked God, "If I go to the Israelites and say to them: The God of your fathers has sent me to you, and they ask me, 'What is His name?' what should I tell them?"
02Ex 3:14 God replied to Moses, "I AM WHO I AM. This is what you are to say to the Israelites: I AM has sent me to you."
02Ex 3:15 God also said to Moses, "Say this to the Israelites: Yahweh, the God of your fathers, the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob, has sent me to you. This is My name forever; this is how I am to be remembered in every generation.
02Ex 3:16 "Go and assemble the elders of Israel and say to them: Yahweh, the God of your fathers, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, has appeared to me and said: I have paid close attention to you and to what has been done to you in Egypt.
02Ex 3:17 And I have promised you that I will bring you up from the misery of Egypt to the land of the Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites-- a land flowing with milk and honey.
02Ex 3:18 They will listen to what you say. Then you, along with the elders of Israel, must go to the king of Egypt and say to him: The LORD, the God of the Hebrews, has met with us. Now please let us go on a three-day trip into the wilderness so that we may sacrifice to the LORD our God.
02Ex 3:19 "However, I know that the king of Egypt will not allow you to go, unless [he is forced] by a strong hand.
02Ex 3:20 I will stretch out My hand and strike Egypt with all My miracles that I will perform in it. After that, he will let you go.
02Ex 3:21 And I will give this people such favor in the sight of the Egyptians that when you go, you will not go empty-handed.
02Ex 3:22 Each woman will ask her neighbor and any woman staying in her house for silver and gold jewelry, and clothing, and you will put them on your sons and daughters. So you will plunder the Egyptians."
02Ex 4:1 Then Moses answered, "What if they won't believe me and will not obey me but say, 'The LORD did not appear to you'?"
02Ex 4:2 The LORD asked him, "What is that in your hand?" "A staff," he replied.
02Ex 4:3 Then He said, "Throw it on the ground." He threw it on the ground, and it became a snake. Moses ran from it,
02Ex 4:4 but the LORD told him, "Stretch out your hand and grab it by the tail." So he stretched out his hand and caught it, and it became a staff in his hand.
02Ex 4:5 "This will take place," He continued, "so they will believe that the LORD, the God of their fathers, the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob, has appeared to you."
02Ex 4:6 In addition the LORD said to him, "Put your hand inside your cloak." So he put his hand inside his cloak, and when he took it out, his hand was diseased, like snow.
02Ex 4:7 Then He said, "Put your hand back inside your cloak." He put his hand back inside his cloak, and when he took it out, it had again become like the rest of his skin.
02Ex 4:8 "If they will not believe you and will not respond to the evidence of the first sign, they may believe the evidence of the second sign.
02Ex 4:9 And if they don't believe even these two signs or listen to what you say, take some water from the Nile and pour it on the dry ground. The water you take from the Nile will become blood on the ground."
02Ex 4:10 But Moses replied to the LORD, "Please, Lord, I have never been eloquent-- either in the past or recently or since You have been speaking to Your servant-- because I am slow and hesitant in speech."
02Ex 4:11 The LORD said to him, "Who made the human mouth? Who makes him mute or deaf, seeing or blind? Is it not I, the LORD?
02Ex 4:12 Now go! I will help you speak and I will teach you what to say."
02Ex 4:13 Moses said, "Please, Lord, send someone else."
02Ex 4:14 Then the LORD's anger burned against Moses, and He said, "Isn't Aaron the Levite your brother? I know that he can speak well. And also, he is on his way now to meet you. When he sees you, his heart will rejoice.
02Ex 4:15 You will speak with him and tell him what to say. I will help both you and him [to speak], and will teach you both what to do.
02Ex 4:16 He will speak to the people for you. He will be your spokesman, and you will serve as God to him.
02Ex 4:17 And take this staff in your hand that you will perform the signs with."
02Ex 4:18 Then Moses went back to his father-in-law Jethro and said to him, "Please let me return to my relatives in Egypt and see if they are still living." Jethro said to Moses, "Go in peace."
02Ex 4:19 Now in Midian the LORD told Moses, "Return to Egypt, for all the men who wanted to kill you are dead."
02Ex 4:20 So Moses took his wife and sons, put them on a donkey, and set out for the land of Egypt. And Moses took God's staff in his hand.
02Ex 4:21 The LORD instructed Moses, "When you go back to Egypt, make sure you do in front of Pharaoh all the wonders I have put within your power. But I will harden his heart so that he won't let the people go.
02Ex 4:22 Then you will say to Pharaoh: This is what the LORD says: Israel is My firstborn son.
02Ex 4:23 I told you: Let My son go so that he may worship Me, but you refused to let him go. Now I will kill your firstborn son!"
02Ex 4:24 On the trip, at an overnight campsite, it happened that the LORD confronted him and sought to put him to death.
02Ex 4:25 So Zipporah took a flint, cut off her son's foreskin, and threw it at Moses' feet. Then she said, "You are a bridegroom of blood to me!"
02Ex 4:26 So He let him alone. At that time she said, "You are a bridegroom of blood," referring to the circumcision.
02Ex 4:27 Now the LORD had said to Aaron, "Go and meet Moses in the wilderness." So he went and met him at the mountain of God and kissed him.
02Ex 4:28 Moses told Aaron everything the LORD had sent him to say, and about all the signs He had commanded him [to do].
02Ex 4:29 Then Moses and Aaron went and assembled all the elders of the Israelites.
02Ex 4:30 Aaron repeated everything the LORD had said to Moses and performed the signs before the people.
02Ex 4:31 The people believed, and when they heard that the LORD had paid attention to them and that He had seen their misery, they bowed down and worshiped.
02Ex 5:1 Later, Moses and Aaron went in and said to Pharaoh, "This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: Let My people go, so that they may hold a festival for Me in the wilderness."
02Ex 5:2 But Pharaoh responded, "Who is the LORD that I should obey Him by letting Israel go? I do not know the LORD, and what's more, I will not let Israel go."
02Ex 5:3 Then they answered, "The God of the Hebrews has met with us. Please let us go on a three-day trip into the wilderness so that we may sacrifice to the LORD our God, or else He may strike us with plague or sword."
02Ex 5:4 The king of Egypt said to them, "Moses and Aaron, why are you causing the people to neglect their work? Get to your labors!"
02Ex 5:5 Pharaoh also said, "Look, the people of the land are so numerous, and you would stop them from working."
02Ex 5:6 That day Pharaoh commanded the overseers of the people as well as their foremen:
02Ex 5:7 "Don't continue to supply the people with straw for making bricks, as before. They must go and gather straw for themselves.
02Ex 5:8 But require the same quota of bricks from them as they were making before; do not reduce it. For they are slackers-- that is why they are crying out, 'Let us go and sacrifice to our God.'
02Ex 5:9 Impose heavier work on the men. Then they will be occupied with it and not pay attention to deceptive words."
02Ex 5:10 So the overseers and foremen of the people went out and said to them, "This is what Pharaoh says: 'I am not giving you straw.
02Ex 5:11 Go get straw yourselves wherever you can find it, but there will be no reduction at all in your workload.'"
02Ex 5:12 So the people scattered throughout the land of Egypt to gather stubble for straw.
02Ex 5:13 The overseers insisted, "Finish your assigned work each day, just as [you did] when straw was [provided]."
02Ex 5:14 Then the Israelite foremen, whom Pharaoh's slave drivers had set over the people, were beaten and asked, "Why haven't you finished making your prescribed number of bricks yesterday or today, as [you did] before?"
02Ex 5:15 So the Israelite foremen went in and cried for help to Pharaoh: "Why are you treating your servants this way?
02Ex 5:16 No straw has been given to your servants, yet they say to us, 'Make bricks!' Look, your servants are being beaten, but it is your own people who are at fault."
02Ex 5:17 But he said, "You are slackers. Slackers! That is why you are saying, 'Let us go sacrifice to the LORD.'
02Ex 5:18 Now get to work. No straw will be given to you, but you must produce the same quantity of bricks."
02Ex 5:19 The Israelite foremen saw that they were in trouble when they were told, "You cannot reduce your daily quota of bricks."
02Ex 5:20 When they left Pharaoh, they confronted Moses and Aaron, who stood [waiting] to meet them.
02Ex 5:21 "May the LORD take note of you and judge," they said to them, "because you have made us reek in front of Pharaoh and his officials-- putting a sword in their hand to kill us!"
02Ex 5:22 So Moses went back to the LORD and asked, "Lord, why have You caused trouble for this people? And why did You ever send me?
02Ex 5:23 Ever since I went in to Pharaoh to speak in Your name he has caused trouble for this people, and You haven't delivered Your people at all."
02Ex 6:1 But the LORD replied to Moses, "Now you are going to see what I will do to Pharaoh: he will let them go because of My strong hand; he will drive them out of his land because of My strong hand."
02Ex 6:2 Then God spoke to Moses, telling him, "I am Yahweh.
02Ex 6:3 I appeared to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob as God Almighty, but I did not make My name Yahweh known to them.
02Ex 6:4 I also established My covenant with them to give them the land of Canaan, the land they lived in as foreigners.
02Ex 6:5 Furthermore, I have heard the groaning of the Israelites, whom the Egyptians are forcing to work as slaves, and I have remembered My covenant.
02Ex 6:6 "Therefore tell the Israelites: I am Yahweh, and I will deliver you from the forced labor of the Egyptians and free you from slavery to them. I will redeem you with an outstretched arm and great acts of judgment.
02Ex 6:7 I will take you as My people, and I will be your God. You will know that I am Yahweh your God, who delivered you from the forced labor of the Egyptians.
02Ex 6:8 I will bring you to the land that I swore to give to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, and I will give it to you as a possession. I am the LORD."
02Ex 6:9 Moses told this to the Israelites, but they did not listen to him because of their broken spirit and hard labor.
02Ex 6:10 Then the LORD spoke to Moses,
02Ex 6:11 "Go and tell Pharaoh king of Egypt to let the Israelites go from his land."
02Ex 6:12 But Moses said in the LORD's presence: "If the Israelites will not listen to me, then how will Pharaoh listen to me, since I am such a poor speaker?"
02Ex 6:13 Then the LORD spoke to Moses and Aaron and gave them commands concerning both the Israelites and Pharaoh king of Egypt to bring the Israelites out of the land of Egypt.
02Ex 6:14 These are the heads of their fathers' families: The sons of Reuben, the firstborn of Israel: Hanoch and Pallu, Hezron and Carmi. These are the clans of Reuben.
02Ex 6:15 The sons of Simeon: Jemuel, Jamin, Ohad, Jachin, Zohar, and Shaul, the son of a Canaanite woman. These are the clans of Simeon.
02Ex 6:16 These are the names of the sons of Levi according to their genealogy: Gershon, Kohath, and Merari. Levi lived 137 years.
02Ex 6:17 The sons of Gershon: Libni and Shimei, by their clans.
02Ex 6:18 The sons of Kohath: Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel. Kohath lived 133 years.
02Ex 6:19 The sons of Merari: Mahli and Mushi. These are the clans of the Levites according to their genealogy.
02Ex 6:20 Amram married his father's sister Jochebed, and she bore him Aaron and Moses. Amram lived 137 years.
02Ex 6:21 The sons of Izhar: Korah, Nepheg, and Zichri.
02Ex 6:22 The sons of Uzziel: Mishael, Elzaphan, and Sithri.
02Ex 6:23 Aaron married Elisheba, daughter of Amminadab and sister of Nahshon. She bore him Nadab and Abihu, Eleazar and Ithamar.
02Ex 6:24 The sons of Korah: Assir, Elkanah, and Abiasaph. These are the clans of the Korahites.
02Ex 6:25 Aaron's son Eleazar married one of the daughters of Putiel and she bore him Phinehas. These are the heads of the Levite families by their clans.
02Ex 6:26 It was this Aaron and Moses whom the LORD told, "Bring the Israelites out of the land of Egypt according to their divisions."
02Ex 6:27 Moses and Aaron were the ones who spoke to Pharaoh king of Egypt in order to bring the Israelites out of Egypt.
02Ex 6:28 On the day the LORD spoke to Moses in the land of Egypt,
02Ex 6:29 He said to him, "I am the LORD; tell Pharaoh king of Egypt everything I am telling you."
02Ex 6:30 But Moses replied in the LORD's presence, "Since I am such a poor speaker, how will Pharaoh listen to me?"
02Ex 7:1 The LORD answered Moses, "See, I have made you like God to Pharaoh, and Aaron your brother will be your prophet.
02Ex 7:2 You must say whatever I command you; then Aaron your brother must declare it to Pharaoh so that he will let the Israelites go from his land.
02Ex 7:3 But I will harden Pharaoh's heart and multiply My signs and wonders in the land of Egypt.
02Ex 7:4 Pharaoh will not listen to you, but I will put My hand on Egypt and bring out the ranks of My people the Israelites, out of the land of Egypt by great acts of judgment.
02Ex 7:5 The Egyptians will know that I am the LORD when I stretch out My hand against Egypt, and bring out the Israelites from among them."
02Ex 7:6 So Moses and Aaron did [this]; they did just as the LORD commanded them.
02Ex 7:7 Moses was 80 years old and Aaron 83 when they spoke to Pharaoh.
02Ex 7:8 The LORD said to Moses and Aaron,
02Ex 7:9 "When Pharaoh tells you: Perform a miracle, tell Aaron: Take your staff and throw it down before Pharaoh. It will become a serpent."
02Ex 7:10 So Moses and Aaron went in to Pharaoh and did just as the LORD had commanded. Aaron threw down his staff before Pharaoh and his officials, and it became a serpent.
02Ex 7:11 But then Pharaoh called the wise men and sorcerers-- the magicians of Egypt, and they also did the same thing by their occult practices.
02Ex 7:12 Each one threw down his staff, and it became a serpent. But Aaron's staff swallowed their staffs.
02Ex 7:13 However, Pharaoh's heart hardened, and he did not listen to them, as the LORD had said.
02Ex 7:14 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Pharaoh is unresponsive: he refuses to let the people go.
02Ex 7:15 Go to Pharaoh in the morning. When you see him walking out to the water, stand ready to meet him by the bank of the Nile. Take in your hand the staff that turned into a snake.
02Ex 7:16 Tell him: The LORD, the God of the Hebrews, has sent me to tell you: Let My people go, so that they may worship Me in the wilderness, but so far you have not listened.
02Ex 7:17 This is what the LORD says: Here is how you will know that I am the LORD. Watch. I will strike the water in the Nile with the staff in my hand, and it will turn to blood.
02Ex 7:18 The fish in the Nile will die, the river will stink, and the Egyptians will be unable to drink water from it."
02Ex 7:19 So the LORD said to Moses, "Tell Aaron: Take your staff and stretch out your hand over the waters of Egypt-- over their rivers, canals, ponds, and all their water reservoirs-- and they will become blood. There will be blood throughout the land of Egypt, even in wooden and stone [containers]."
02Ex 7:20 Moses and Aaron did just as the LORD had commanded; in the sight of Pharaoh and his officials, he raised the staff and struck the water in the Nile, and all the water in the Nile was turned to blood.
02Ex 7:21 The fish in the Nile died, and the river smelled so bad the Egyptians could not drink water from it. There was blood throughout the land of Egypt.
02Ex 7:22 But the magicians of Egypt did the same thing by their occult practices. So Pharaoh's heart hardened, and he would not listen to them, as the LORD had said.
02Ex 7:23 Pharaoh turned around, went into his palace, and didn't even take this to heart.
02Ex 7:24 All the Egyptians dug around the Nile for water to drink because they could not drink the water from the river.
02Ex 7:25 Seven days passed after the LORD struck the Nile.
02Ex 8:1  Then the LORD said to Moses, "Go in to Pharaoh and tell him: This is what the LORD says: Let My people go, so that they may worship Me.
02Ex 8:2 But if you refuse to let them go, then I will plague all your territory with frogs.
02Ex 8:3 The Nile will swarm with frogs; they will come up and go into your palace, into your bedroom and on your bed, into the houses of your officials and your people, and into your ovens and kneading bowls.
02Ex 8:4 The frogs will come up on you, your people, and all your officials."
02Ex 8:5  The LORD then said to Moses, "Tell Aaron: Stretch out your hand with your staff over the rivers, canals, and ponds, and cause the frogs to come up onto the land of Egypt."
02Ex 8:6 When Aaron stretched out his hand over the waters of Egypt, the frogs came up and covered the land of Egypt.
02Ex 8:7 But the magicians did the same thing by their occult practices and brought frogs up onto the land of Egypt.
02Ex 8:8 Pharaoh summoned Moses and Aaron and said, "Ask the LORD that He remove the frogs from me and my people. Then I will let the people go and they can sacrifice to the LORD."
02Ex 8:9 Moses said to Pharaoh, "Make the choice rather than me [by saying] when I should ask for you, your officials, and your people, that the frogs be taken away from you and your houses, and remain only in the Nile."
02Ex 8:10 "Tomorrow," he answered. Moses replied, "As you have said, so you may know there is no one like the LORD our God,
02Ex 8:11 the frogs will go away from you, your houses, your officials, and your people. The frogs will remain only in the Nile."
02Ex 8:12 After Moses and Aaron went out from Pharaoh, Moses cried out to the LORD for help concerning the frogs that He had brought against Pharaoh.
02Ex 8:13 The LORD did as Moses had said: the frogs in the houses, courtyards, and fields died.
02Ex 8:14 They piled them in countless heaps, and there was a terrible odor in the land.
02Ex 8:15 But when Pharaoh saw there was relief, he hardened his heart and would not listen to them, as the LORD had said.
02Ex 8:16 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Tell Aaron: Stretch out your staff and strike the dust of the earth, and it will become gnats throughout the land of Egypt."
02Ex 8:17 And they did this. Aaron stretched out his hand with his staff, and when he struck the dust of the earth, gnats were on the people and animals. All the dust of the earth became gnats throughout the land of Egypt.
02Ex 8:18 The magicians tried to produce gnats using their occult practices, but they could not. The gnats remained on the people and animals.
02Ex 8:19 "This is the finger of God," the magicians said to Pharaoh. But Pharaoh's heart hardened, and he would not listen to them, as the LORD had said.
02Ex 8:20 The LORD said to Moses, "Get up early in the morning and present yourself to Pharaoh when you see him going out to the water. Tell him: This is what the LORD says: Let My people go, so that they may worship Me.
02Ex 8:21 But if you will not let My people go, then I will send swarms of flies against you, your officials, your people, and your houses. The Egyptians' houses will swarm with flies, and so will the land where they live.
02Ex 8:22 But on that day I will give special treatment to the land of Goshen, where My people are living; no flies will be there. This way you will know that I, the Lord, am in the land.
02Ex 8:23 I will make a distinction between My people and your people. This sign will take place tomorrow."
02Ex 8:24 And the LORD did this. Thick swarms of flies went into Pharaoh's palace and his officials' houses. Throughout Egypt the land was ruined because of the swarms of flies.
02Ex 8:25 Then Pharaoh summoned Moses and Aaron and said, "Go sacrifice to your God within the country."
02Ex 8:26 But Moses said, "It would not be right to do that, because what we will sacrifice to the LORD our God is detestable to the Egyptians. If we sacrifice what the Egyptians detest in front of them, won't they stone us?
02Ex 8:27 We must go a distance of three days into the wilderness and sacrifice to the LORD our God as He instructs us."
02Ex 8:28 Pharaoh responded, "I will let you go and sacrifice to the LORD your God in the wilderness, but don't go very far. Make an appeal for me."
02Ex 8:29 "As soon as I leave you," Moses said, "I will appeal to the Lord, and tomorrow the swarms of flies will depart from Pharaoh, his officials, and his people. But Pharaoh must not act deceptively again by refusing to let the people go and sacrifice to the LORD."
02Ex 8:30 Then Moses left Pharaoh's presence and appealed to the LORD.
02Ex 8:31 The LORD did as Moses had said: He removed the swarms of flies from Pharaoh, his officials, and his people; not one was left.
02Ex 8:32 But Pharaoh hardened his heart this time also and did not let the people go.
02Ex 9:1 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Go in to Pharaoh and say to him: This is what the LORD, the God of the Hebrews, says: Let My people go, so that they may worship Me.
02Ex 9:2 But if you refuse to let [them] go and keep holding them,
02Ex 9:3 then the LORD's hand will bring a severe plague against your livestock in the field-- the horses, donkeys, camels, herds, and flocks.
02Ex 9:4 But the LORD will make a distinction between the livestock of Israel and the livestock of Egypt, so that nothing of all that the Israelites own will die."
02Ex 9:5 And the LORD set a time, saying, "Tomorrow the LORD will do this thing in the land."
02Ex 9:6 The LORD did this the next day. All the Egyptian livestock died, but none among the Israelite livestock died.
02Ex 9:7 Pharaoh sent [messengers] who saw that not a single one of the Israelite livestock was dead. But Pharaoh's heart was hardened, and he did not let the people go.
02Ex 9:8 Then the LORD said to Moses and Aaron, "Take handfuls of furnace soot, and Moses is to throw it toward heaven in the sight of Pharaoh.
02Ex 9:9 It will become fine dust over the entire land of Egypt. It will become festering boils on people and animals throughout the land of Egypt."
02Ex 9:10 So they took furnace soot and stood before Pharaoh. Moses threw it toward heaven, and it became festering boils on man and beast.
02Ex 9:11 The magicians could not stand before Moses because of the boils, for the boils were on the magicians as well as on all the Egyptians.
02Ex 9:12 But the LORD hardened Pharaoh's heart and he did not listen to them, as the LORD had told Moses.
02Ex 9:13 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Get up early in the morning and present yourself to Pharaoh. Tell him: This is what the LORD, the God of the Hebrews says: Let My people go, so that they may worship Me.
02Ex 9:14 Otherwise, I am going to send all My plagues against you, your officials, and your people. Then you will know there is no one like Me in all the earth.
02Ex 9:15 By now I could have stretched out My hand and struck you and your people with a plague, and you would have been obliterated from the earth.
02Ex 9:16 However, I have let you live for this purpose: to show you My power and to make My name known in all the earth.
02Ex 9:17 You are still acting arrogantly against My people by not letting them go.
02Ex 9:18 Tomorrow at this time I will rain down the worst hail that has ever occurred in Egypt from the day it was founded until now.
02Ex 9:19 Therefore give orders to bring your livestock and all that you have in the field into shelters. Every person and animal that is in the field and not brought inside will die when the hail falls on them."
02Ex 9:20 Those among Pharaoh's officials who feared the word of the LORD made their servants and livestock flee to shelters,
02Ex 9:21 but those who didn't take the LORD's word seriously left their servants and livestock in the field.
02Ex 9:22 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Stretch out your hand toward heaven and let there be hail throughout the land of Egypt-- on man and beast and every plant of the field in the land of Egypt."
02Ex 9:23 So Moses stretched out his staff toward heaven, and the LORD sent thunder and hail. Lightning struck the earth, and the LORD rained hail on the land of Egypt.
02Ex 9:24 The hail, with lightning flashing through it, was so severe that nothing like it had occurred in the land of Egypt since it had become a nation.
02Ex 9:25 Throughout the land of Egypt, the hail struck down everything in the field, both man and beast. The hail beat down every plant of the field and shattered every tree in the field.
02Ex 9:26 The only place it didn't hail was in the land of Goshen where the Israelites were.
02Ex 9:27 Pharaoh sent for Moses and Aaron. "I have sinned this time," he said to them. "The LORD is the Righteous One, and I and my people are the guilty ones.
02Ex 9:28 Make an appeal to the LORD. There has been enough of God's thunder and hail. I will let you go; you don't need to stay any longer."
02Ex 9:29 Moses said to him, "When I have left the city, I will extend my hands to the LORD. The thunder will cease, and there will be no more hail, so that you may know the earth is the LORD's.
02Ex 9:30 But as for you and your officials, I know that you still do not fear the LORD God."
02Ex 9:31 The flax and the barley were destroyed because the barley was ripe and the flax was budding,
02Ex 9:32 but the wheat and the spelt were not destroyed since they are later crops.
02Ex 9:33 Moses went out from Pharaoh and the city, and extended his hands to the LORD. Then the thunder and hail ceased, and rain no longer poured down on the land.
02Ex 9:34 When Pharaoh saw that the rain, hail, and thunder had ceased, he sinned again and hardened his heart, he and his officials.
02Ex 9:35 So Pharaoh's heart hardened, and he did not let the Israelites go, as the LORD had said through Moses.
02Ex 10:1 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Go to Pharaoh, for I have hardened his heart and the hearts of his officials so that I may do these miraculous signs of Mine among them,
02Ex 10:2 and so that you may tell your son and grandson how severely I dealt with the Egyptians and performed miraculous signs among them, and you will know that I am the LORD."
02Ex 10:3 So Moses and Aaron went in to Pharaoh and told him, "This is what the LORD, the God of the Hebrews, says: How long will you refuse to humble yourself before Me? Let My people go, that they may worship Me.
02Ex 10:4 But if you refuse to let My people go, then tomorrow I will bring locusts into your territory.
02Ex 10:5 They will cover the surface of the land so that no one will be able to see the land. They will eat the remainder left to you that escaped the hail; they will eat every tree you have growing in the fields.
02Ex 10:6 They will fill your houses, all your officials' houses, and the houses of all the Egyptians-- something your fathers and ancestors never saw since the time they occupied the land until today." Then he turned and left Pharaoh's presence.
02Ex 10:7 Pharaoh's officials asked him, "How long must this man be a snare to us? Let the men go, so that they may worship the LORD their God. Don't you realize yet that Egypt is devastated?"
02Ex 10:8 So Moses and Aaron were brought back to Pharaoh. "Go, worship the LORD your God," Pharaoh said. "But exactly who will be going?"
02Ex 10:9 Moses replied, "We will go with our young and our old; we will go with our sons and daughters and with our flocks and herds because we must hold the LORD's festival."
02Ex 10:10 He said to them, "May the LORD be with you if I [ever] let you and your families go! Look out-- you are planning evil.
02Ex 10:11 No, only the men may go and worship the LORD, for that is what you have been asking for." And they were driven from Pharaoh's presence.
02Ex 10:12 The LORD then said to Moses, "Stretch out your hand over the land of Egypt and the locusts will come up over it and eat every plant in the land, everything that the hail left."
02Ex 10:13 So Moses stretched out his staff over the land of Egypt, and the LORD sent an east wind over the land all that day and through the night. By morning the east wind had brought in the locusts.
02Ex 10:14 The locusts went up over the entire land of Egypt and settled on the whole territory of Egypt. Never before had there been such a large number of locusts, and there will never be again.
02Ex 10:15 They covered the surface of the whole land so that the land was black, and they consumed all the plants on the ground and all the fruit on the trees that the hail had left. Nothing green was left on the trees or the plants in the field throughout the land of Egypt.
02Ex 10:16 Pharaoh urgently sent for Moses and Aaron and said, "I have sinned against the LORD your God and against you.
02Ex 10:17 Please forgive my sin once more and make an appeal to the LORD your God, so that He will take this death away from me."
02Ex 10:18 Moses left Pharaoh's presence and appealed to the LORD.
02Ex 10:19 Then the LORD changed the wind to a strong west wind, and it carried off the locusts and blew them into the Red Sea. Not a single locust was left in all the territory of Egypt.
02Ex 10:20 But the LORD hardened Pharaoh's heart, and he did not let the Israelites go.
02Ex 10:21 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Stretch out your hand toward heaven, and there will be darkness over the land of Egypt, a darkness that can be felt."
02Ex 10:22 So Moses stretched out his hand toward heaven, and there was thick darkness throughout the land of Egypt for three days.
02Ex 10:23 One person could not see another, and for three days they did not move from where they were. Yet all the Israelites had light where they lived.
02Ex 10:24 Pharaoh summoned Moses and said, "Go, worship the LORD. Even your families may go with you; only your flocks and your herds must stay behind."
02Ex 10:25 Moses responded, "You must also let us have sacrifices and burnt offerings to prepare for the LORD our God.
02Ex 10:26 Even our livestock must go with us; not a hoof will be left behind because we will take some of them to worship the LORD our God. We will not know what we will use to worship the LORD until we get there."
02Ex 10:27 But the LORD hardened Pharaoh's heart, and he was unwilling to let them go.
02Ex 10:28 Pharaoh said to him, "Leave me! Make sure you never see my face again, for on the day you see my face, you will die."
02Ex 10:29 "As you've said," Moses replied, "I will never see your face again."
02Ex 11:1 The LORD said to Moses, "I will bring one more plague on Pharaoh and on Egypt. After that, he will let you go from here. When he lets [you] go, he will drive you out of here.
02Ex 11:2 Now announce to the people that both men and women should ask their neighbors for gold and silver jewelry."
02Ex 11:3 The LORD gave the people favor in the sight of the Egyptians. And the man Moses was feared in the land of Egypt, by Pharaoh's officials and the people.
02Ex 11:4 So Moses said, "This is what the LORD says: 'About midnight I will go throughout Egypt
02Ex 11:5 and every firstborn [male] in the land of Egypt will die, from the firstborn of Pharaoh who sits on his throne to the firstborn of the servant girl who is behind the millstones, as well as every firstborn of the livestock.
02Ex 11:6 Then there will be a great cry of anguish through all the land of Egypt such as never was before, or ever will be again.
02Ex 11:7 But against all the Israelites, whether man or beast, not [even] a dog will snarl, so that you may know that the LORD makes a distinction between Egypt and Israel.
02Ex 11:8 All these officials of yours will come down to me and bow before me, saying: Leave, you and all the people who follow you. After that, I will leave.' " And he left Pharaoh's presence in fierce anger.
02Ex 11:9 The LORD said to Moses, "Pharaoh will not listen to you, so that My wonders may be multiplied in the land of Egypt."
02Ex 11:10 Moses and Aaron did all these wonders before Pharaoh, but the LORD hardened Pharaoh's heart, and he would not let the Israelites go out of his land.
02Ex 12:1 The LORD said to Moses and Aaron in the land of Egypt:
02Ex 12:2 "This month is to be the beginning of months for you; it is the first month of your year.
02Ex 12:3 Tell the whole community of Israel that on the tenth day of this month they must each select an animal of the flock according to [their] fathers' households, one animal per household.
02Ex 12:4 If the household is too small for a [whole] animal, that person and the neighbor nearest his house are to select one based on the combined number of people; you should apportion the animal according to what each person will eat.
02Ex 12:5 You must have an unblemished animal, a year-old male; you may take it from either the sheep or the goats.
02Ex 12:6 You are to keep it until the fourteenth day of this month; then the whole assembly of the community of Israel will slaughter the animals at twilight.
02Ex 12:7 They must take some of the blood and put it on the two doorposts and the lintel of the houses in which they eat them.
02Ex 12:8 They are to eat the meat that night; they should eat it, roasted over the fire along with unleavened bread and bitter herbs.
02Ex 12:9 Do not eat any of it raw or cooked in boiling water, but only roasted over fire-- its head as well as its legs and inner organs.
02Ex 12:10 Do not let any of it remain until morning; you must burn up any part of it that does remain until morning.
02Ex 12:11 Here is how you must eat it: dressed for travel, your sandals on your feet, and your staff in your hand. You are to eat it in a hurry; it is the LORD's Passover.
02Ex 12:12 "I will pass through the land of Egypt on that night and strike every firstborn [male] in the land of Egypt, both man and beast. I am the LORD; I will execute judgments against all the gods of Egypt.
02Ex 12:13 The blood on the houses where you are staying will be a distinguishing mark for you; when I see the blood, I will pass over you. No plague will be among you to destroy [you] when I strike the land of Egypt.
02Ex 12:14 "This day is to be a memorial for you, and you must celebrate it as a festival to the LORD. You are to celebrate it throughout your generations as a permanent statute.
02Ex 12:15 You must eat unleavened bread for seven days. On the first day you must remove yeast from your houses. Whoever eats what is leavened from the first day through the seventh day must be cut off from Israel.
02Ex 12:16 You are to hold a sacred assembly on the first day and another sacred assembly on the seventh day. No work may be done on those [days] except for preparing what people need to eat-- you may do only that.
02Ex 12:17 "You are to observe the [Festival of] Unleavened Bread because on this very day I brought your ranks out of the land of Egypt. You must observe this day throughout your generations as a permanent statute.
02Ex 12:18 You are to eat unleavened bread in the first [month], from the evening of the fourteenth day of the month until the evening of the twenty-first day.
02Ex 12:19 Yeast must not be found in your houses for seven days. If anyone eats something leavened, that person, whether a foreign resident or native of the land, must be cut off from the community of Israel.
02Ex 12:20 Do not eat anything leavened; eat unleavened bread in all your homes."
02Ex 12:21 Then Moses summoned all the elders of Israel and said to them, "Go, select an animal from the flock according to your families, and slaughter the Passover lamb.
02Ex 12:22 Take a cluster of hyssop, dip it in the blood that is in the basin, and brush the lintel and the two doorposts with some of the blood in the basin. None of you may go out the door of his house until morning.
02Ex 12:23 When the LORD passes through to strike Egypt and sees the blood on the lintel and the two doorposts, He will pass over the door and not let the destroyer enter your houses to strike [you].
02Ex 12:24 "Keep this command permanently as a statute for you and your descendants.
02Ex 12:25 When you enter the land that the LORD will give you as He promised, you are to observe this ritual.
02Ex 12:26 When your children ask you, 'What does this ritual mean to you?'
02Ex 12:27 you are to reply, 'It is the Passover sacrifice to the LORD, for He passed over the houses of the Israelites in Egypt when He struck the Egyptians and spared our homes.' " So the people bowed down and worshiped.
02Ex 12:28 Then the Israelites went and did [this]; they did just as the LORD had commanded Moses and Aaron.
02Ex 12:29 Now at midnight the LORD struck every firstborn [male] in the land of Egypt, from the firstborn of Pharaoh who sat on his throne to the firstborn of the prisoner who was in the dungeon, and every firstborn of the livestock.
02Ex 12:30 During the night Pharaoh got up, he along with all his officials and all the Egyptians, and there was a loud wailing throughout Egypt because there wasn't a house without someone dead.
02Ex 12:31 He summoned Moses and Aaron during the night and said, "Get up, leave my people, both you and the Israelites, and go, worship the LORD as you have asked.
02Ex 12:32 Take even your flocks and your herds as you asked, and leave, and this will also be a blessing to me."
02Ex 12:33 Now the Egyptians pressured the people in order to send them quickly out of the country, for they said, "We're all going to die!"
02Ex 12:34 So the people took their dough before it was leavened, with their kneading bowls wrapped up in their clothes on their shoulders.
02Ex 12:35 The Israelites acted on Moses' word and asked the Egyptians for silver and gold jewelry and for clothing.
02Ex 12:36 And the LORD gave the people such favor in the Egyptians' sight that they gave them what they requested. In this way they plundered the Egyptians.
02Ex 12:37 The Israelites traveled from Rameses to Succoth, about 600,000 soldiers on foot, besides their families.
02Ex 12:38 An ethnically diverse crowd also went up with them, along with a huge number of livestock, both flocks and herds.
02Ex 12:39 The people baked the dough they had brought out of Egypt into unleavened loaves, since it had no yeast; for when they had been driven out of Egypt they could not delay and had not prepared any provisions for themselves.
02Ex 12:40 The time that the Israelites lived in Egypt was 430 years.
02Ex 12:41 At the end of 430 years, on that same day, all the divisions of the LORD went out from the land of Egypt.
02Ex 12:42 It was a night of vigil in honor of the LORD, because He would bring them out of the land of Egypt. This same night is in honor of the LORD, a night vigil for all the Israelites throughout their generations.
02Ex 12:43 The LORD said to Moses and Aaron, "This is the statute of the Passover: no foreigner may eat it.
02Ex 12:44 But any slave a man has purchased may eat it, after you have circumcised him.
02Ex 12:45 A temporary resident or hired hand may not eat the Passover.
02Ex 12:46 It is to be eaten in one house. You may not take any of the meat outside the house, and you may not break any of its bones.
02Ex 12:47 The whole community of Israel must celebrate it.
02Ex 12:48 If a foreigner resides with you and wants to celebrate the LORD's Passover, every male in his household must be circumcised, and then he may participate; he will become like a native of the land. But no uncircumcised person may eat it.
02Ex 12:49 The same law will apply to both the native and the foreigner who resides among you."
02Ex 12:50 Then all the Israelites did [this]; they did just as the LORD had commanded Moses and Aaron.
02Ex 12:51 On that same day the LORD brought the Israelites out of the land of Egypt according to their military divisions.
02Ex 13:1 The LORD spoke to Moses:
02Ex 13:2 "Consecrate every firstborn male to Me, the firstborn from every womb among the Israelites, both man and animal; it is Mine."
02Ex 13:3 Then Moses said to the people, "Remember this day when you came out of Egypt, out of the place of slavery, for the LORD brought you out of here by the strength of [His] hand. Nothing leavened may be eaten.
02Ex 13:4 Today, in the month of Abib, you are leaving.
02Ex 13:5 When the LORD brings you into the land of the Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Hivites, and Jebusites, which He swore to your fathers that He would give you, a land flowing with milk and honey, you must carry out this ritual in this month.
02Ex 13:6 For seven days you must eat unleavened bread, and on the seventh day there is to be a festival to the LORD.
02Ex 13:7 Unleavened bread is to be eaten for those seven days. Nothing leavened may be found among you, and no yeast may be found among you in all your territory.
02Ex 13:8 On that day explain to your son, 'This is because of what the LORD did for me when I came out of Egypt.'
02Ex 13:9 Let it serve as a sign for you on your hand and as a reminder on your forehead, so that the law of the LORD may be in your mouth; for the LORD brought you out of Egypt with a strong hand.
02Ex 13:10 Keep this statute at its appointed time from year to year.
02Ex 13:11 "When the LORD brings you into the land of the Canaanites, as He swore to you and your fathers, and gives it to you,
02Ex 13:12 you are to present to the LORD every firstborn male of the womb. All firstborn offspring of the livestock you own that are males will be the LORD's.
02Ex 13:13 You must redeem every firstborn of a donkey with a flock animal, but if you do not redeem it, break its neck. However, you must redeem every firstborn among your sons.
02Ex 13:14 "In the future, when your son asks you, 'What does this mean?' say to him, 'By the strength of [His] hand the LORD brought us out of Egypt, out of the place of slavery.
02Ex 13:15 When Pharaoh stubbornly refused to let us go, the LORD killed every firstborn [male] in the land of Egypt, from the firstborn of man to the firstborn of livestock. That is why I sacrifice to the LORD all the firstborn of the womb that are males, but I redeem all the firstborn of my sons.'
02Ex 13:16 So let it be a sign on your hand and a symbol on your forehead, for the LORD brought us out of Egypt by the strength of His hand."
02Ex 13:17 When Pharaoh let the people go, God did not lead them along the road to the land of the Philistines, even though it was nearby; for God said, "The people will change their minds and return to Egypt if they face war."
02Ex 13:18 So He led the people around toward the Red Sea along the road of the wilderness. And the Israelites left the land of Egypt in battle formation.
02Ex 13:19 Moses took the bones of Joseph with him, because Joseph had made the Israelites swear a solemn oath, saying, "God will certainly come to your aid; then you must take my bones with you from this place."
02Ex 13:20 They set out from Succoth and camped at Etham on the edge of the wilderness.
02Ex 13:21 The LORD went ahead of them in a pillar of cloud to lead them on their way during the day and in a pillar of fire to give them light at night, so that they could travel day or night.
02Ex 13:22 The pillar of cloud by day and the pillar of fire by night never left its place in front of the people.
02Ex 14:1 Then the LORD spoke to Moses:
02Ex 14:2 "Tell the Israelites to turn back and camp in front of Pi-hahiroth, between Migdol and the sea; you must camp in front of Baal-zephon, facing it by the sea.
02Ex 14:3 Pharaoh will say of the Israelites: They are wandering around the land in confusion; the wilderness has boxed them in.
02Ex 14:4 I will harden Pharaoh's heart so that he will pursue them. Then I will receive glory by means of Pharaoh and all his army, and the Egyptians will know that I am the LORD." So the Israelites did this.
02Ex 14:5 When the king of Egypt was told that the people had fled, Pharaoh and his officials changed their minds about the people and said: "What have we done? We have released Israel from serving us."
02Ex 14:6 So he got his chariot ready and took his troops with him;
02Ex 14:7 he took 600 of the best chariots and all the rest of the chariots of Egypt, with officers in each one.
02Ex 14:8 The LORD hardened the heart of Pharaoh king of Egypt, and he pursued the Israelites, who were going out triumphantly.
02Ex 14:9 The Egyptians-- all Pharaoh's horses and chariots, his horsemen, and his army-- chased after them and caught up with them as they camped by the sea beside Pi-hahiroth, in front of Baal-zephon.
02Ex 14:10 As Pharaoh approached, the Israelites looked up and saw the Egyptians coming after them. Then the Israelites were terrified and cried out to the LORD for help.
02Ex 14:11 They said to Moses: "Is it because there are no graves in Egypt that you took us to die in the wilderness? What have you done to us by bringing us out of Egypt?
02Ex 14:12 Isn't this what we told you in Egypt: Leave us alone so that we may serve the Egyptians? It would have been better for us to serve the Egyptians than to die in the wilderness."
02Ex 14:13 But Moses said to the people, "Don't be afraid. Stand firm and see the LORD's salvation He will provide for you today; for the Egyptians you see today, you will never see again.
02Ex 14:14 The LORD will fight for you; you must be quiet."
02Ex 14:15 The LORD said to Moses, "Why are you crying out to Me? Tell the Israelites to break camp.
02Ex 14:16 As for you, lift up your staff, stretch out your hand over the sea, and divide it so that the Israelites can go through the sea on dry ground.
02Ex 14:17 I am going to harden the hearts of the Egyptians so that they will go in after them, and I will receive glory by means of Pharaoh, all his army, and his chariots and horsemen.
02Ex 14:18 The Egyptians will know that I am the LORD when I receive glory through Pharaoh, his chariots, and his horsemen."
02Ex 14:19 Then the Angel of God, who was going in front of the Israelite forces, moved and went behind them. The pillar of cloud moved from in front of them and stood behind them.
02Ex 14:20 It came between the Egyptian and Israelite forces. The cloud was there [in] the darkness, yet it lit up the night. So neither group came near the other all night long.
02Ex 14:21 Then Moses stretched out his hand over the sea. The LORD drove the sea [back] with a powerful east wind all that night and turned the sea into dry land. So the waters were divided,
02Ex 14:22 and the Israelites went through the sea on dry ground, with the waters [like] a wall to them on their right and their left.
02Ex 14:23 The Egyptians set out in pursuit-- all Pharaoh's horses, his chariots, and his horsemen-- and went into the sea after them.
02Ex 14:24 Then during the morning watch, the LORD looked down on the Egyptian forces from the pillar of fire and cloud, and threw them into confusion.
02Ex 14:25 He caused their chariot wheels to swerve and made them drive with difficulty. "Let's get away from Israel," the Egyptians said, "because the LORD is fighting for them against Egypt!"
02Ex 14:26 Then the LORD said to Moses, "Stretch out your hand over the sea so that the waters may come back on the Egyptians, on their chariots and horsemen."
02Ex 14:27 So Moses stretched out his hand over the sea, and at daybreak the sea returned to its normal depth. While the Egyptians were trying to escape from it, the LORD overthrew them in the sea.
02Ex 14:28 The waters came back and covered the chariots and horsemen, the entire army of Pharaoh, that had gone after them into the sea. None of them survived.
02Ex 14:29 But the Israelites had walked through the sea on dry ground, with the waters [like] a wall to them on their right and their left.
02Ex 14:30 That day the LORD saved Israel from the power of the Egyptians, and Israel saw the Egyptians dead on the seashore.
02Ex 14:31 When Israel saw the great power that the LORD used against the Egyptians, the people feared the LORD and believed in Him and in His servant Moses.
02Ex 15:1 Then Moses and the Israelites sang this song to the LORD. They said: I will sing to the LORD, for He is highly exalted; He has thrown the horse and its rider into the sea.
02Ex 15:2 The LORD is my strength and my song; He has become my salvation. This is my God, and I will praise Him, my father's God, and I will exalt Him.
02Ex 15:3 The LORD is a warrior; Yahweh is His name.
02Ex 15:4 He threw Pharaoh's chariots and his army into the sea; the elite of his officers were drowned in the Red Sea.
02Ex 15:5 The floods covered them; they sank to the depths like a stone.
02Ex 15:6 LORD, Your right hand is glorious in power. LORD, Your right hand shattered the enemy.
02Ex 15:7 You overthrew Your adversaries by Your great majesty. You unleashed Your burning wrath; it consumed them like stubble.
02Ex 15:8 The waters heaped up at the blast of Your nostrils; the currents stood firm like a dam. The watery depths congealed in the heart of the sea.
02Ex 15:9 The enemy said: "I will pursue, I will overtake, I will divide the spoil. My desire will be gratified at their expense. I will draw my sword; my hand will destroy them."
02Ex 15:10 But You blew with Your breath, and the sea covered them. They sank like lead in the mighty waters.
02Ex 15:11 LORD, who is like You among the gods? Who is like You, glorious in holiness, revered with praises, performing wonders?
02Ex 15:12 You stretched out Your right hand, and the earth swallowed them.
02Ex 15:13 You will lead the people You have redeemed with Your faithful love; You will guide [them] to Your holy dwelling with Your strength.
02Ex 15:14 When the peoples hear, they will shudder; anguish will seize the inhabitants of Philistia.
02Ex 15:15 Then the chiefs of Edom will be terrified; trembling will seize the leaders of Moab; the inhabitants of Canaan will panic;
02Ex 15:16 and terror and dread will fall on them. They will be as still as a stone because of Your powerful arm until Your people pass by, LORD, until the people whom You purchased pass by.
02Ex 15:17 You will bring them in and plant them on the mountain of Your possession; LORD, You have prepared the place for Your dwelling; Lord, Your hands have established the sanctuary.
02Ex 15:18 The LORD will reign forever and ever!
02Ex 15:19 When Pharaoh's horses with his chariots and horsemen went into the sea, the LORD brought the waters of the sea back over them. But the Israelites walked through the sea on dry ground.
02Ex 15:20 Then Miriam the prophetess, Aaron's sister, took a tambourine in her hand, and all the women followed her with tambourines and dancing.
02Ex 15:21 Miriam sang to them: Sing to the Lord, for He is highly exalted; He has thrown the horse and its rider into the sea.
02Ex 15:22 Then Moses led Israel on from the Red Sea, and they went out to the Wilderness of Shur. They journeyed for three days in the wilderness without finding water.
02Ex 15:23 They came to Marah, but they could not drink the water at Marah because it was bitter-- that is why it was named Marah.
02Ex 15:24 The people grumbled to Moses, "What are we going to drink?"
02Ex 15:25 So he cried out to the LORD, and the LORD showed him a tree. When he threw it into the water, the water became drinkable. He made a statute and ordinance for them at Marah and He tested them there.
02Ex 15:26 He said, "If you will carefully obey the LORD your God, do what is right in His eyes, pay attention to His commands, and keep all His statutes, I will not inflict any illness on you I inflicted on the Egyptians. For I am the LORD who heals you."
02Ex 15:27 Then they came to Elim, where there were 12 springs of water and 70 date palms, and they camped there by the waters.
02Ex 16:1 The entire Israelite community departed from Elim and came to the Wilderness of Sin, which is between Elim and Sinai, on the fifteenth day of the second month after they had left the land of Egypt.
02Ex 16:2 The entire Israelite community grumbled against Moses and Aaron in the wilderness.
02Ex 16:3 The Israelites said to them, "If only we had died by the LORD's hand in the land of Egypt, when we sat by pots of meat and ate all the bread we wanted. Instead, you brought us into this wilderness to make this whole assembly die of hunger!"
02Ex 16:4 Then the LORD said to Moses, "I am going to rain bread from heaven for you. The people are to go out each day and gather enough for that day. This way I will test them to see whether or not they will follow My instructions.
02Ex 16:5 On the sixth day, when they prepare what they bring in, it will be twice as much as they gather on other days."
02Ex 16:6 So Moses and Aaron said to all the Israelites: "This evening you will know that it was the LORD who brought you out of the land of Egypt;
02Ex 16:7 in the morning you will see the LORD's glory because He has heard your complaints about Him. For who are we that you complain about us?"
02Ex 16:8 Moses continued, "The LORD will give you meat to eat this evening and abundant bread in the morning, for He has heard the complaints that you are raising against Him. Who are we? Your complaints are not against us but against the LORD."
02Ex 16:9 Then Moses told Aaron, "Say to the entire Israelite community, 'Come before the LORD, for He has heard your complaints.'"
02Ex 16:10 As Aaron was speaking to the entire Israelite community, they turned toward the wilderness, and there, in a cloud, the LORD's glory appeared.
02Ex 16:11 The LORD spoke to Moses,
02Ex 16:12 "I have heard the complaints of the Israelites. Tell them: At twilight you will eat meat, and in the morning you will eat bread until you are full. Then you will know that I am the LORD your God."
02Ex 16:13 So at evening quail came and covered the camp. In the morning there was a layer of dew all around the camp.
02Ex 16:14 When the layer of dew evaporated, there on the desert surface were fine flakes, as fine as frost on the ground.
02Ex 16:15 When the Israelites saw it, they asked one another, "What is it?" because they didn't know what it was. Moses told them, "It is the bread the LORD has given you to eat.
02Ex 16:16 This is what the LORD has commanded: 'Gather as much of it as each person needs to eat. You may take two quarts per individual, according to the number of people each of you has in his tent.'"
02Ex 16:17 So the Israelites did this. Some gathered a lot, some a little.
02Ex 16:18 When they measured it by quarts, the person who gathered a lot had no surplus, and the person who gathered a little had no shortage. Each gathered as much as he needed to eat.
02Ex 16:19 Moses said to them, "No one is to let any of it remain until morning."
02Ex 16:20 But they didn't listen to Moses; some people left part of it until morning, and it bred worms and smelled. Therefore Moses was angry with them.
02Ex 16:21 They gathered it every morning. Each gathered as much as he needed to eat, but when the sun grew hot, it melted.
02Ex 16:22 On the sixth day they gathered twice as much food, four quarts apiece, and all the leaders of the community came and reported [this] to Moses.
02Ex 16:23 He told them, "This is what the LORD has said: 'Tomorrow is a day of complete rest, a holy Sabbath to the LORD. Bake what you want to bake, and boil what you want to boil, and everything left over set aside to be kept until morning.'"
02Ex 16:24 So they set it aside until morning as Moses commanded, and it didn't smell or have any maggots in it.
02Ex 16:25 "Eat it today," Moses said, "because today is a Sabbath to the LORD. Today you won't find any in the field.
02Ex 16:26 For six days you may gather it, but on the seventh day, the Sabbath, there will be none."
02Ex 16:27 Yet on the seventh day some of the people went out to gather, but they did not find any.
02Ex 16:28 Then the LORD said to Moses, "How long will you refuse to keep My commands and instructions?
02Ex 16:29 Understand that the LORD has given you the Sabbath; therefore on the sixth day He will give you two days' worth of bread. Each of you stay where you are; no one is to leave his place on the seventh day."
02Ex 16:30 So the people rested on the seventh day.
02Ex 16:31 The house of Israel named the substance manna. It resembled coriander seed, was white, and tasted like wafers [made] with honey.
02Ex 16:32 Moses said, "This is what the LORD has commanded: 'Two quarts of it are to be preserved throughout your generations, so that they may see the bread I fed you in the wilderness when I brought you out of the land of Egypt.'"
02Ex 16:33 Moses told Aaron, "Take a container and put two quarts of manna in it. Then place it before the LORD to be preserved throughout your generations."
02Ex 16:34 As the LORD commanded Moses, Aaron placed it before the testimony to be preserved.
02Ex 16:35 The Israelites ate manna for 40 years, until they came to an inhabited land. They ate manna until they reached the border of the land of Canaan.
02Ex 16:36 (Two quarts are a tenth of an ephah.)
02Ex 17:1 The entire Israelite community left the Wilderness of Sin, moving from one place to the next according to the LORD's command. They camped at Rephidim, but there was no water for the people to drink.
02Ex 17:2 So the people complained to Moses: "Give us water to drink." "Why are you complaining to me?" Moses replied to them. "Why are you testing the LORD?"
02Ex 17:3 But the people thirsted there for water, and grumbled against Moses. They said, "Why did you ever bring us out of Egypt to kill us and our children and our livestock with thirst?"
02Ex 17:4 Then Moses cried out to the LORD, "What should I do with these people? In a little while they will stone me!"
02Ex 17:5 The LORD answered Moses, "Go on ahead of the people and take some of the elders of Israel with you. Take the rod you struck the Nile with in your hand and go.
02Ex 17:6 I am going to stand there in front of you on the rock at Horeb; when you hit the rock, water will come out of it and the people will drink." Moses did this in the sight of the elders of Israel.
02Ex 17:7 He named the place Massah and Meribah because the Israelites complained, and because they tested the LORD, saying, "Is the LORD among us or not?"
02Ex 17:8 At Rephidim, Amalek came and fought against Israel.
02Ex 17:9 Moses said to Joshua, "Select some men for us, and go fight against Amalek. Tomorrow I will stand on the hilltop with God's staff in my hand."
02Ex 17:10 Joshua did as Moses had told him, and fought against Amalek, while Moses, Aaron, and Hur went up to the top of the hill.
02Ex 17:11 While Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed, but whenever he put his hand down, Amalek prevailed.
02Ex 17:12 When Moses' hands grew heavy, they took a stone and put [it] under him, and he sat down on it. Then Aaron and Hur supported his hands, one on one side and one on the other so that his hands remained steady until the sun went down.
02Ex 17:13 So Joshua defeated Amalek and his army with the sword.
02Ex 17:14 The LORD then said to Moses, "Write this down on a scroll as a reminder and recite it to Joshua: I will completely blot out the memory of Amalek under heaven."
02Ex 17:15 And Moses built an altar and named it, "The LORD Is My Banner."
02Ex 17:16 He said, "Indeed, [my] hand is [lifted up] toward the LORD's throne. The LORD will be at war with Amalek from generation to generation."
02Ex 18:1 Moses' father-in-law Jethro, the priest of Midian, heard about everything that God had done for Moses and His people Israel, and how the LORD had brought Israel out of Egypt.
02Ex 18:2 Now Jethro, Moses' father-in-law, had taken in Zipporah, Moses' wife, after he had sent her back,
02Ex 18:3 along with her two sons, one of whom was named Gershom (because Moses had said, "I have been a stranger in a foreign land")
02Ex 18:4 and the other Eliezer (because [he had said,] "The God of my father was my helper and delivered me from Pharaoh's sword").
02Ex 18:5 Moses' father-in-law Jethro, along with Moses' wife and sons, came to him in the wilderness where he was camped at the mountain of God.
02Ex 18:6 He sent word to Moses, "I, your father-in-law Jethro, am coming to you with your wife and her two sons."
02Ex 18:7 So Moses went out to meet his father-in-law, bowed down, and then kissed him. They asked each other how they had been and went into the tent.
02Ex 18:8 Moses recounted to his father-in-law all that the LORD had done to Pharaoh and the Egyptians for Israel's sake, all the hardships that confronted them on the way, and how the LORD delivered them.
02Ex 18:9 Jethro rejoiced over all the good things the LORD had done for Israel when He rescued them from the Egyptians.
02Ex 18:10 "Blessed is the LORD," Jethro exclaimed, "who rescued you from Pharaoh and the power of the Egyptians, and snatched the people from the power of the Egyptians.
02Ex 18:11 Now I know that the LORD is greater than all gods, because He [did wonders] at the time the Egyptians acted arrogantly against Israel."
02Ex 18:12 Then Jethro, Moses' father-in-law, brought a burnt offering and sacrifices to God, and Aaron came with all the elders of Israel to eat a meal with Moses' father-in-law in God's presence.
02Ex 18:13 The next day Moses sat down to judge the people, and they stood around Moses from morning until evening.
02Ex 18:14 When Moses' father-in-law saw everything he was doing for them he asked, "What is this thing you're doing for the people? Why are you alone sitting as judge, while all the people stand around you from morning until evening?"
02Ex 18:15 Moses replied to his father-in-law, "Because the people come to me to inquire of God.
02Ex 18:16 Whenever they have a dispute, it comes to me, and I make a decision between one man and another. I teach [them] God's statutes and laws."
02Ex 18:17 "What you're doing is not good," Moses' father-in-law said to him.
02Ex 18:18 "You will certainly wear out both yourself and these people who are with you, because the task is too heavy for you. You can't do it alone.
02Ex 18:19 Now listen to me; I will give you some advice, and God be with you. You be the one to represent the people before God and bring their cases to Him.
02Ex 18:20 Instruct them about the statutes and laws, and teach them the way to live and what they must do.
02Ex 18:21 But you should select from all the people able men, God-fearing, trustworthy, and hating bribes. Place [them] over the people as officials of thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens.
02Ex 18:22 They should judge the people at all times. Then they can bring you every important case but judge every minor case themselves. In this way you will lighten your load, and they will bear [it] with you.
02Ex 18:23 If you do this, and God [so] directs you, you will be able to endure, and also all these people will be able to go home satisfied."
02Ex 18:24 Moses listened to his father-in-law and did everything he said.
02Ex 18:25 So Moses chose able men from all Israel and made them leaders over the people [as] officials of thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens.
02Ex 18:26 They judged the people at all times; the hard cases they would bring to Moses, but every minor case they would judge themselves.
02Ex 18:27 Then Moses said goodbye to his father-in-law, and he journeyed to his own land.
02Ex 19:1 In the third month, on the same day [of the month] that the Israelites had left the land of Egypt, they entered the Wilderness of Sinai.
02Ex 19:2 After they departed from Rephidim, they entered the Wilderness of Sinai and camped in the wilderness, and Israel camped there in front of the mountain.
02Ex 19:3 Moses went up [the mountain] to God, and the LORD called to him from the mountain: "This is what you must say to the house of Jacob, and explain to the Israelites:
02Ex 19:4 You have seen what I did to the Egyptians and how I carried you on eagles' wings and brought you to Me.
02Ex 19:5 Now if you will listen to Me and carefully keep My covenant, you will be My own possession out of all the peoples, although all the earth is Mine,
02Ex 19:6 and you will be My kingdom of priests and My holy nation. These are the words that you are to say to the Israelites."
02Ex 19:7 After Moses came back, He summoned the elders of the people, and put before them all these words that the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 19:8 Then all the people responded together, "We will do all that the LORD has spoken." So Moses brought the people's words back to the LORD.
02Ex 19:9 The LORD said to Moses, "I am going to come to you in a dense cloud, so that the people will hear when I speak with you and will always believe you." Then Moses reported the people's words to the LORD.
02Ex 19:10 And the LORD told Moses, "Go to the people and purify them today and tomorrow. They must wash their clothes
02Ex 19:11 and be prepared by the third day, for on the third day the LORD will come down on Mount Sinai in the sight of all the people.
02Ex 19:12 Put boundaries for the people all around the [mountain] and say: Be careful that you don't go up on the mountain or touch its base. Anyone who touches the mountain will be put to death.
02Ex 19:13 No hand may touch him; instead he will be stoned or shot [with arrows], neither animal or man will live. When the ram's horn sounds a long blast, they may go up the mountain."
02Ex 19:14 Then Moses came down from the mountain to the people and consecrated them, and they washed their clothes.
02Ex 19:15 He said to the people, "Be prepared by the third day. Do not have sexual relations with women."
02Ex 19:16 On the third day, when morning came, there was thunder and lightning, a thick cloud on the mountain, and a loud trumpet sound, so that all the people in the camp shuddered.
02Ex 19:17 Then Moses brought the people out of the camp to meet God, and they stood at the foot of the mountain.
02Ex 19:18 Mount Sinai was completely enveloped in smoke because the LORD came down on it in fire. Its smoke went up like the smoke of a furnace, and the whole mountain shook violently.
02Ex 19:19 As the sound of the trumpet grew louder and louder, Moses spoke and God answered him in the thunder.
02Ex 19:20 The LORD came down on Mount Sinai, at the top of the mountain. Then the LORD summoned Moses to the top of the mountain, and he went up.
02Ex 19:21 The LORD directed Moses, "Go down and warn the people not to break through to see the LORD; otherwise many of them will die.
02Ex 19:22 Even the priests who come near the LORD must purify themselves or the LORD will break out [in anger] against them."
02Ex 19:23 But Moses responded to the LORD, "The people cannot come up Mount Sinai, since You warned us: Put a boundary around the mountain and consider it holy."
02Ex 19:24 And the LORD replied to him, "Go down and come back with Aaron. But the priests and the people must not break through to come up to the LORD, or He will break out [in anger] against them."
02Ex 19:25 So Moses went down to the people and told them.
02Ex 20:1 Then God spoke all these words:
02Ex 20:2 I am the LORD your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, out of the place of slavery.
02Ex 20:3 Do not have other gods besides Me.
02Ex 20:4 Do not make an idol for yourself, whether in the shape of anything in the heavens above or on the earth below or in the waters under the earth.
02Ex 20:5 You must not bow down to them or worship them; for I, the LORD your God, am a jealous God, punishing the children for the fathers' sin, to the third and fourth [generations] of those who hate Me,
02Ex 20:6 but showing faithful love to a thousand [generations] of those who love Me and keep My commands.
02Ex 20:7 Do not misuse the name of the LORD your God, because the LORD will punish anyone who misuses His name.
02Ex 20:8 Remember to dedicate the Sabbath day:
02Ex 20:9 You are to labor six days and do all your work,
02Ex 20:10 but the seventh day is a Sabbath to the LORD your God. You must not do any work-- you, your son or daughter, your male or female slave, your livestock, or the foreigner who is within your gates.
02Ex 20:11 For the LORD made the heavens and the earth, the sea, and everything in them in six days; then He rested on the seventh day. Therefore the LORD blessed the Sabbath day and declared it holy.
02Ex 20:12 Honor your father and your mother so that you may have a long life in the land that the LORD your God is giving you.
02Ex 20:13 Do not murder.
02Ex 20:14 Do not commit adultery.
02Ex 20:15 Do not steal.
02Ex 20:16 Do not give false testimony against your neighbor.
02Ex 20:17 Do not covet your neighbor's house. Do not covet your neighbor's wife, his male or female slave, his ox or donkey, or anything that belongs to your neighbor.
02Ex 20:18 All the people witnessed the thunder and lightning, the sound of the trumpet, and the mountain [surrounded by] smoke. When the people saw [it] they trembled and stood at a distance.
02Ex 20:19 "You speak to us, and we will listen," they said to Moses, "but don't let God speak to us, or we will die."
02Ex 20:20 Moses responded to the people, "Don't be afraid, for God has come to test you, so that you will fear Him and will not sin."
02Ex 20:21 And the people remained standing at a distance as Moses approached the thick darkness where God was.
02Ex 20:22 Then the LORD told Moses, "This is what you are to say to the Israelites: You have seen that I have spoken to you from heaven.
02Ex 20:23 You must not make gods of silver to rival Me; you must not make [gods of gold] for yourselves.
02Ex 20:24 "You must make an earthen altar for Me and sacrifice on it your burnt offerings and fellowship offerings, your sheep and goats, as well as your cattle. I will come to you and bless you in every place where I cause My name to be remembered.
02Ex 20:25 If you make a stone altar for Me, you must not build it out of cut stones. If you use your chisel on it, you will defile it.
02Ex 20:26 You must not go up to My altar on steps, so that your nakedness is not exposed on it.
02Ex 21:1 "These are the ordinances that you must set before them:
02Ex 21:2 "When you buy a Hebrew slave, he is to serve for six years; then in the seventh he is to leave as a free man without paying anything.
02Ex 21:3 If he arrives alone, he is to leave alone; if he arrives with a wife, his wife is to leave with him.
02Ex 21:4 If his master gives him a wife and she bears him sons or daughters, the wife and her children belong to her master, and the man must leave alone.
02Ex 21:5 "But if the slave declares: 'I love my master, my wife, and my children; I do not want to leave as a free man,'
02Ex 21:6 his master is to bring him to the judges and then bring him to the door or doorpost. His master must pierce his ear with an awl, and he will serve his master for life.
02Ex 21:7 "When a man sells his daughter as a slave, she is not to leave as the male slaves do.
02Ex 21:8 If she is displeasing to her master, who chose her for himself, then he must let her be redeemed. He has no right to sell her to foreigners because he has acted treacherously toward her.
02Ex 21:9 Or if he chooses her for his son, he must deal with her according to the customary treatment of daughters.
02Ex 21:10 If he takes an additional wife, he must not reduce the food, clothing, or marital rights of the first wife.
02Ex 21:11 And if he does not do these three things for her, she may leave free of charge, without any exchange of money.
02Ex 21:12 "Whoever strikes a person so that he dies must be put to death.
02Ex 21:13 But if he didn't intend any harm, and yet God caused it to happen by his hand, I will appoint a place for you where he may flee.
02Ex 21:14 If a person willfully acts against his neighbor to murder him by scheming, you must take him from My altar to be put to death.
02Ex 21:15 "Whoever strikes his father or his mother must be put to death.
02Ex 21:16 "Whoever kidnaps a person must be put to death, whether he sells him or the person is found in his possession.
02Ex 21:17 "Whoever curses his father or his mother must be put to death.
02Ex 21:18 "When men quarrel and one strikes the other with a stone or fist, and the injured man does not die but is confined to bed,
02Ex 21:19 if he can [later] get up and walk around outside [leaning] on his staff, then the one who struck [him] will be exempt from punishment. Nevertheless, he must pay for his lost work time and provide for [his] complete recovery.
02Ex 21:20 "When a man strikes his male or female slave with a rod, and the slave dies under his abuse, the owner must be punished.
02Ex 21:21 However, if the slave can stand up after a day or two, the owner should not be punished because he is his [owner's] property.
02Ex 21:22 "When men get in a fight, and hit a pregnant woman so that her children are born [prematurely], but there is no injury, the one who hit her must be fined as the woman's husband demands from him, and he must pay according to judicial assessment.
02Ex 21:23 If there is an injury, then you must give life for life,
02Ex 21:24 eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot,
02Ex 21:25 burn for burn, bruise for bruise, wound for wound.
02Ex 21:26 "When a man strikes the eye of his male or female slave and destroys it, he must let the slave go free in compensation for his eye.
02Ex 21:27 If he knocks out the tooth of his male or female slave, he must let the slave go free in compensation for his tooth.
02Ex 21:28 "When an ox gores a man or a woman to death, the ox must be stoned, and its meat may not be eaten, but the ox's owner is innocent.
02Ex 21:29 However, if the ox was in the habit of goring, and its owner has been warned yet does not restrain it, and it kills a man or a woman, the ox must be stoned, and its owner must also be put to death.
02Ex 21:30 If instead a ransom is demanded of him, he can pay a redemption price for his life in the full amount demanded from him.
02Ex 21:31 If it gores a son or a daughter, he is to be dealt with according to this same law.
02Ex 21:32 If the ox gores a male or female slave, he must give 30 shekels of silver to the slave's master, and the ox must be stoned.
02Ex 21:33 "When a man uncovers a pit or digs a pit, and does not cover it, and an ox or a donkey falls into it,
02Ex 21:34 the owner of the pit must give compensation; he must pay money to its owner, but the dead animal will become his.
02Ex 21:35 "When a man's ox injures his neighbor's ox and it dies, they must sell the live ox and divide its proceeds; they must also divide the dead animal.
02Ex 21:36 If, however, it is known that the ox was in the habit of goring, yet its owner has not restrained it, he must compensate fully, ox for ox; the dead animal will become his.
02Ex 22:1  "When a man steals an ox or a sheep and butchers it or sells it, he must repay five cattle for the ox or four sheep for the sheep.
02Ex 22:2  If a thief is caught in the act of breaking in, and he is beaten to death, no one is guilty of bloodshed.
02Ex 22:3 But if this happens after sunrise, there is guilt of bloodshed. A thief must make full restitution. If he is unable, he is to be sold because of his theft.
02Ex 22:4 If what was stolen-- whether ox, donkey, or sheep-- is actually found alive in his possession, he must repay double.
02Ex 22:5 "When a man lets a field or vineyard be grazed in, and then allows his animals to go and graze in someone else's field, he must repay with the best of his own field or vineyard.
02Ex 22:6 "When a fire gets out of control, spreads to thornbushes, and consumes stacks of cut grain, standing grain, or a field, the one who started the fire must make full restitution for what was burned.
02Ex 22:7 "When a man gives his neighbor money or goods to keep, but they are stolen from that person's house, the thief, if caught, must repay double.
02Ex 22:8 If the thief is not caught, the owner of the house must present himself to the judges to determine whether or not he has taken his neighbor's property.
02Ex 22:9 In any case of wrongdoing involving an ox, a donkey, a sheep, a garment, or anything [else] lost, and someone claims: That's mine, the case between the two parties is to come before the judges. The one the judges condemn must repay double to his neighbor.
02Ex 22:10 "When a man gives his neighbor a donkey, an ox, a sheep, or any [other] animal to care for, but it dies, is injured, or is stolen, while no one is watching,
02Ex 22:11 there must be an oath before the LORD between the two of them to determine whether or not he has taken his neighbor's property. Its owner must accept [the oath], and the other man does not have to make restitution.
02Ex 22:12 But if, in fact, the animal was stolen from his custody, he must make restitution to its owner.
02Ex 22:13 If it was actually torn apart [by a wild animal], he is to bring it as evidence; he does not have to make restitution for the torn carcass.
02Ex 22:14 "When a man borrows [an animal] from his neighbor, and it is injured or dies while its owner is not there with it, the man must make full restitution.
02Ex 22:15 If its owner is there with it, the man does not have to make restitution. If it was rented, the loss is covered by its rental price.
02Ex 22:16 "When a man seduces a virgin who was not promised in marriage, and he has sexual relations with her, he must certainly pay the bridal price for her to be his wife.
02Ex 22:17 If her father absolutely refuses to give her to him, he must pay an amount in silver equal to the bridal price for virgins.
02Ex 22:18 "You must not allow a sorceress to live.
02Ex 22:19 "Whoever has sexual intercourse with an animal must be put to death.
02Ex 22:20 "Whoever sacrifices to any gods, except the LORD alone, is to be set apart for destruction.
02Ex 22:21 "You must not exploit a foreign resident or oppress him, since you were foreigners in the land of Egypt.
02Ex 22:22 "You must not mistreat any widow or fatherless child.
02Ex 22:23 If you do mistreat them, they will no doubt cry to Me, and I will certainly hear their cry.
02Ex 22:24 My anger will burn, and I will kill you with the sword; then your wives will be widows and your children fatherless.
02Ex 22:25 "If you lend money to My people-- to the poor person among you, you must not be like a moneylender to him; you must not charge him interest.
02Ex 22:26 "If you ever take your neighbor's cloak as collateral, return it to him before sunset.
02Ex 22:27 For it is his only covering; it is the clothing for his body. What will he sleep in? And if he cries out to Me, I will listen because I am compassionate.
02Ex 22:28 "You must not blaspheme God or curse a leader among your people.
02Ex 22:29 "You must not hold back [offerings from] your harvest or your vats. Give Me the firstborn of your sons.
02Ex 22:30 Do the same with your cattle and your flock. Let them stay with their mothers for seven days, but on the eighth day you are to give them to Me.
02Ex 22:31 "Be My holy people. You must not eat the meat of a mauled animal [found] in the field; throw it to the dogs.
02Ex 23:1 "You must not spread a false report. Do not join the wicked to be a malicious witness.
02Ex 23:2 "You must not follow a crowd in wrongdoing. Do not testify in a lawsuit and go along with a crowd to pervert [justice].
02Ex 23:3 Do not show favoritism to a poor person in his lawsuit.
02Ex 23:4 "If you come across your enemy's stray ox or donkey, you must return it to him.
02Ex 23:5 "If you see the donkey of someone who hates you lying [helpless] under its load, and you want to refrain from helping it, you must help with it.
02Ex 23:6 "You must not deny justice to the poor among you in his lawsuit.
02Ex 23:7 Stay far away from a false accusation. Do not kill the innocent and the just, because I will not justify the guilty.
02Ex 23:8 You must not take a bribe, for a bribe blinds the clear-sighted and corrupts the words of the righteous.
02Ex 23:9 You must not oppress a foreign resident; you yourselves know how it feels to be a foreigner because you were foreigners in the land of Egypt.
02Ex 23:10 "Sow your land for six years and gather its produce.
02Ex 23:11 But during the seventh year you are to let it rest and leave it uncultivated, so that the poor among your people may eat [from it] and the wild animals may consume what they leave. Do the same with your vineyard and your olive grove.
02Ex 23:12 "Do your work for six days but rest on the seventh day so that your ox and your donkey may rest, and the son of your female slave as well as the foreign resident may be refreshed.
02Ex 23:13 "Pay strict attention to everything I have said to you. You must not invoke the names of other gods; they must not be heard on your lips.
02Ex 23:14 "Celebrate a festival in My honor three times a year.
02Ex 23:15 Observe the Festival of Unleavened Bread. As I commanded you, you are to eat unleavened bread for seven days at the appointed time in the month of Abib, because you came out of Egypt in that month. No one is to appear before Me empty-handed.
02Ex 23:16 Also [observe] the Festival of Harvest with the firstfruits of your produce from what you sow in the field, and [observe] the Festival of Ingathering at the end of the year, when you gather your produce from the field.
02Ex 23:17 Three times a year all your males are to appear before the Lord God.
02Ex 23:18 "You must not offer the blood of My sacrifices with anything leavened. The fat of My festival offering must not remain until morning.
02Ex 23:19 "Bring the best of the firstfruits of your land to the house of the LORD your God. "You must not boil a young goat in its mother's milk.
02Ex 23:20 "I am going to send an Angel before you to protect you on the way and bring you to the place I have prepared.
02Ex 23:21 Be attentive to Him and listen to His voice. Do not defy Him, because He will not forgive your acts of rebellion, for My name is in Him.
02Ex 23:22 But if you will carefully obey Him and do everything I say, then I will be an enemy to your enemies and a foe to your foes.
02Ex 23:23 For My Angel will go before you and bring you to [the land of] the Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Canaanites, Hivites, and Jebusites, and I will wipe them out.
02Ex 23:24 You must not bow down to their gods or worship them. Do not imitate their practices. Instead, demolish them and smash their sacred pillars to pieces.
02Ex 23:25 Worship the LORD your God, and He will bless your bread and your water. I will take away your illnesses.
02Ex 23:26 No woman will miscarry or be barren in your land. I will give [you] the full number of your days.
02Ex 23:27 "I will cause the people ahead of you to feel terror and throw into confusion all the nations you come to. I will make all your enemies turn their backs to you in retreat.
02Ex 23:28 I will send the hornet in front of you, and it will drive the Hivites, Canaanites, and Hittites away from you.
02Ex 23:29 I will not drive them out ahead of you in a single year; otherwise, the land would become desolate, and wild animals would multiply against you.
02Ex 23:30 I will drive them out little by little ahead of you until you have become numerous and take possession of the land.
02Ex 23:31 I will set your borders from the Red Sea to the Mediterranean Sea, and from the wilderness to the Euphrates River. For I will place the inhabitants of the land under your control, and you will drive them out ahead of you.
02Ex 23:32 You must not make a covenant with them or their gods.
02Ex 23:33 They must not remain in your land, or else they will make you sin against Me. If you worship their gods, it will be a snare for you."
02Ex 24:1 Then He said to Moses, "Go up to the LORD, you and Aaron, Nadab, and Abihu, and 70 of Israel's elders, and bow in worship at a distance.
02Ex 24:2 Moses alone is to approach the LORD, but the others are not to approach, and the people are not to go up with him."
02Ex 24:3 Moses came and told the people all the commands of the LORD and all the ordinances. Then all the people responded with a single voice, "We will do everything that the LORD has commanded."
02Ex 24:4 And Moses wrote down all the words of the LORD. He rose early the next morning and set up an altar and 12 pillars for the 12 tribes of Israel at the base of the mountain.
02Ex 24:5 Then he sent out young Israelite men, and they offered burnt offerings and sacrificed bulls as fellowship offerings to the LORD.
02Ex 24:6 Moses took half the blood and set it in basins; the [other] half of the blood he sprinkled on the altar.
02Ex 24:7 He then took the covenant scroll and read [it] aloud to the people. They responded, "We will do and obey everything that the LORD has commanded."
02Ex 24:8 Moses took the blood, sprinkled it on the people, and said, "This is the blood of the covenant that the LORD has made with you concerning all these words."
02Ex 24:9 Then Moses went up with Aaron, Nadab, and Abihu, and 70 of Israel's elders,
02Ex 24:10 and they saw the God of Israel. Beneath His feet was something like a pavement made of sapphire stone, as clear as the sky itself.
02Ex 24:11 God did not harm the Israelite nobles; they saw Him, and they ate and drank.
02Ex 24:12 The LORD said to Moses, "Come up to Me on the mountain and stay there so that I may give you the stone tablets with the law and commands I have written for their instruction."
02Ex 24:13 So Moses arose with his assistant Joshua, and went up the mountain of God.
02Ex 24:14 He told the elders, "Wait here for us until we return to you. Aaron and Hur are here with you. Whoever has a dispute should go to them."
02Ex 24:15 When Moses went up the mountain, the cloud covered it.
02Ex 24:16 The glory of the LORD settled on Mount Sinai, and the cloud covered it for six days. On the seventh day He called to Moses from the cloud.
02Ex 24:17 The appearance of the LORD's glory to the Israelites was like a consuming fire on the mountaintop.
02Ex 24:18 Moses entered the cloud as he went up the mountain, and he remained on the mountain 40 days and 40 nights.
02Ex 25:1 The LORD spoke to Moses:
02Ex 25:2 "Tell the Israelites to take an offering for Me. You are to take My offering from everyone whose heart stirs him [to give].
02Ex 25:3 This is the offering you are to receive from them: gold, silver, and bronze;
02Ex 25:4 blue, purple, and scarlet yarn; fine linen and goat hair;
02Ex 25:5 ram skins dyed red and manatee skins; acacia wood;
02Ex 25:6 oil for the light; spices for the anointing oil and for the fragrant incense;
02Ex 25:7 and onyx along with [other] gemstones for mounting on the ephod and breastpiece.
02Ex 25:8 "They are to make a sanctuary for Me so that I may dwell among them.
02Ex 25:9 You must make [it] according to all that I show you-- the design of the tabernacle as well as the design of all its furnishings."
02Ex 25:10 "They are to make an ark of acacia wood, 45 inches long, 27 inches wide, and 27 inches high.
02Ex 25:11 Overlay it with pure gold; overlay it both inside and out. Also make a gold molding all around it.
02Ex 25:12 Cast four gold rings for it and place [them] on its four feet, two rings on one side and two rings on the other side.
02Ex 25:13 Make poles of acacia wood and overlay them with gold.
02Ex 25:14 Insert the poles into the rings on the sides of the ark in order to carry the ark with them.
02Ex 25:15 The poles are to remain in the rings of the ark; they must not be removed from it.
02Ex 25:16 Put the [tablets of the] testimony that I will give you into the ark.
02Ex 25:17 Make a mercy seat of pure gold, 45 inches long and 27 inches wide.
02Ex 25:18 Make two cherubim of gold; make them of hammered work at the two ends of the mercy seat.
02Ex 25:19 Make one cherub at one end and one cherub at the other end. Make the cherubim of one piece with the mercy seat at its two ends.
02Ex 25:20 The cherubim are to have wings spread out above, covering the mercy seat with their wings, and are to face one another. The faces of the cherubim should be toward the mercy seat.
02Ex 25:21 Set the mercy seat on top of the ark and put the testimony that I will give you into the ark.
02Ex 25:22 I will meet with you there above the mercy seat, between the two cherubim that are over the ark of the testimony; I will speak with you from there about all that I command you regarding the Israelites.
02Ex 25:23 "You are to construct a table of acacia wood, 36 inches long, 18 inches wide, and 27 inches high.
02Ex 25:24 Overlay it with pure gold and make a gold molding all around it.
02Ex 25:25 Make a three-inch frame all around it and make a gold molding for it all around its frame.
02Ex 25:26 Make four gold rings for it, and attach the rings to the four corners at its four legs.
02Ex 25:27 The rings should be next to the frame as holders for the poles to carry the table.
02Ex 25:28 Make the poles of acacia wood and overlay them with gold so that the table can be carried by them.
02Ex 25:29 You are also to make its plates and cups, as well as its pitchers and bowls for pouring drink offerings. Make them out of pure gold.
02Ex 25:30 Put the bread of the Presence on the table before Me at all times.
02Ex 25:31 "You are to make a lampstand out of pure, hammered gold. It is to be made of one piece: its base and shaft, its [ornamental] cups, and its calyxes and petals.
02Ex 25:32 Six branches are to extend from its sides, three branches of the lampstand from one side and three branches of the lampstand from the other side.
02Ex 25:33 There are to be three cups shaped like almond blossoms, each with a calyx and petals, on the first branch, and three cups shaped like almond blossoms, each with a calyx and petals, on the next branch. It is to be this way for the six branches that extend from the lampstand.
02Ex 25:34 There are to be four cups shaped like almond blossoms on the lampstand [shaft] along with its calyxes and petals.
02Ex 25:35 For the six branches that extend from the lampstand, a calyx must be under the [first] pair of branches from it, a calyx under the [second] pair of branches from it, and a calyx under the [third] pair of branches from it.
02Ex 25:36 Their calyxes and branches are to be of one piece. All of it is to be a single hammered piece of pure gold.
02Ex 25:37 "Make seven lamps on it. Its lamps are to be set up so they illuminate the area in front of it.
02Ex 25:38 Its snuffers and firepans must be of pure gold.
02Ex 25:39 The lampstand with all these utensils is to be made from 75 pounds of pure gold.
02Ex 25:40 Be careful to make [everything] according to the model of them you have been shown on the mountain.
02Ex 26:1 "You are to construct the tabernacle itself with 10 curtains. You must make them of finely spun linen, and blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, with a design of cherubim worked into them.
02Ex 26:2 The length of each curtain should be 42 feet, and the width of each curtain six feet; all the curtains are to have the same measurements.
02Ex 26:3 Five of the curtains should be joined together, and the [other] five curtains joined together.
02Ex 26:4 Make loops of blue yarn on the edge of the last curtain in the [first] set, and do the same on the edge of the outermost curtain in the second set.
02Ex 26:5 Make 50 loops on the one curtain and make 50 loops on the edge of the curtain in the second set, so that the loops line up together.
02Ex 26:6 Also make 50 gold clasps and join the curtains together with the clasps, so that the tabernacle may be a single unit.
02Ex 26:7 "You are to make curtains of goat hair for a tent over the tabernacle; make 11 of these curtains.
02Ex 26:8 The length of each curtain should be 45 feet and the width of each curtain six feet. All 11 curtains are to have the same measurements.
02Ex 26:9 Join five of the curtains by themselves, and the [other] six curtains by themselves. Then fold the sixth curtain double at the front of the tent.
02Ex 26:10 Make 50 loops on the edge of the one curtain, the outermost in the [first] set, and make 50 loops on the edge of the [corresponding] curtain of the second set.
02Ex 26:11 Make 50 bronze clasps; put the clasps through the loops and join the tent together so that it is a single unit.
02Ex 26:12 As for the flap that is left over from the tent curtains, the leftover half curtain is to hang down over the back of the tabernacle.
02Ex 26:13 The half yard on one side and the half yard on the other of what is left over along the length of the tent curtains should be hanging down over the sides of the tabernacle on either side to cover it.
02Ex 26:14 Make a covering for the tent from ram skins dyed red, and a covering of manatee skins on top of that.
02Ex 26:15 "You are to make upright planks of acacia wood for the tabernacle.
02Ex 26:16 The length of each plank is to be 15 feet, and the width of each plank 27 inches.
02Ex 26:17 Each plank must be connected together with two tenons. Do the same for all the planks of the tabernacle.
02Ex 26:18 Make the planks for the tabernacle as follows: 20 planks for the south side,
02Ex 26:19 and make 40 silver bases under the 20 planks, two bases under the first plank for its two tenons, and two bases under the next plank for its two tenons;
02Ex 26:20 20 planks for the second side of the tabernacle, the north side,
02Ex 26:21 along with their 40 silver bases, two bases under the first plank and two bases under each plank;
02Ex 26:22 and make six planks for the west side of the tabernacle.
02Ex 26:23 Make two additional planks for the two back corners of the tabernacle.
02Ex 26:24 They are to be paired at the bottom, and joined together at the top in a single ring. So it should be for both of them; they will serve as the two corners.
02Ex 26:25 There are to be eight planks with their silver bases: 16 bases; two bases under the first plank and two bases under each plank.
02Ex 26:26 "You are to make five crossbars of acacia wood for the planks on one side of the tabernacle,
02Ex 26:27 five crossbars for the planks on the other side of the tabernacle, and five crossbars for the planks of the back side of the tabernacle on the west.
02Ex 26:28 The central crossbar is to run through the middle of the planks from one end to the other.
02Ex 26:29 Then overlay the planks with gold, and make their rings of gold as the holders for the crossbars. Also overlay the crossbars with gold.
02Ex 26:30 You are to set up the tabernacle according to the plan for it that you have been shown on the mountain.
02Ex 26:31 "You are to make a veil of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and finely spun linen with a design of cherubim worked into it.
02Ex 26:32 Hang it on four gold-plated posts of acacia wood that have gold hooks [and that stand] on four silver bases.
02Ex 26:33 Hang the veil under the clasps and bring the ark of the testimony there behind the veil, so the veil will make a separation for you between the holy place and the most holy place.
02Ex 26:34 Put the mercy seat on the ark of the testimony in the most holy place.
02Ex 26:35 Place the table outside the veil and the lampstand on the south side of the tabernacle, opposite the table; put the table on the north side.
02Ex 26:36 "For the entrance to the tent you are to make a screen embroidered with blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and finely spun linen.
02Ex 26:37 Make five posts of acacia wood for the screen and overlay them with gold; their hooks are to be gold, and you are to cast five bronze bases for them.
02Ex 27:1 "You are to construct the altar of acacia wood. The altar must be square, seven and a half feet long, and seven and a half feet wide; it must be four and a half feet high.
02Ex 27:2 Make horns for it on its four corners; the horns are to be of one piece. Overlay it with bronze.
02Ex 27:3 Make its pots for removing ashes, and its shovels, basins, meat forks, and firepans; make all its utensils of bronze.
02Ex 27:4 Construct a grate for it of bronze mesh, and make four bronze rings on the mesh at its four corners.
02Ex 27:5 Set it below, under the altar's ledge, so that the mesh comes halfway up the altar.
02Ex 27:6 Then make poles for the altar, poles of acacia wood, and overlay them with bronze.
02Ex 27:7 The poles are to be inserted into the rings, so that the poles are on two sides of the altar when it is carried.
02Ex 27:8 Construct the altar with boards so that it is hollow. They are to make it just as it was shown to you on the mountain.
02Ex 27:9 "You are to make the courtyard for the tabernacle. [Make the hangings] on the south of the courtyard out of finely spun linen, 150 feet long on that side.
02Ex 27:10 There are to be 20 posts and 20 bronze bases. The hooks and bands of the posts must be silver.
02Ex 27:11 Then [make the hangings] on the north side 150 [feet] long. There are to be 20 posts and 20 bronze bases. The hooks and bands of the posts must be silver.
02Ex 27:12 [Make] the hangings of the courtyard on the west side 75 feet long, including their 10 posts and 10 bases.
02Ex 27:13 Make the hangings of the courtyard on the east side toward the sunrise 75 feet.
02Ex 27:14 [Make] the hangings on one side [of the gate] 22 and a half feet, including their three posts and their three bases.
02Ex 27:15 And make the hangings on the other side 22 and a half [feet], including their three posts and their three bases.
02Ex 27:16 The gate of the courtyard is to have a thirty-foot screen embroidered with blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and finely spun linen. It is to have four posts including their four bases.
02Ex 27:17 "All the posts around the courtyard are to be banded with silver and have silver hooks and bronze bases.
02Ex 27:18 The length of the courtyard is to be 150 feet, the width 75 [feet] at each end, and the height seven and a half feet, [all of it made] of finely spun linen. The bases of the posts must be bronze.
02Ex 27:19 All the tools of the tabernacle for every use and all its tent pegs as well as all the tent pegs of the courtyard are to be made of bronze.
02Ex 27:20 "You are to command the Israelites to bring you pure oil from crushed olives for the light, in order to keep the lamp burning continually.
02Ex 27:21 In the tent of meeting outside the veil that is in front of the testimony, Aaron and his sons are to tend the lamp from evening until morning before the LORD. This is to be a permanent statute for the Israelites throughout their generations.
02Ex 28:1 "Have your brother Aaron, with his sons, come to you from the Israelites to serve Me as priest-- Aaron, his sons Nadab and Abihu, Eleazar and Ithamar.
02Ex 28:2 Make holy garments for your brother Aaron, for glory and beauty.
02Ex 28:3 You are to instruct all the skilled craftsmen, whom I have filled with a spirit of wisdom, to make Aaron's garments for consecrating him to serve Me as priest.
02Ex 28:4 These are the garments that they must make: a breastpiece, an ephod, a robe, a specially woven tunic, a turban, and a sash. They are to make holy garments for your brother Aaron and his sons so that they may serve Me as priests.
02Ex 28:5 They should use gold; blue, purple, and scarlet yarn; and fine linen.
02Ex 28:6 "They are to make the ephod of finely spun linen embroidered with gold, and with blue, purple, and scarlet yarn.
02Ex 28:7 It must have two shoulder pieces attached to its two edges so that it can be joined together.
02Ex 28:8 The artistically woven waistband that is on the ephod must be of one piece, according to the same workmanship of gold, of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and of finely spun linen.
02Ex 28:9 "Take two onyx stones and engrave on them the names of Israel's sons:
02Ex 28:10 six of their names on the first stone and the remaining six names on the second stone, in the order of their birth.
02Ex 28:11 Engrave the two stones with the names of Israel's sons as a gem cutter engraves a seal. Mount them, surrounded with gold filigree settings.
02Ex 28:12 Fasten both stones on the shoulder pieces of the ephod as memorial stones for the Israelites. Aaron will carry their names on his two shoulders before the LORD as a reminder.
02Ex 28:13 Fashion gold filigree settings
02Ex 28:14 and two chains of pure gold; you will make them of braided cord work, and attach the cord chains to the settings.
02Ex 28:15 "You are to make an embroidered breastpiece for decisions. Make it with the same workmanship as the ephod; make it of gold, of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and of finely spun linen.
02Ex 28:16 It must be square and folded double, nine inches long and nine inches wide.
02Ex 28:17 Place a setting of gemstones on it, four rows of stones: The first row should be a row of carnelian, topaz, and emerald;
02Ex 28:18 the second row, a turquoise, a sapphire, and a diamond;
02Ex 28:19 the third row, a jacinth, an agate, and an amethyst;
02Ex 28:20 and the fourth row, a beryl, an onyx, and a jasper. They should be adorned with gold filigree in their settings.
02Ex 28:21 The 12 stones are to correspond to the names of Israel's sons. Each stone must be engraved like a seal, with one of the names of the 12 tribes.
02Ex 28:22 "You are to make braided chains of pure gold cord work for the breastpiece.
02Ex 28:23 Fashion two gold rings for the breastpiece and attach them to its two corners.
02Ex 28:24 Then attach the two gold cords to the two gold rings at the corners of the breastpiece.
02Ex 28:25 Attach the other ends of the two cords to the two filigree settings and in this way attach [them] to the ephod's shoulder pieces in the front.
02Ex 28:26 Make two [other] gold rings and put them at the two other corners of the breastpiece on the edge that is next to the inner border of the ephod.
02Ex 28:27 Make two [more] gold rings and attach them to the bottom of the ephod's two shoulder pieces on its front, close to its seam, and above the ephod's woven waistband.
02Ex 28:28 The craftsmen are to tie the breastpiece from its rings to the rings of the ephod with a cord of blue yarn, so that the breastpiece is above the ephod's waistband and does not come loose from the ephod.
02Ex 28:29 "Whenever he enters the sanctuary, Aaron is to carry the names of Israel's sons over his heart on the breastpiece for decisions, as a continual reminder before the LORD.
02Ex 28:30 Place the Urim and Thummim in the breastpiece for decisions, so that they will also be over Aaron's heart whenever he comes before the LORD. Aaron will continually carry the [means of] decisions for the Israelites over his heart before the LORD.
02Ex 28:31 "You are to make the robe of the ephod entirely of blue yarn.
02Ex 28:32 There should be an opening at its top in the center of it. Around the opening, there should be a woven collar with an opening like that for body armor so that it does not tear.
02Ex 28:33 Make pomegranates of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn on its lower hem and all around it. Put gold bells between them all the way around,
02Ex 28:34 [so that] gold bells and pomegranates alternate around the lower hem of the robe.
02Ex 28:35 The robe must be [worn by] Aaron whenever he ministers, and its sound will be heard when he enters the sanctuary before the LORD and when he exits, so that he does not die.
02Ex 28:36 "You are to make a plate of pure gold and engrave it, like the engraving of a seal: HOLY TO THE LORD
02Ex 28:37 Fasten it to a cord of blue yarn so it can be placed on the turban; the plate is to be on the front of the turban.
02Ex 28:38 It will be on Aaron's forehead so that Aaron may bear the guilt connected with the holy offerings that the Israelites consecrate as all their holy gifts. It is always to be on his forehead, so that they may find acceptance with the LORD.
02Ex 28:39 "You are to weave the tunic from fine linen, make a turban of fine linen, and make an embroidered sash.
02Ex 28:40 Make tunics, sashes, and headbands for Aaron's sons to [give them] glory and beauty.
02Ex 28:41 Put these on your brother Aaron and his sons; then anoint, ordain, and consecrate them, so that they may serve Me as priests.
02Ex 28:42 Make them linen undergarments to cover [their] naked bodies; they must extend from the waist to the thighs.
02Ex 28:43 These must be [worn by] Aaron and his sons whenever they enter the tent of meeting or approach the altar to minister in the sanctuary [area], so that they do not incur guilt and die. This is to be a permanent statute for Aaron and for his descendants after him.
02Ex 29:1 "This is what you are to do for them to consecrate them to serve Me as priests. Take a young bull and two unblemished rams,
02Ex 29:2 with unleavened bread, unleavened cakes mixed with oil, and unleavened wafers coated with oil. Make them out of fine wheat flour,
02Ex 29:3 put them in a basket, and bring them in the basket, along with the bull and two rams.
02Ex 29:4 Bring Aaron and his sons to the entrance to the tent of meeting and wash them with water.
02Ex 29:5 Then take the garments and clothe Aaron with the tunic, the robe for the ephod, the ephod itself, and the breastpiece; fasten the ephod on him with its woven waistband.
02Ex 29:6 Put the turban on his head and place the holy diadem on the turban.
02Ex 29:7 Take the anointing oil, pour [it] on his head, and anoint him.
02Ex 29:8 You must also bring his sons, clothe them with tunics,
02Ex 29:9 fasten headbands on them, and tie sashes around both Aaron and his sons. The priesthood is to be theirs by a permanent statute. This is the way you will ordain Aaron and his sons.
02Ex 29:10 "You are to bring the bull to the front of the tent of meeting, and Aaron and his sons must lay their hands on the bull's head.
02Ex 29:11 Slaughter the bull before the LORD at the entrance to the tent of meeting.
02Ex 29:12 Take some of the bull's blood and apply [it] to the horns of the altar with your finger; then pour out all the [rest] of the blood at the base of the altar.
02Ex 29:13 Take all the fat that covers the entrails, the fatty lobe of the liver, and the two kidneys with the fat on them, and burn [them] on the altar.
02Ex 29:14 But burn up the bull's flesh, its hide, and its dung outside the camp; it is a sin offering.
02Ex 29:15 "Take one ram, and Aaron and his sons are to lay their hands on the ram's head.
02Ex 29:16 You are to slaughter the ram, take its blood, and sprinkle [it] on all sides of the altar.
02Ex 29:17 Cut the ram into pieces. Wash its entrails and shanks, and place [them] with its head and its pieces [on the altar].
02Ex 29:18 Then burn the whole ram on the altar; it is a burnt offering to the LORD. It is a pleasing aroma, a fire offering to the LORD.
02Ex 29:19 "You are to take the second ram, and Aaron and his sons must lay their hands on the ram's head.
02Ex 29:20 Slaughter the ram, take some of its blood, and put it on Aaron's right earlobe, on his sons' right earlobes, on the thumbs of their right hands, and on the big toes of their right feet. Sprinkle the [remaining] blood on all sides of the altar.
02Ex 29:21 Take some of the blood that is on the altar and some of the anointing oil, and sprinkle [them] on Aaron and his garments, as well as on his sons and their garments. In this way, he and his garments will become holy, as well as his sons and their garments.
02Ex 29:22 "Take the fat from the ram, the fat tail, the fat covering the entrails, the fatty lobe of the liver, the two kidneys and the fat on them, and the right thigh (since this is a ram for ordination);
02Ex 29:23 take one loaf of bread, one cake of bread [made] with oil, and one wafer from the basket of unleavened bread that is before the LORD;
02Ex 29:24 and put all of them in the hands of Aaron and his sons and wave them as a presentation offering before the LORD.
02Ex 29:25 Take them from their hands and burn [them] on the altar on top of the burnt offering, as a pleasing aroma before the LORD; it is a fire offering to the LORD.
02Ex 29:26 "Take the breast from the ram of Aaron's ordination and wave it as a presentation offering before the LORD; it is to be your portion.
02Ex 29:27 Consecrate for Aaron and his sons the breast of the presentation offering that is waved and the thigh of the contribution that is lifted up from the ram of ordination.
02Ex 29:28 This will belong to Aaron and his sons as a regular portion from the Israelites, for it is a contribution. It will be the Israelites' contribution from their fellowship sacrifices, their contribution to the LORD.
02Ex 29:29 "The holy garments that belong to Aaron are to belong to his sons after him, so that they can be anointed and ordained in them.
02Ex 29:30 Any priest who is one of his sons and who succeeds him and enters the tent of meeting to minister in the sanctuary must wear them for seven days.
02Ex 29:31 "You are to take the ram of ordination and boil its flesh in a holy place.
02Ex 29:32 Aaron and his sons are to eat the meat of the ram and the bread that is in the basket at the entrance to the tent of meeting.
02Ex 29:33 They must eat those things by which atonement was made at the [time of] their ordination and consecration. An unauthorized person must not eat [them], for these things are holy.
02Ex 29:34 If any of the meat of ordination or any of the bread is left until morning, burn up what is left over. It must not be eaten because it is holy.
02Ex 29:35 "This is what you are to do for Aaron and his sons based on all I have commanded you. Ordain them for seven days.
02Ex 29:36 Sacrifice a bull as a sin offering each day for atonement. Purify the altar when you make atonement for it, and anoint it in order to consecrate it.
02Ex 29:37 For seven days you must make atonement for the altar and consecrate it. The altar will become especially holy; whatever touches the altar will become holy.
02Ex 29:38 "This is what you are to offer regularly on the altar every day: two year-old lambs.
02Ex 29:39 In the morning offer one lamb, and at twilight offer the other lamb.
02Ex 29:40 With the first lamb offer two quarts of fine flour mixed with one quart of crushed olive oil, and a drink offering of one quart of wine.
02Ex 29:41 You are to offer the second lamb at twilight. Offer a grain offering and a drink offering with it, like the one in the morning, as a pleasing aroma, a fire offering to the LORD.
02Ex 29:42 This will be a regular burnt offering throughout your generations at the entrance to the tent of meeting before the LORD, where I will meet you to speak with you.
02Ex 29:43 I will also meet with the Israelites there, and that place will be consecrated by My glory.
02Ex 29:44 I will consecrate the tent of meeting and the altar; I will also consecrate Aaron and his sons to serve Me as priests.
02Ex 29:45 I will dwell among the Israelites and be their God.
02Ex 29:46 And they will know that I am the LORD their God, who brought them out of the land of Egypt, so that I might dwell among them. I am the LORD their God.
02Ex 30:1 "You are to make an altar for the burning of incense; make it of acacia wood.
02Ex 30:2 It must be square, 18 inches long and 18 inches wide; it must be 36 inches high. Its horns must be of one piece.
02Ex 30:3 Overlay its top, all around its sides, and its horns with pure gold; make a gold molding all around it.
02Ex 30:4 Make two gold rings for it under the molding on two of its sides; put these on opposite sides of it to be holders for the poles to carry it with.
02Ex 30:5 Make the poles of acacia wood and overlay them with gold.
02Ex 30:6 "You are to place the altar in front of the veil by the ark of the testimony-- in front of the mercy seat that is over the testimony-- where I will meet with you.
02Ex 30:7 Aaron must burn fragrant incense on it; he must burn it every morning when he tends the lamps.
02Ex 30:8 When Aaron sets up the lamps at twilight, he must burn incense. There is to be an incense [offering] before the LORD throughout your generations.
02Ex 30:9 You must not offer unauthorized incense on it, or a burnt or grain offering; you are not to pour a drink offering on it.
02Ex 30:10 "Once a year Aaron is to perform the purification rite on the horns of the altar. Throughout your generations he is to perform the purification rite for it once a year, with the blood of the sin offering for atonement. The altar is especially holy to the LORD."
02Ex 30:11 The LORD spoke to Moses:
02Ex 30:12 "When you take a census of the Israelites to register them, each of the men must pay a ransom for himself to the LORD as they are registered. Then no plague will come on them as they are registered.
02Ex 30:13 Everyone who is registered must pay half a shekel according to the sanctuary shekel
02Ex 30:14 Each man who is registered, 20 years old or more, must give this contribution to the LORD.
02Ex 30:15 The wealthy may not give more, and the poor may not give less, than half a shekel when giving the contribution to the LORD to atone for your lives.
02Ex 30:16 Take the atonement money from the Israelites and use it for the service of the tent of meeting. It will serve as a reminder for the Israelites before the LORD to atone for your lives."
02Ex 30:17 The LORD spoke to Moses:
02Ex 30:18 "Make a bronze basin for washing and a bronze stand for it. Set it between the tent of meeting and the altar, and put water in it.
02Ex 30:19 Aaron and his sons must wash their hands and feet from the basin.
02Ex 30:20 Whenever they enter the tent of meeting or approach the altar to minister by burning up an offering to the LORD, they must wash with water so that they will not die.
02Ex 30:21 They must wash their hands and feet so that they will not die; this is to be a permanent statute for them, for Aaron and his descendants throughout their generations."
02Ex 30:22 The LORD spoke to Moses:
02Ex 30:23 "Take for yourself the finest spices: 12 and a half pounds of liquid myrrh, half as much (six and a quarter pounds) of fragrant cinnamon, six and a quarter pounds of fragrant cane,
02Ex 30:24 12 and a half pounds of cassia (by the sanctuary shekel), and one gallon of olive oil.
02Ex 30:25 Prepare from these a holy anointing oil, a scented blend, the work of a perfumer; it will be holy anointing oil.
02Ex 30:26 "With it you are to anoint the tent of meeting, the ark of the testimony,
02Ex 30:27 the table with all its utensils, the lampstand with its utensils, the altar of incense,
02Ex 30:28 the altar of burnt offering with all its utensils, and the basin with its stand.
02Ex 30:29 Consecrate them and they will be especially holy. Whatever touches them will be consecrated.
02Ex 30:30 Anoint Aaron and his sons and consecrate them to serve Me as priests.
02Ex 30:31 "Tell the Israelites: This will be My holy anointing oil throughout your generations.
02Ex 30:32 It must not be used for [ordinary] anointing on a person's body, and you must not make anything like it using its formula. It is holy, and it must be holy to you.
02Ex 30:33 Anyone who blends something like it or puts some of it on an unauthorized person must be cut off from his people."
02Ex 30:34 The LORD said to Moses: "Take fragrant spices: stacte, onycha, and galbanum; the spices and pure frankincense are to be in equal measures.
02Ex 30:35 Prepare expertly blended incense from these; it is to be seasoned with salt, pure and holy.
02Ex 30:36 Grind some of it into a fine powder and put some in front of the testimony in the tent of meeting, where I will meet with you. It must be especially holy to you.
02Ex 30:37 As for the incense you are making, you must not make [any] for yourselves using its formula. It is to be regarded by you as sacred to the LORD.
02Ex 30:38 Anyone who makes something like it to smell its fragrance must be cut off from his people."
02Ex 31:1 The LORD also spoke to Moses:
02Ex 31:2 "Look, I have appointed by name Bezalel son of Uri, son of Hur, of the tribe of Judah.
02Ex 31:3 I have filled him with God's Spirit, with wisdom, understanding, and ability in every craft
02Ex 31:4 to design artistic works in gold, silver, and bronze,
02Ex 31:5 to cut gemstones for mounting, and to carve wood for work in every craft.
02Ex 31:6 I have also selected Oholiab son of Ahisamach, of the tribe of Dan, to be with him. I have placed wisdom within every skilled craftsman in order to make all that I have commanded you:
02Ex 31:7 the tent of meeting, the ark of the testimony, the mercy seat that is on top of it, and all the [other] furnishings of the tent--
02Ex 31:8 the table with its utensils, the pure [gold] lampstand with all its utensils, the altar of incense,
02Ex 31:9 the altar of burnt offering with all its utensils, the basin with its stand--
02Ex 31:10 the specially woven garments, both the holy garments for Aaron the priest and the garments for his sons to serve as priests,
02Ex 31:11 the anointing oil, and the fragrant incense for the sanctuary. They must make [them] according to all that I have commanded you."
02Ex 31:12 The LORD said to Moses:
02Ex 31:13 "Tell the Israelites: You must observe My Sabbaths, for it is a sign between Me and you throughout your generations, so that you will know that I am the LORD who sets you apart.
02Ex 31:14 Observe the Sabbath, for it is holy to you. Whoever profanes it must be put to death. If anyone does work on it, that person must be cut off from his people.
02Ex 31:15 For six days work may be done, but on the seventh day there must be a Sabbath of complete rest, dedicated to the LORD. Anyone who does work on the Sabbath day must be put to death.
02Ex 31:16 The Israelites must observe the Sabbath, celebrating it throughout their generations as a perpetual covenant.
02Ex 31:17 It is a sign forever between Me and the Israelites, for in six days the LORD made the heavens and the earth, but on the seventh day He rested and was refreshed."
02Ex 31:18 When He finished speaking with Moses on Mount Sinai, He gave him the two tablets of the testimony, stone tablets inscribed by the finger of God.
02Ex 32:1 When the people saw that Moses delayed in coming down from the mountain, they gathered around Aaron and said to him, "Come, make us a god who will go before us because this Moses, the man who brought us up from the land of Egypt-- we don't know what has happened to him!"
02Ex 32:2 Then Aaron replied to them, "Take off the gold rings that are on the ears of your wives, your sons, and your daughters and bring [them] to me."
02Ex 32:3 So all the people took off the gold rings that were on their ears and brought [them] to Aaron.
02Ex 32:4 He took [the gold] from their hands, fashioned it with an engraving tool, and made it into an image of a calf. Then they said, "Israel, this is your God, who brought you up from the land of Egypt!"
02Ex 32:5 When Aaron saw [this], he built an altar before it; then he made an announcement: "There will be a festival to the LORD tomorrow."
02Ex 32:6 Early the next morning they arose, offered burnt offerings, and presented fellowship offerings. The people sat down to eat and drink, then got up to revel.
02Ex 32:7 The LORD spoke to Moses: "Go down at once! For your people you brought up from the land of Egypt have acted corruptly.
02Ex 32:8 They have quickly turned from the way I commanded them; they have made for themselves an image of a calf. They have bowed down to it, sacrificed to it, and said, 'Israel, this is your God, who brought you up from the land of Egypt.'"
02Ex 32:9 The LORD also said to Moses: "I have seen this people, and they are indeed a stiff-necked people.
02Ex 32:10 Now leave Me alone, so that My anger can burn against them and I can destroy them. Then I will make you into a great nation."
02Ex 32:11 But Moses interceded with the LORD his God: "LORD, why does Your anger burn against Your people You brought out of the land of Egypt with great power and a strong hand?
02Ex 32:12 Why should the Egyptians say, 'He brought them out with an evil intent to kill them in the mountains and wipe them off the face of the earth'? Turn from Your great anger and change Your mind about this disaster [planned] for Your people.
02Ex 32:13 Remember that You swore to Your servants Abraham, Isaac, and Israel by Yourself and declared to them, 'I will make your offspring as numerous as the stars of the sky and will give your offspring all this land that I have promised, and they will inherit [it] forever.'"
02Ex 32:14 So the LORD changed His mind about the disaster He said He would bring on His people.
02Ex 32:15 Then Moses turned and went down the mountain with the two tablets of the testimony in his hands. They were inscribed on both sides-- inscribed front and back.
02Ex 32:16 The tablets were the work of God, and the writing was God's writing, engraved on the tablets.
02Ex 32:17 When Joshua heard the sound of the people as they shouted, he said to Moses, "There is a sound of war in the camp."
02Ex 32:18 But Moses replied: It's not the sound of a victory cry and not the sound of a cry of defeat; I hear the sound of singing!
02Ex 32:19 As he approached the camp and saw the calf and the dancing, Moses became enraged and threw the tablets out of his hands, smashing them at the base of the mountain.
02Ex 32:20 Then he took the calf they had made, burned [it] up, and ground [it] to powder. He scattered [the powder] over the surface of the water and forced the Israelites to drink [the water].
02Ex 32:21 Then Moses asked Aaron, "What did this people do to you that you have led them into [such] a grave sin?"
02Ex 32:22 "Don't be enraged, my lord," Aaron replied. "You yourself know that the people are [intent] on evil.
02Ex 32:23 They said to me, 'Make us a god who will go before us because this Moses, the man who brought us up from the land of Egypt-- we don't know what has happened to him!'
02Ex 32:24 So I said to them, 'Whoever has gold, take it off,' and they gave [it] to me. When I threw it into the fire, out came this calf!"
02Ex 32:25 Moses saw that the people were out of control, for Aaron had let them get out of control, so that they would be vulnerable to their enemies.
02Ex 32:26 And Moses stood at the camp's entrance and said, "Whoever is for the LORD, [come] to me." And all the Levites gathered around him.
02Ex 32:27 He told them, "This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says, 'Every man fasten his sword to his side; go back and forth through the camp from entrance to entrance, and each of you kill his brother, his friend, and his neighbor.'"
02Ex 32:28 The Levites did as Moses commanded, and about 3,000 men fell dead that day among the people.
02Ex 32:29 Afterwards Moses said, "Today you have been dedicated to the LORD, since each man went against his son and his brother. Therefore you have brought a blessing on yourselves today."
02Ex 32:30 The following day Moses said to the people, "You have committed a great sin. Now I will go up to the LORD; perhaps I will be able to pay for your sin."
02Ex 32:31 So Moses returned to the LORD and said, "Oh, this people has committed a great sin; they have made for themselves a god of gold.
02Ex 32:32 Now if You would only forgive their sin. But if not, please erase me from the book You have written."
02Ex 32:33 The LORD replied to Moses: "Whoever has sinned against Me I will erase from My book.
02Ex 32:34 Now go, lead the people to the place I told you about; see, My angel will go before you. But on the day I settle accounts, I will hold them accountable for their sin."
02Ex 32:35 And the LORD inflicted a plague on the people for what they did with the calf Aaron had made.
02Ex 33:1 The LORD spoke to Moses: "Go, leave here, you and the people you brought up from the land of Egypt, to the land I promised to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, saying: I will give it to your offspring.
02Ex 33:2 I will send an angel ahead of you and will drive out the Canaanites, Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites.
02Ex 33:3 [Go up] to a land flowing with milk and honey. But I will not go with you because you are a stiff-necked people; otherwise, I might destroy you on the way."
02Ex 33:4 When the people heard this bad news, they mourned and didn't put on their jewelry.
02Ex 33:5 For the LORD said to Moses: "Tell the Israelites: You are a stiff-necked people. If I went with you for a single moment, I would destroy you. Now take off your jewelry, and I will decide what to do with you."
02Ex 33:6 So the Israelites stripped of their jewelry from Mount Horeb [onward].
02Ex 33:7 Now Moses took a tent and set it up outside the camp, far away from the camp; he called it the tent of meeting. Anyone who wanted to consult the LORD would go to the tent of meeting that was outside the camp.
02Ex 33:8 Whenever Moses went out to the tent, all the people would stand up, each one at the door of his tent, and they would watch Moses until he entered the tent.
02Ex 33:9 When Moses entered the tent, the pillar of cloud would come down and remain at the entrance to the tent, and [the LORD] would speak with Moses.
02Ex 33:10 As all the people saw the pillar of cloud remaining at the entrance to the tent, they would stand up, then bow in worship, each one at the door of his tent.
02Ex 33:11 The LORD spoke with Moses face to face, just as a man speaks with his friend. Then Moses would return to the camp, but his assistant, the young man Joshua son of Nun, would not leave the inside of the tent.
02Ex 33:12 Moses said to the LORD, "Look, You have told me, 'Lead this people up,' but You have not let me know whom You will send with me. You said, 'I know you by name, and you have also found favor in My sight.'
02Ex 33:13 Now if I have indeed found favor in Your sight, please teach me Your ways, and I will know You and find favor in Your sight. Now consider that this nation is Your people."
02Ex 33:14 Then He replied, "My presence will go [with you], and I will give you rest."
02Ex 33:15 "If Your presence does not go," Moses responded to Him, "don't make us go up from here.
02Ex 33:16 How will it be known that I and Your people have found favor in Your sight unless You go with us? I and Your people will be distinguished [by this] from all the other people on the face of the earth."
02Ex 33:17 The LORD answered Moses, "I will do this very thing you have asked, for you have found favor in My sight, and I know you by name."
02Ex 33:18 Then Moses said, "Please, let me see Your glory."
02Ex 33:19 He said, "I will cause all My goodness to pass in front of you, and I will proclaim the name Yahweh before you. I will be gracious to whom I will be gracious, and I will have compassion on whom I will have compassion."
02Ex 33:20 But He answered, "You cannot see My face, for no one can see Me and live."
02Ex 33:21 The LORD said, "Here is a place near Me. You are to stand on the rock,
02Ex 33:22 and when My glory passes by, I will put you in the crevice of the rock and cover you with My hand until I have passed by.
02Ex 33:23 Then I will take My hand away, and you will see My back, but My face will not be seen."
02Ex 34:1 The LORD said to Moses, "Cut two stone tablets like the first ones, and I will write on them the words that were on the first tablets, which you broke.
02Ex 34:2 Be prepared by morning. Come up Mount Sinai in the morning and stand before Me on the mountaintop.
02Ex 34:3 No one may go up with you; in fact, no one must be seen anywhere on the mountain. Even the flocks and herds are not to graze in front of that mountain."
02Ex 34:4 Moses cut two stone tablets like the first ones. He got up early in the morning, and taking the two stone tablets in his hand, he climbed Mount Sinai, just as the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 34:5 The LORD came down in a cloud, stood with him there, and proclaimed [His] name Yahweh.
02Ex 34:6 Then the LORD passed in front of him and proclaimed: Yahweh-- Yahweh is a compassionate and gracious God, slow to anger and rich in faithful love and truth,
02Ex 34:7 maintaining faithful love to a thousand [generations], forgiving wrongdoing, rebellion, and sin. But He will not leave [the guilty] unpunished, bringing the consequences of the fathers' wrongdoing on the children and grandchildren to the third and fourth generation.
02Ex 34:8 Moses immediately bowed down to the ground and worshiped.
02Ex 34:9 Then he said, "My Lord, if I have indeed found favor in Your sight, my Lord, please go with us. Even though this is a stiff-necked people, forgive our wrongdoing and sin, and accept us as Your own possession."
02Ex 34:10 And the LORD responded: "Look, I am making a covenant. I will perform wonders in the presence of all your people that have never been done in all the earth or in any nation. All the people you live among will see the LORD's work, for what I am doing with you is awe-inspiring.
02Ex 34:11 Observe what I command you today. I am going to drive out before you the Amorites, Canaanites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites.
02Ex 34:12 Be careful not to make a treaty with the inhabitants of the land that you are going to enter; otherwise, they will become a snare among you.
02Ex 34:13 Instead, you must tear down their altars, smash their sacred pillars, and chop down their Asherah poles.
02Ex 34:14 You are to never bow down to another god because the LORD, being jealous by nature, is a jealous God.
02Ex 34:15 "Do not make a treaty with the inhabitants of the land, or else when they prostitute themselves with their gods and sacrifice to their gods, they will invite you, and you will eat of their sacrifice.
02Ex 34:16 Then you will take some of their daughters [as brides] for your sons. Their daughters will prostitute themselves with their gods and cause your sons to prostitute themselves with their gods.
02Ex 34:17 "Do not make cast images of gods for yourselves.
02Ex 34:18 "Observe the Festival of Unleavened Bread. You are to eat unleavened bread for seven days at the appointed time in the month of Abib as I commanded you. For you came out of Egypt in the month of Abib.
02Ex 34:19 "The firstborn male from every womb belongs to Me, including all your male livestock, the firstborn of cattle or sheep.
02Ex 34:20 You must redeem the firstborn of a donkey with a sheep, but if you do not redeem [it], break its neck. You must redeem all the firstborn of your sons. No one is to appear before Me empty-handed.
02Ex 34:21 "You are to labor six days but you must rest on the seventh day; you must even rest during plowing and harvesting times.
02Ex 34:22 "Observe the Festival of Weeks with the firstfruits of the wheat harvest, and the Festival of Ingathering at the turn of the [agricultural] year.
02Ex 34:23 Three times a year all your males are to appear before the Lord God, the God of Israel.
02Ex 34:24 For I will drive out nations before you and enlarge your territory. No one will covet your land when you go up three times a year to appear before the LORD your God.
02Ex 34:25 "Do not present the blood for My sacrifice with anything leavened. The sacrifice of the Passover Festival must not remain until morning.
02Ex 34:26 "Bring the best firstfruits of your land to the house of the LORD your God. "You must not boil a young goat in its mother's milk."
02Ex 34:27 The LORD also said to Moses, "Write down these words, for I have made a covenant with you and with Israel based on these words."
02Ex 34:28 Moses was there with the LORD 40 days and 40 nights; he did not eat bread or drink water. He wrote down on the tablets the words of the covenant-- the Ten Commandments.
02Ex 34:29 As Moses descended from Mount Sinai-- with the two tablets of the testimony in his hands as he descended the mountain-- he did not realize that the skin of his face shone as a result of his speaking with the LORD.
02Ex 34:30 When Aaron and all the Israelites saw Moses, the skin of his face shone! They were afraid to come near him.
02Ex 34:31 But Moses called out to them, so Aaron and all the leaders of the community returned to him, and Moses spoke to them.
02Ex 34:32 Afterwards all the Israelites came near, and he commanded them everything the LORD had told him on Mount Sinai.
02Ex 34:33 When Moses had finished speaking with them, he put a veil over his face.
02Ex 34:34 But whenever Moses went before the LORD to speak with Him, he would remove the veil until he came out. After he came out, he would tell the Israelites what he had been commanded,
02Ex 34:35 and the Israelites would see that Moses' face was radiant. Then Moses would put the veil over his face again until he went to speak with the LORD.
02Ex 35:1 Moses assembled the entire Israelite community and said to them, "These are the things that the LORD has commanded you to do:
02Ex 35:2 For six days work is to be done, but on the seventh day you are to have a holy day, a Sabbath of complete rest to the LORD. Anyone who does work on it must be executed.
02Ex 35:3 Do not light a fire in any of your homes on the Sabbath day."
02Ex 35:4 Then Moses said to the entire Israelite community, "This is what the LORD has commanded:
02Ex 35:5 Take up an offering for the LORD among you. Let everyone whose heart is willing bring this as the LORD's offering: gold, silver, and bronze;
02Ex 35:6 blue, purple, and scarlet yarn; fine linen and goat hair;
02Ex 35:7 ram skins dyed red and manatee skins; acacia wood;
02Ex 35:8 oil for the light; spices for the anointing oil and for the fragrant incense;
02Ex 35:9 and onyx with gemstones to mount on the ephod and breastpiece.
02Ex 35:10 "Let all the skilled craftsmen among you come and make everything that the LORD has commanded:
02Ex 35:11 the tabernacle-- its tent and covering, its clasps and planks, its crossbars, its posts and bases;
02Ex 35:12 the ark with its poles, the mercy seat, and the veil for the screen;
02Ex 35:13 the table with its poles, all its utensils, and the bread of the Presence;
02Ex 35:14 the lampstand for light with its utensils and lamps as well as the oil for the light;
02Ex 35:15 the altar of incense with its poles; the anointing oil and the fragrant incense; the entryway screen for the entrance to the tabernacle;
02Ex 35:16 the altar of burnt offering with its bronze grate, its poles, and all its utensils; the basin with its stand;
02Ex 35:17 the hangings of the courtyard, its posts and bases, and the screen for the gate of the courtyard;
02Ex 35:18 the tent pegs for the tabernacle and the tent pegs for the courtyard, along with their ropes;
02Ex 35:19 and the specially woven garments for ministering in the sanctuary-- the holy garments for Aaron the priest and the garments for his sons to serve as priests."
02Ex 35:20 Then the entire Israelite community left Moses' presence.
02Ex 35:21 Everyone whose heart was moved and whose spirit prompted him came and brought an offering to the LORD to construct the tent of meeting for every use, and [to make] the holy garments.
02Ex 35:22 Both men and women came; all who had willing hearts brought brooches, earrings, rings, necklaces, and all kinds of gold jewelry-- everyone who waved a presentation offering of gold to the LORD.
02Ex 35:23 Everyone who had in his possession blue, purple, or scarlet yarn, fine linen or goat hair, ram skins dyed red or manatee skins, brought [them].
02Ex 35:24 Everyone who offered a contribution of silver or bronze brought it to the LORD. Everyone who possessed acacia wood useful for any task in the work brought [it].
02Ex 35:25 Every skilled woman spun [yarn] with her hands and brought it: blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and fine linen.
02Ex 35:26 And all the women whose hearts were moved spun the goat hair by virtue of [their] skill.
02Ex 35:27 The leaders brought onyx and gemstones to mount on the ephod and breastpiece,
02Ex 35:28 as well as the spice and oil for the light, for the anointing oil, and for the fragrant incense.
02Ex 35:29 So the Israelites brought a freewill offering to the LORD, all the men and women whose hearts prompted them to bring [something] for all the work that the LORD, through Moses, had commanded to be done.
02Ex 35:30 Moses then said to the Israelites: "Look, the LORD has appointed by name Bezalel son of Uri, son of Hur, of the tribe of Judah.
02Ex 35:31 He has filled him with God's Spirit, with wisdom, understanding, and ability in every kind of craft
02Ex 35:32 to design artistic works in gold, silver, and bronze,
02Ex 35:33 to cut gemstones for mounting, and to carve wood for work in every kind of artistic craft.
02Ex 35:34 He has also given both him and Oholiab son of Ahisamach, of the tribe of Dan, [the ability] to teach [others].
02Ex 35:35 He has filled them with skill to do all the work of a gem cutter; a designer; an embroiderer in blue, purple, and scarlet yarn and fine linen; and a weaver. They can do every kind of craft and design artistic designs.
02Ex 36:1 Bezalel, Oholiab, and all the skilled people are to work based on everything the LORD has commanded. The LORD has given them wisdom and understanding to know how to do all the work of constructing the sanctuary."
02Ex 36:2 So Moses summoned Bezalel, Oholiab, and every skilled person in whose heart the LORD had placed wisdom, everyone whose heart moved him, to come to the work and do it.
02Ex 36:3 They took from Moses' presence all the contributions that the Israelites had brought for the task of making the sanctuary. Meanwhile, the people continued to bring freewill offerings morning after morning.
02Ex 36:4 Then all the craftsmen who were doing all the work for the sanctuary came one by one from the work they were doing
02Ex 36:5 and said to Moses, "The people are bringing more than is needed for the construction of the work the LORD commanded to be done."
02Ex 36:6 After Moses gave an order, they sent a proclamation throughout the camp: "Let no man or woman make anything else as an offering for the sanctuary." So the people stopped.
02Ex 36:7 The materials were sufficient for them to do all the work. There was more than enough.
02Ex 36:8 All the skilled craftsmen among those doing the work made the tabernacle with 10 curtains. Bezalel made them of finely spun linen, as well as blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, with a design of cherubim worked into them.
02Ex 36:9 The length of each curtain was 42 feet, and the width of each curtain six feet; all the curtains had the same measurements.
02Ex 36:10 He joined five of the curtains to each other, and the [other] five curtains he joined to each other.
02Ex 36:11 He made loops of blue yarn on the edge of the last curtain in the first set and did the same on the edge of the outermost curtain in the second set.
02Ex 36:12 He made 50 loops on the one curtain and 50 loops on the edge of the curtain in the second set, so that the loops lined up with each other.
02Ex 36:13 He also made 50 gold clasps and joined the curtains to each other, so that the tabernacle became a single unit.
02Ex 36:14 He made curtains of goat hair for a tent over the tabernacle; he also made 11 of them.
02Ex 36:15 The length of each curtain was 45 feet, and the width of each curtain six feet. All 11 curtains had the same measurements.
02Ex 36:16 He joined five of the curtains together, and [the other] six together.
02Ex 36:17 He made 50 loops on the edge of the outermost curtain in the [first] set and 50 loops on the edge of the [corresponding] curtain in the second set.
02Ex 36:18 He made 50 bronze clasps to join the tent together as a single unit.
02Ex 36:19 He also made a covering for the tent from ram skins dyed red and a covering of manatee skins on top of it.
02Ex 36:20 He made upright planks of acacia wood for the tabernacle.
02Ex 36:21 The length of each plank was 15 feet, and the width of each was 27 inches.
02Ex 36:22 There were two tenons connected to each other for each plank. He did the same for all the planks of the tabernacle.
02Ex 36:23 He made planks for the tabernacle as follows: 20 for the south side,
02Ex 36:24 and he made 40 silver bases to put under the 20 planks, two bases under the first plank for its two tenons, and two bases under each of the following planks for their two tenons;
02Ex 36:25 for the second side of the tabernacle, the north side, he made 20 planks,
02Ex 36:26 with their 40 silver bases, two bases under the first plank and two bases under each of the following ones;
02Ex 36:27 and for the west side of the tabernacle he made six planks.
02Ex 36:28 He also made two additional planks for the two back corners of the tabernacle.
02Ex 36:29 They were paired at the bottom and joined together at the top in a single ring. This is what he did with both of them for the two corners.
02Ex 36:30 So there were eight planks with their 16 silver bases, two bases under each one.
02Ex 36:31 He made five crossbars of acacia wood for the planks on one side of the tabernacle,
02Ex 36:32 five crossbars for the planks on the other side of the tabernacle, and five crossbars for those at the back of the tabernacle on the west.
02Ex 36:33 He made the central crossbar run through the middle of the planks from one end to the other.
02Ex 36:34 He overlaid them with gold and made their rings and holders for the crossbars out of gold. He also overlaid the crossbars with gold.
02Ex 36:35 Then he made the veil with blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and finely spun linen. He made it with a design of cherubim worked into it.
02Ex 36:36 For it he made four posts of acacia wood and overlaid them with gold; their hooks were of gold. And he cast four silver bases for the posts.
02Ex 36:37 He made a screen embroidered with blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and finely spun linen for the entrance to the tent,
02Ex 36:38 together with its five posts and their hooks. He overlaid the tops of the posts and their bands with gold, but their five bases were bronze.
02Ex 37:1 Bezalel made the ark of acacia wood, 45 inches long, 27 inches wide, and 27 inches high.
02Ex 37:2 He overlaid it with pure gold inside and out and made a gold molding all around it.
02Ex 37:3 He cast four gold rings for it to be on its four feet, two rings on one side and two rings on the other side.
02Ex 37:4 He made poles of acacia wood and overlaid them with gold.
02Ex 37:5 He inserted the poles into the rings on the sides of the ark for carrying the ark.
02Ex 37:6 He made a mercy seat of pure gold, 45 inches long and 27 inches wide.
02Ex 37:7 He made two cherubim of gold; he made them of hammered work at the two ends of the mercy seat,
02Ex 37:8 one cherub at one end and one cherub at the other end. He made the cherubim [of one piece] with the mercy seat, [a cherubim] at each end.
02Ex 37:9 They had wings spread out, covering the mercy seat with their wings and facing each other. The faces of the cherubim were looking toward the mercy seat.
02Ex 37:10 He constructed the table of acacia wood, 36 inches long, 18 inches wide, and 27 inches high.
02Ex 37:11 He overlaid it with pure gold and made a gold molding all around it.
02Ex 37:12 He made a three-inch frame all around it and made a gold molding all around its frame.
02Ex 37:13 He cast four gold rings for it and attached the rings to the four corners at its four legs.
02Ex 37:14 The rings were next to the frame as holders for the poles to carry the table.
02Ex 37:15 He made the poles for carrying the table from acacia wood and overlaid them with gold.
02Ex 37:16 He also made the utensils that would be on the table out of pure gold: its plates and cups, as well as its bowls and pitchers for pouring drink offerings.
02Ex 37:17 Then he made the lampstand out of pure hammered gold. He made it [all] of one piece: its base and shaft, its [ornamental] cups, and its calyxes and petals.
02Ex 37:18 Six branches extended from its sides, three branches of the lampstand from one side and three branches of the lampstand from the other side.
02Ex 37:19 There were three cups shaped like almond blossoms, each with a calyx and petals, on the first branch, and three cups shaped like almond blossoms, each with a calyx and petals, on the next branch. It was this way for the six branches that extended from the lampstand.
02Ex 37:20 On the lampstand shaft there were four cups shaped like almond blossoms with its calyxes and petals.
02Ex 37:21 For the six branches that extended from it, a calyx was under the first pair of branches from it, a calyx under the second pair of branches from it, and a calyx under the third pair of branches from it.
02Ex 37:22 Their calyxes and branches were of one piece. All of it was a single hammered piece of pure gold.
02Ex 37:23 He also made its seven lamps, snuffers, and firepans of pure gold.
02Ex 37:24 He made it and all its utensils of 75 pounds of pure gold.
02Ex 37:25 He made the altar of incense out of acacia wood. It was square, 18 inches long and 18 inches wide; it was 36 inches high. Its horns were of one piece.
02Ex 37:26 He overlaid it, its top, all around its sides, and its horns with pure gold. Then he made a gold molding all around it.
02Ex 37:27 He made two gold rings for it under the molding on two of its sides; [he put these] on opposite sides of it to be holders for the poles to carry it with.
02Ex 37:28 He made the poles of acacia wood and overlaid them with gold.
02Ex 37:29 He also made the holy anointing oil and the pure, fragrant, and expertly blended incense.
02Ex 38:1 Bezalel constructed the altar of burnt offering from acacia wood. It was square, seven and a half feet long and seven and a half feet wide, and was four and a half feet high.
02Ex 38:2 He made horns for it on its four corners; the horns were of one piece. Then he overlaid it with bronze.
02Ex 38:3 He made all the altar's utensils: the pots, shovels, basins, meat forks, and firepans; he made all its utensils of bronze.
02Ex 38:4 He constructed for the altar a grate of bronze mesh under its ledge, halfway up from the bottom.
02Ex 38:5 At the four corners of the bronze grate he cast four rings as holders for the poles.
02Ex 38:6 He also made the poles of acacia wood and overlaid them with bronze.
02Ex 38:7 Then he inserted the poles into the rings on the sides of the altar in order to carry it with them. He constructed the altar with boards so that it was hollow.
02Ex 38:8 He made the bronze basin and its stand from the [bronze] mirrors of the women who served at the entrance to the tent of meeting.
02Ex 38:9 Then he made the courtyard. The hangings on the south side of the courtyard were of finely spun linen, 150 feet in length,
02Ex 38:10 including their 20 posts and 20 bronze bases. The hooks and bands of the posts were silver.
02Ex 38:11 [The hangings] on the north side were also 150 feet in length, including their 20 posts and 20 bronze bases. The hooks and bands of the posts were silver.
02Ex 38:12 The hangings on the west side were 75 feet in length, including their 10 posts and 10 bases. The hooks and bands of the posts were silver.
02Ex 38:13 [The hangings] on the east toward the sunrise were also 75 feet in length.
02Ex 38:14 The hangings on one side [of the gate] were 22 and a half feet, including their three posts and three bases.
02Ex 38:15 It was the same for the other side. The hangings were 22 and a half feet, including their three posts and three bases on both sides of the courtyard gate.
02Ex 38:16 All the hangings around the courtyard were of finely spun linen.
02Ex 38:17 The bases for the posts were bronze; the hooks and bands of the posts were silver; and the plating for the tops of the posts was silver. All the posts of the courtyard were banded with silver.
02Ex 38:18 The screen for the gate of the courtyard was embroidered with blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and finely spun linen. It was 30 feet long, and like the hangings of the courtyard, seven and a half feet high.
02Ex 38:19 It had four posts, including their four bronze bases. Their hooks were silver, and the bands as well as the plating of their tops were silver.
02Ex 38:20 All the tent pegs for the tabernacle and for the surrounding courtyard were bronze.
02Ex 38:21 This is the inventory for the tabernacle, the tabernacle of the testimony, that was recorded at Moses' command. It was the work of the Levites under the direction of Ithamar son of Aaron the priest.
02Ex 38:22 Bezalel son of Uri, son of Hur, of the tribe of Judah, made everything that the LORD commanded Moses.
02Ex 38:23 With him was Oholiab son of Ahisamach, of the tribe of Dan, a gem cutter, a designer, and an embroiderer with blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and fine linen.
02Ex 38:24 All the gold of the presentation offering that was used for the project in all the work on the sanctuary, was 2,193 pounds, according to the sanctuary shekel.
02Ex 38:25 The silver from those of the community who were registered was 7,544 pounds, according to the sanctuary shekel--
02Ex 38:26 two-fifths of an ounce per man, that is, half a shekel according to the sanctuary shekel, from everyone 20 years old or more who had crossed over to the registered group, 603,550 men.
02Ex 38:27 There were 7,500 pounds of silver [used] to cast the bases of the sanctuary and the bases of the veil-- 100 bases from 7,500 pounds, 75 pounds for each base.
02Ex 38:28 With the [remaining] 44 pounds he made the hooks for the posts, overlaid their tops, and supplied bands for them.
02Ex 38:29 The bronze of the presentation offering totaled 5,310 pounds.
02Ex 38:30 He made with it the bases for the entrance to the tent of meeting, the bronze altar and its bronze grate, all the utensils for the altar,
02Ex 38:31 the bases for the surrounding courtyard, the bases for the gate of the courtyard, all the tent pegs for the tabernacle, and all the tent pegs for the surrounding courtyard.
02Ex 39:1 They made specially woven garments for ministry in the sanctuary, and the holy garments for Aaron from the blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:2 Bezalel made the ephod of gold, of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and of finely spun linen.
02Ex 39:3 They hammered out thin sheets of gold, and he cut threads [from them] to interweave with the blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and the fine linen in a skillful design.
02Ex 39:4 They made shoulder pieces for attaching it; it was joined together at its two edges.
02Ex 39:5 The artistically woven waistband that was on the ephod was of one piece with the ephod, according to the same workmanship of gold, of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and of finely spun linen, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:6 Then they mounted the onyx stones surrounded with gold filigree settings, engraved with the names of Israel's sons as a gem cutter engraves a seal.
02Ex 39:7 He fastened them on the shoulder pieces of the ephod as memorial stones for the Israelites, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:8 He also made the embroidered breastpiece with the same workmanship as the ephod of gold, of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and of finely spun linen.
02Ex 39:9 They made the breastpiece square and folded double, nine inches long and nine inches wide.
02Ex 39:10 They mounted four rows of gemstones on it. The first row was a row of carnelian, topaz, and emerald;
02Ex 39:11 the second row, a turquoise, a sapphire, and a diamond;
02Ex 39:12 the third row, a jacinth, an agate, and an amethyst;
02Ex 39:13 and the fourth row, a beryl, an onyx, and a jasper. They were surrounded with gold filigree in their settings.
02Ex 39:14 The 12 stones corresponded to the names of Israel's sons. Each stone was engraved like a seal with one of the names of the 12 tribes.
02Ex 39:15 They made braided chains of pure gold cord for the breastpiece.
02Ex 39:16 They also fashioned two gold filigree settings and two gold rings and attached the two rings to its two corners.
02Ex 39:17 Then they attached the two gold cords to the two gold rings on the corners of the breastpiece.
02Ex 39:18 They attached the other ends of the two cords to the two filigree settings and, in this way, attached [them] to the ephod's shoulder pieces in front.
02Ex 39:19 They made two [other] gold rings and put [them] at the two other corners of the breastpiece on the edge that is next to the inner border of the ephod.
02Ex 39:20 They made two [more] gold rings and attached them to the bottom of the ephod's two shoulder pieces on its front, close to its seam, above the ephod's woven waistband.
02Ex 39:21 Then they tied the breastpiece from its rings to the rings of the ephod with a cord of blue yarn, so that the breastpiece was above the ephod's waistband and did not come loose from the ephod. [They did] just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:22 They made the woven robe of the ephod entirely of blue yarn.
02Ex 39:23 There was an opening in the center of the robe like that for body armor with a collar around the opening so that it would not tear.
02Ex 39:24 They made pomegranates of finely spun blue, purple, and scarlet yarn on the lower hem of the robe.
02Ex 39:25 They made bells of pure gold and attached the bells between the pomegranates, all around the hem of the robe between the pomegranates,
02Ex 39:26 a bell and a pomegranate alternating all around the lower hem of the robe. It is to be used for ministry, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:27 They made the tunics of fine woven linen for Aaron and his sons.
02Ex 39:28 [They also made] the turban and the ornate headbands of fine linen, the undergarments,
02Ex 39:29 and the sash of finely spun linen of embroidered blue, purple, and scarlet yarn. [They did] just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:30 They also made a plate, the holy diadem, out of pure gold, and wrote on it an inscription like the engraving on a seal: HOLY TO THE LORD
02Ex 39:31 Then they attached a cord of blue yarn to it in order to mount [it] on the turban, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:32 So all the work for the tabernacle, the tent of meeting, was finished. The Israelites did everything just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:33 Then they brought the tabernacle to Moses: the tent with all its furnishings, its clasps, its planks, its crossbars, and its posts and bases;
02Ex 39:34 the covering of ram skins dyed red and the covering of manatee skins; the veil for the screen;
02Ex 39:35 the ark of the testimony with its poles and the mercy seat;
02Ex 39:36 the table, all its utensils, and the bread of the Presence;
02Ex 39:37 the pure [gold] lampstand, with its lamps arranged and all its utensils, as well as the oil for the light;
02Ex 39:38 the gold altar; the anointing oil; the fragrant incense; the screen for the entrance to the tent;
02Ex 39:39 the bronze altar with its bronze grate, its poles, and all its utensils; the basin with its stand;
02Ex 39:40 the hangings of the courtyard, its posts and bases, the screen for the gate of the courtyard, its ropes and tent pegs, and all the equipment for the service of the tabernacle, the tent of meeting;
02Ex 39:41 and the specially woven garments for ministering in the sanctuary, the holy garments for Aaron the priest and the garments for his sons to serve as priests.
02Ex 39:42 The Israelites had done all the work according to everything the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 39:43 Moses inspected all the work they had accomplished. They had done just as the LORD commanded. Then Moses blessed them.
02Ex 40:1 The LORD spoke to Moses:
02Ex 40:2 "You are to set up the tabernacle, the tent of meeting, on the first day of the first month.
02Ex 40:3 Put the ark of the testimony there, and screen off the ark with the veil.
02Ex 40:4 Then bring in the table and lay out its arrangement; also bring in the lampstand and set up its lamps.
02Ex 40:5 Place the gold altar for incense in front of the ark of the testimony. Put up the screen for the entrance to the tabernacle.
02Ex 40:6 Position the altar of burnt offering in front of the entrance to the tabernacle, the tent of meeting.
02Ex 40:7 Place the basin between the tent of meeting and the altar, and put water in it.
02Ex 40:8 Assemble the surrounding courtyard and hang the screen for the gate of the courtyard.
02Ex 40:9 "Take the anointing oil, and anoint the tabernacle and everything in it; consecrate it along with all its furnishings so that it will be holy.
02Ex 40:10 Anoint the altar of burnt offering and all its utensils; consecrate the altar so that it will be especially holy.
02Ex 40:11 Anoint the basin and its stand, and consecrate it.
02Ex 40:12 "Then bring Aaron and his sons to the entrance to the tent of meeting and wash them with water.
02Ex 40:13 Clothe Aaron with the holy garments, anoint him, and consecrate him, so that he can serve Me as a priest.
02Ex 40:14 Have his sons come forward and clothe them in tunics.
02Ex 40:15 Anoint them just as you anointed their father, so that they may also serve Me as priests. Their anointing will serve to inaugurate a permanent priesthood for them throughout their generations."
02Ex 40:16 Moses did everything just as the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 40:17 The tabernacle was set up in the first month of the second year, on the first [day] of the month.
02Ex 40:18 Moses set up the tabernacle: he laid its bases, positioned its planks, inserted its crossbars, and set up its posts.
02Ex 40:19 Then he spread the tent over the tabernacle and put the covering of the tent on top of it, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 40:20 Moses took the testimony and placed [it] in the ark, and attached the poles to the ark. He set the mercy seat on top of the ark.
02Ex 40:21 He brought the ark into the tabernacle, put up the veil for the screen, and screened off the ark of the testimony, just as the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 40:22 Moses placed the table in the tent of meeting on the north side of the tabernacle, outside the veil.
02Ex 40:23 He arranged the bread on it before the LORD, just as the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 40:24 He also put the lampstand in the tent of meeting opposite the table on the south side of the tabernacle
02Ex 40:25 and set up the lamps before the LORD, just as the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 40:26 Moses also installed the gold altar in the tent of meeting, in front of the veil,
02Ex 40:27 and burned fragrant incense on it, just as the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 40:28 He put up the screen at the entrance to the tabernacle.
02Ex 40:29 Then he placed the altar of burnt offering at the entrance to the tabernacle, the tent of meeting, and offered the burnt offering and the grain offering on it, just as the LORD had commanded him.
02Ex 40:30 He set the basin between the tent of meeting and the altar and put water in it for washing.
02Ex 40:31 Moses, Aaron, and his sons washed their hands and feet from it.
02Ex 40:32 They washed whenever they came to the tent of meeting and approached the altar, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.
02Ex 40:33 Next Moses set up the surrounding courtyard for the tabernacle and the altar and hung a screen for the gate of the courtyard. So Moses finished the work.
02Ex 40:34 The cloud covered the tent of meeting, and the glory of the LORD filled the tabernacle.
02Ex 40:35 Moses was unable to enter the tent of meeting because the cloud rested on it, and the glory of the LORD filled the tabernacle.
02Ex 40:36 The Israelites set out whenever the cloud was taken up from the tabernacle throughout all the stages of their journey.
02Ex 40:37 If the cloud was not taken up, they did not set out until the day it was taken up.
02Ex 40:38 For the cloud of the LORD was over the tabernacle by day, and there was a fire inside the cloud by night, visible to the entire house of Israel throughout all the stages of their journey.
